<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DroughtOdds Bjt   08-19 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Odds, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Odds on Ending Drought a Bad Bet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The odds the government is putting on an end
to the drought over the next couple of months would likely be of
little interest to even the most dedicated riverboat gambler.
   The probability of getting enough rain to end the drought ranges
``from 1 in 500 for central Iowa to 1 in 1,000'' for at least three
other major drought regions, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration reports.
   And, looking back at history, even that may be optimistic.
   That's because never in the period that records have been kept
has rainfall in August, September and October in major
drought-plagued areas been enough to end a shortage equivalent to
today's.
   In this week's drought advisory, the National Climatic Data
Center takes a look at four specific drought areas, and what it
finds isn't encouraging.
   In central Iowa, for example, the amount of rain needed by Oct.
31 to end the drought totals 22.42 inches. That amount can be
expected in the August-October period only once in 500 years, the
advisory said.
   Richard Heim, a meteorologist at the Asheville, N.C., data
center, said those were the best odds found in the four areas
studied _ the other three all came out to one chance in 1,000 of
getting enough rain by the end of October to declare the drought
broken.
   Those areas are northeastern Montana, near the North Dakota
border, where 10.36 inches of rain would be needed to end the
drought; the east slope of the Cascades in Washington, where 13.21
inches would be needed, and Tennessee, which would require 21.98
inches by Oct. 31, Heim said.
   Only once in 1,000 years can those regions expect that much rain
in the months of August, September and October, he said.
   ``In no prior year,'' going back to 1895, did any of the four
studied regions receive as much rain as they now need in the
three-month period, according to records kept by the center.
   The calculations are based on the detailed Palmer Drought Index,
a system developed to allow scientists to measure shortages of
moisture over the long term.
   The system compares water available from precipitation and from
stored soil moisture with water used by plants, evaporation,
runoff, people and to recharge lakes, reservoirs and dry soil. If
incoming and outgoing water balance, the reading is zero.
   An index reading of minus 4 is termed severe drought, and the
drought is considered to have ended when the Palmer reading gets
back up to minus 0.5, since that is nearly a balance and indicates
that much of the soil moisture has been replenished.
   Severe drought continues to afflict large areas of the nation
despite some recent rains which provided short-term moisture, but
did little to recharge depleted ground water supplies or to improve
the conditions of many rivers and lakes. Palmer Drought Index
readings range as high as minus 7 and minus 8 in some areas.
   In addition to soil moisture problems, restoring normal river
and stream conditions in some regions could take years.
   ``Two to three years of above normal winter precipitation over
the mountainous headwaters of the basin followed by above normal
snowpack runoff for each of the years'' is needed to get the
Missouri River basin back to normal, the National Weather Service
hydrologic office reported.
   For California, the hydrologic office reports, ``one year of
normal winter precipitation followed by normal spring snowpack
runoff'' would do the job.
   The Ohio and lower Mississippi river basins, the agency says,
could be restored to normal flows by ``a series of major low
pressure systems producing at least 8-12 inches of rain over much
of the Ohio River Basin over a two-four week period.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
