<1ST_LINE>r a PM-US-Pakistan     08-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Pakistan,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Praises Pakistani Government's Steps Toward
Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is
applauding ``continuing steps toward democracy'' in Pakistan and
sending Secretary of State George Shultz as the chief U.S. mourner
at the funeral of President Zia ul-Haq.
   President Reagan, vacationing at his ranch north of here,
announced the makeup of the funeral delegation Thursday.
   At the same time, acting with unusual speed for a diplomatic
appointment, he announced that he will nominate veteran foreign
service officer Robert B. Oakley to succeed Arnold Raphel as
ambassador to Pakistan.
   Zia and Raphel were killed Wednesday in an airplane crash near
Lahore, Pakistan. Gen. Herbert M. Wassom, the chief U.S. military
representative in Pakistan, also was among the 37 people who
perished in the crash.
   In Washington, the State Department declined to speculate about
the cause of the crash.
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Dan Howard announced the dispatch of
a team of eight U.S. accident investigators to Pakistan.
   A team of six U.S. military forensic specialists also was being
sent from West Germany to assist the Pakistanis in identifying the
crash victims, Howard said.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley, the wife of the new
ambassador-designate, said that Acting President Ghulam Ishak Khan
had reaffirmed Pakistan's pro-United States foreign policy and she
praised the nation's ``continuing steps toward democracy.''
   She applauded Ishaf Khan's indication that elections would be
held in mid-November, as scheduled by Zia, saying, ``These are
sound first steps ... a welcome sign.''
   Oakley, 57, the prospective ambassador, previously has served as
ambassador to Somalia and Zaire and headed the State Department's
Office for Combatting Terrorism. At present, he is senior director
of Middle East, South Asia and North Africa affairs for the
National Security Council.
   He will accompany Shultz to Zia's funeral Saturday in Islamabad.
Others in the delegation will include Undersecretary of State
Michael Armacost, State Department Country Director Robert Flatten
and Army Maj. Gen. Robert Jones, who will represent the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
   Congressional members of the delegation will include Rep. John
Murtha, D-Pa., Rep. Bill McCollum Jr., R-Fla., and Rep. Charles
Wilson, D-Texas.
   The White House said the president placed telephone calls
Thursday to Nancy Ely-Raphel, the ambassador's widow; Sara Raphel,
his mother, and Judy Wasson, the general's widow.
   ``The president is expressing condolences and sympathy on behalf
of the nation,'' said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater also said that the president and his wife, Nancy,
along with Vice President George Bush and his wife, Barbara, had
sent messages of condolence to the Zia family.
   Reagan and Bush also sent messages to Ishaq Khan, Fitzwater
said. Reagan told the acting president, ``Let us all rededicate
ourselves to the task of regional peace and reconstruction to which
President Zia dedicated his life. As you carry out your heavy
responsibilities in his absence, please count on the United States
for support.''
</TEXT>
