<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     08-19 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>There's Help For Small Agriculture Firms That Want To Export
Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small agriculture operators who want a piece
of the action in farm exports can get help from the Agriculture
Department's Foreign Agricultural Service, the department says.
   It's a tricky game to compete with the corporate giants, said
Dugger Harris, coordinator of the minority and small business
program for FAS.
   The agency has a formal agreement with the Small Business
Administration to include small and minority-owned companies in
USDA's export market development programs.
   Most of the assistance offered under the programs is free or
available at nominal costs. Harris said his office is providing
services to about 250 companies and is looking for more.
   ``We want small and minority-owned businesses to know that we
will make available to them the same services the FAS provides to
large exporting businesses,'' he said.
   Harris described the program in the forthcoming September issue
of Foreign Agriculture magazine, a monthly publication of the USDA
agency.
   One of the best ways FAS can help small businesses gain a
foothold in exporting is through participation in international
trade fairs and the business contacts that can be made through
them, he said.
   There is a large demand for the limited exhibit space at trade
fairs, but Harris said FAS has reserved 10 percent of the U.S.
space for small and minority-owned businesses.
   Participation fees are covered by the agency and the Small
Business Administration for those small and minority companies that
are selected to exhibit at the overseas fairs. However, the
companies must bear the costs of travel, lodging and other expenses.
   A firm can qualify for consideration if it has an annual gross
income of $5 million or less and not more than 25 full-time
employees.
   Jerry Ravenell, president of Low Country International Inc. of
Washington, D.C. and Mount Pleasant, S.C., was cited as an example
of how the program works. The company provides export services to
small- and medium-size U.S. companies, ranging from crating and
shipping to serving as overseas agents for U.S. food products.
   Ravenell began four years ago, working with FAS and Small
Business Administration programs, and now ``is gaining a reputation
as a knowledgeable and experienced exporting enterprise,'' the
report said.
   Another example involves beef jerky made by the Apache Meat
Processing Co., Apache, Okla., owned by Robert Rowell, a Kiowa
Indian. Like Ravenell, Rowell also exhibited at a 1984 food trade
show in London. His beef jerky attracted so much attention that
Rowell received an order from Harrod's, the famous London
department store.
   For six months, he supplied Harrod's with beef jerky made with a
special patented sauce.
   Rowell even got a National Minority Business Person of the Year
Award from President Reagan. Unfortunately, Rowell's dream ran
afoul of British suspicion of the water in Oklahoma.
   ``While my jerky met with U.S. government health guidelines, the
English analyzed it and decided that Oklahoma's water, which is
used in making the jerky, wasn't as pure as they would like,''
Rowell said.
   But the report added that Rowell is installing a water
chlorinator at his processing plant and is hoping to get back into
the British jerky market. The Japanese also ``are showing interest
in our dried beef products,'' he said.
   The report said people interested in the USDA program can
contact: Dugger Harris, Coordinator, Minority and Small Business
Programs, High Value Products Division, Foreign Agricultural
Service, Room 4639-South Building, Washington, D.C. 20250-1000.
Phone 202 475-3417.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has been given the go-ahead by the
Agriculture Department to buy an additional 2 million metric tons
of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said Thursday the
wheat will be sold to China at competitive world prices under the
department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Under various authorizations, or initiatives, since Jan. 26,
1987, China has bought about 7 million tons of U.S. wheat under the
program. The previous authorization was for 2 million tons on April
5, of which only 10,000 tons remain for use, which is added to the
latest authorization.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Under EEP arrangements, exporters can sell U.S. commodities at
reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   The Soviet Union also has been a big buyer of U.S. wheat under
EEP, with purchases totaling about 13 million tons since April 30,
1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 355 million bushels of surplus feed
grains owned by the Agriculture Department have been set aside as a
reserve to meet potential demand for emergency livestock use under
the recently passed $3.9 billion Drought Assistance Act.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said Thursday the grains are
owned by the department's Commodity Credit Corp. and are being held
in warehouses in 40 states. The grains include 250.4 million
bushels of corn, 79.7 million bushels of sorghum, and 25 million
bushels of barley.
   Myers said additional stocks of CCC feed grains can be made
available if demand from eligible farmers proves greater than
current projections.
   The drought relief measure was signed by President Reagan on
Aug. 11. Myers said final rules as to eligibility requirements for
the grain will be issued in the near future. The program will be
carried out by county offices of the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service.
</TEXT>
