<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeatRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0793 08-19 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0793,0858</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Taking Its Toll Nationwide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE temperature readings, note that
some areas got relief from the heat, picking up 5th graf pvs, `A
75-year-old ....' INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs, `Boston
Housing ...,' with reports from more states.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNE BUCKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing authorities in Boston on Thursday investigated the
deaths of five elderly people, the homeless in Tennessee sought
shelter from the swelter and New York City's mayor decided water
troughs make good horse sense.
   Things weren't much better in other parts of the country as the
nation sweats through one of the hottest summers on record, but
rain and lower temperatures helped a rural community in western
Pennsylvania save its water supply for now.
   At Fort Bragg and Pope Air Force Base in North Carolina, the
mercury climbed to 106 degrees Thursday, the highest reading in the
steamy state. Raleigh tied its all-time high of July 23, 1952, as
the mercury climbed to 105 degrees, the National Weather Service
said.
   Also setting heat records for the date were Charlotte, N.C.,
where 101 degrees broke a 1956 record of 99, and Lynchburg, Va.,
where 98 broke a 97-degree mark set in 1914.
   But a front stretching central Iowa across the Ohio Valley and
into the Appalachians brought relief _ and thunderstorms _ to many
cities north of it, with temperatures in the 70s.
   A 75-year-old Boston woman died of heart failure Monday,
bringing to five the number of residents at a housing project who
have died during 10 days of high temperatures. Four of the
residents lived on the same floor.
   The woman earlier became ill in her room on the top floor of the
eight-story building. Three other top-floor residents and a man who
lived on the floor below have died since Aug. 4, a period in which
temperatures soared into the 90s.
   ``It's quite obvious someone has to look at it and see why that
floor must have been so hot,'' said Massachusetts Medical Examiner
Bryan Blackbourne.
   Boston Housing Authority officials Thursday found all systems
functional at the 18-year-old building, said spokesman Bill Wright.
The 12 exhaust fans on the roof were working, and temperatures in
the halls on each floor were only a few degrees apart, he said.
   The heat in Kentucky, where it reached 103 degrees in Paducah,
breaking the 1954 mark of 102, forced some school systems to put
off the start of classes.
   ``I think the heat index (measuring the combined effects of heat
and humidity) is hotter than I can ever remember it,'' said Darvin
Estes, school superintendent in Bath County, where opening day was
postponed from Wednesday to Monday.
   Southern Illinois also remained in the heat wave's grip as the
northern part of the state got relief from a cold front that
brought thunderstorms and hail. By 2 p.m., Peoria reported the
mercury had soared to 101 degrees; in contrast, Chicago had a
relatively mild 85 degrees.
   Two homeless shelters in Nashville, Tenn., where temperatures
hovered around 100 degrees all week, stayed open all day to provide
a cool spot.
   ``It's a terrible problem. There's really nowhere for these
people to go,'' said Winnie McKenzie, director of St. Patrick's
Shelter. ``I've been keeping our people in during the day. I can't
put them out with babies and all.''
   The Nashville Union Rescue Mission also opened its
air-conditioned chapel during the day.
   In New York City, the collapse earlier this week of a carriage
horse working in 90-degree-plus weather created a public furor and
prompted Mayor Edward I. Koch to announce some changes.
   Koch said Thursday the city will provide more watering holes in
Central Park, move a horse ambulance there and provide shade in hot
weather. He also called for review of a regulation that requires
horses to return to the stable when the temperature hits 90 degrees.
   The changes, he said ``make good old-fashioned horse sense.''
   Rain and lower temperatures enabled Tidioute, Pa., to save its
public water supply.
   ``We don't know how long it's going to last. Another hot day and
we'll be right back where we were,'' said Karen Bajorek, borough
secretary.
   Workers installed a pump to draw water from a well that was
drilled in 1985 but left unused because of high concentrations of
minerals, including iron that leaves rust-colored stains and sodium
that has been linked to high blood pressure.
   ``So people on a no-salt diet will not be able to drink it, and
because of the high iron content, it might stain their sinks and
their clothes,'' Ms. Bajorek said.
   Despite the misery, some people have come up with creative ways
of beating the heat.
   H.M. Hines, who owns Home Ice and Coal Co. in Raleigh, said it
was hot enough that some people had asked him to dump blocks of ice
into their swimming pools.
   ``But it's not a good idea,'' Hines said.``Somebody jumps in and
hits that 300-pound block of ice, it's dangerous.''
</TEXT>
