<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TexasAir     08-19 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Air,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Accuses United, American of Illegal Acts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. has accused American and
United airlines of gaining hundreds of millions of dollars through
illegal use of their reservations systems.
   Texas Air, the nation's largest airline group, charged in a
complaint filed Thursday with the Department of Transportation that
United and American were deliberately misleading travel agents
using their computerized reservations systems.
   By giving agents unreliable information about rivals' flights,
American and United have discouraged the agents from booking
passengers on airlines other than theirs, the complaint said.
   ``This is the first time anyone has documented how American and
United use the power of technology to pick the pockets of
consumers,'' said Bill Diffenderffer, vice president and general
counsel of System One, which runs Texas Air's computerized
reservations system.
   The complaint was made in the names of System One and Texas
Air's two main carriers, Continental and Eastern.
   American and United both denied the charges, saying past
attempts by Texas Air to challenge the legality of their
computerized reservations systems had failed.
   ``This effort by Texas Air is unworthy of serious attention,''
said Charles Novak, a United spokesman in Chicago. He said Texas
Air had been unsuccessful in past lawsuits against the United
computerized reservations system.
   Novak accused Texas Air of trying to ``use the courts, the
Congress and federal agencies ... to gain for itself business that
(United) has secured through hard work, large investments and
innovation.''
   Jim Brown, an American spokesman, said Texas Air's charges were
without foundation.
   The inch-thick Texas Air complaint said United's computerized
reservations system, called Apollo, and American's, known as Sabre,
are supposed to allow travel agents to make seat reservations and
issue boarding passes reliably for flights on other airlines.
   Instead, Sabre and Apollo are designed deliberately not to
provide consistently reliable information about other carriers, the
Texas Air complaint said. Because of the unreliability, travel
agents are discouraged from booking flights on airlines other than
American and United, Texas Air contended.
   The Houston-based Texas Air claimed United and American had
violated Section 411 of the Federal Aviation Act, which prohibits
unfair or deceptive methods of airline competition.
   The complaint includes a copy of what Texas Air called an
internal American memo dated July 15, 1980, expressing concern that
United's Sabre system might be giving United an edge.
   The memo says that if American can determine that United's
computerized system gives it ``greater market preferences'' than
does American's system, ``either through conscious bias or by
making it inconvenient to book carriers other than United, we must
find a way to skew the usage rates of Sabre in similar ways.''
   The complaint also accused United and American of preventing
travel agents from obtaining competing computerized reservations
systems, such as Texas Air's System One.
   Texas Air contends in a 20-city survey included in the complaint
that American's system diverted to American $7.1 million in
additional passenger revenue from flights serving Los Angeles in
May 1988. Similarly, United diverted $8.7 million on the same
routes in that period, the complaint alleges.
   It said such diversions had totaled hundreds of millions of
dollars in recent years, but it gave no exact figures.
</TEXT>
