<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Quayle-Delegates 2ndLd-Writethru a0864 08-19 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Delegates, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0864,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates Abuzz Over Quayle's Military Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 4-5 with Bentley tempering criticism, ``Bentley at
xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican delegates fretted Thursday over
Dan Quayle's decision to join the National Guard when the Vietnam
war was raging, but many shrugged it off and some groused about a
news media ``witch hunt.''
   Several said they would have done the same themselves had they
been eligible for the military draft during the conflict. National
Guard units were rarely activated for Vietnam duty.
   Rep. Helen Delich Bentley of Maryland said, ``I don't like the
sound of it,'' She said Quayle, George Bush's choice as a running
mate, had denied Wednesday that anyone used influence to help him
get into the Guard in 1969.
   Bentley at first suggested that Quayle had only two choices:
either admit ``he was a liar or he can withdraw from the race.''
But later she backed off, saying the issue was ``dead'' and had
been based on ``inaccurate news reports.''
   Rep. Bob Dornan, a staunch conservative and co-chairman of the
Bush campaign in California, said, ``It requires a Checkers-like
speech, and he must do _ must do it _ quickly, before this gets out
of hand.''
   George Walker Bush Jr., the vice president's eldest son, called
the flap ``ridiculous'' and said he joined the National Guard, too,
in 1968.
   ``It was available and I went,'' said Bush, 42, who was a pilot
in the Guard. ``I thought it was service to my country and I'm
proud of my time in the National Guard.'
   Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch said, ``If Dan can withstand the next two
weeks, which will be brutal, he'll be vice president of the United
States.''
   ``What's the big deal?' said Sen. Gordon Humphrey of New
Hampshire. ``He pulled some strings to serve his country. He could
have gone to Canada.''
   The questions through the state delegation meetings Thursday
morning, hours before the climactic night of the Republican
National Convention.
   Samuel Atkins, 43, a Watkinsville, Ga., lawyer, said the ``baby
boomers will understand, but the older generation may hold it
against him.''
   Gordon Pederson of Wall, S.D., a retired U.S. Army lieutenant
colonel, said: ``I was in three wars and a riot and see nothing
wrong with that. It was just a legal option. ... It just burns me
up because somebody is looking for headlines.''
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Navy fighter pilot who spent 5{
years in a Hanoi prison, said, ``Service in the National Guard is
an honorable profession.''
   ``If, however, there is clear evidence that the process may have
been manipulated to give some kind of special preference, then I
think it's a problem ... that needs to be resolved,'' he said.
   T.J. Bailey of Bailey, Ore., the state GOP chairman and a
Vietnam veteran, said: ``I truly do not resent Dan Quayle for not
having gone. It is a way a number of my lifelong friends opted. We
have to examine the sanity and wisdom of people who resent him for
not being shot at.''
   Noble Cody, a businessman from Cookeville, Tenn., said: ``If I
had a son that age and knowing what I do now about that war, I'd do
everything I could to keep him out of it.''
   Bob Naylor, the California state GOP chairman and a Vietnam
veteran, said Quayle did what ``anyone in his position would do at
that time.''
   Delegate Tom Adam of Pierre, S.D., said, ``I think that's just a
witch hunt.''
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. Jerry Curry, a congressional candidate
from Virginia Beach, Va., who served two tours in Vietnam, said,
``The idea that anybody who serves in the National Guard or
Reserves should be called a draft dodger because their unit did not
get activated and sent off to war is disgusting.''
   Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska said Quayle should ``get his uniform
pictures and put them out everywhere. It's a plus, not a negative.''
   Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt said suggesting that joining the National
Guard ``was almost the same as going to Canada'' made him ``the
fightingest mad that I've been in a long time.''
   Jerry Prevo of Anchorage, chairman of the Alaska delegation,
said, ``People make mistakes when they're young.''
   Tom Cole, chairman of the Oklahoma Republican Party, called it
``Quayle-bashing. I think it's kind of a cheap shot and a low
blow.''
</TEXT>
