<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 5thLd-Writethru a0929 08-19 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0929,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>North, South Korean Delegates Meet at Panmunjom</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs with talks over for day, more scheduled
Saturday. Pick up 2nd pvs, `The talks...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates of South Korea and North Korea
met Friday for the first time in more than 2{ years to discuss
easing their bitter 40-year rivalry, but they disagreed on the
North's demand to be a co-host of the Summer Olympics.
   The two sides adjourned without reaching any agreement after
talking for almost three hours on the format and agenda for
full-scale parliamentary talks. They agreed to a second meeting
Saturday.
   The talks between five lawmakers from each side opened with
chief North Korean delegate Chon Kum Chol insisting the communist
North act as co-host at the Games and calling for a non-aggression
pact between the two Koreas.
   The Olympics, he said, were a ``serious political problem which
will decide the destiny of the Korean people.''
   Chief South Korean delegate Park Joon-kyu, in his opening
speech, said the only solution was for the North to take part in
the Olympics in Seoul, which begin Sept. 17. He made no reference
to co-hosting the Games with North Korea.
   ``The only way for the two sides to cooperate with each other in
the cause of the 24th Olympiad is for your athletes to take part in
the Seoul Games together with our athletes,'' he told North Korean
delegates.
   The North is demanding to co-host the Olympics to stave off what
might be viewed as a major political defeat. Both sides claim to be
the sole legitimate government of Korea, and the South sees its
selection to host the Olympics as international recognition of its
claim.
   Park said the South would keep the door open until the last
moment for the North to take part, but he noted that the deadline
for entries was Sept. 2.
   ``How regretful it would be if our nation, already suffering
from the division of the homeland, must see even the Olympics cause
a split between Seoul and Pyongyang,'' he said.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics if it is not
allowed to co-host the Games.
   The International Olympic Committee has said repeatedly North
Korean cannot co-host because the Games are awarded to a single
city. South Korean authorities fear the North may use terrorism to
try to disrupt the Olympics.
   The two Koreas, technically still at war, are archenemies with
hundreds of thousands of troops poised along the 150-mile border in
a state of constant tension.
   The two sides have no relations. The border is sealed, and the
two countries maintain no direct transportation or communications
links except for a single hotline.
   The Korean peninsula was divided in 1945 by Soviet and U.S.
forces that ended the Japanese occupation at the end of World War
II. Separate republics were declared in 1948. North Korea invaded
the South in 1950, beginning the Korean War that ended in stalemate
three years later.
   The South has evolved into a major economic power and started to
move toward full democracy. The North has remained one of the most
isolated and authoritarian nations in the world.
   Friday's meeting at the truce city in Panmunjom represented the
first meeting between the two sides since the last peace talks
collapsed in January 1986.
   All the North Korean delegates at Friday's sesssion were drawn
from the official rubber-stamp Supreme Peoples' Assembly. The South
Korean delegation consisted of two government party members of the
National Assembly and a legislator from each of the three main
opposition parties.
   While stressing the importance of the Olympics, the North Korean
delegation placed it second on its list of priorities, putting the
need for a non-aggression pact first.
   South Korean observers said it could be a sign the North
realized it could not co-host the Olympics and was already looking
beyond the Games.
   The two sides also remained far apart on the agenda for later
full-scale talks. North Korea wants to discuss a non-aggression
pact and the Olympics. The South said it wants much broader talks
covering a range of social, political, and economic issues.
   The North also continued to insist on participation of the full
parliaments of both sides, in addition to representatives of social
and cultural groups.
   South Korea insisted on smaller delegations.
   Chon said the first full-scale meeting should be held Aug. 26 in
the North Korean capital of Pyongyang. He said any final agreement
would be put to a vote of the two assemblies.
</TEXT>
