<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Quayle-Guard 5thLd-Writethru a0903-a0887 08-19
1116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Guard, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0903-a0887,1,050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Swamped In Controversy Over National Guard Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 10th graf to update with Bentley backing off,
``She backed xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even as he became the Republican vice
presidential nominee Thursday, Dan Quayle was mired in controversy
after it was disclosed that a family connection helped him join the
National Guard at the height of the Vietnam War.
   Top aides to presidential nominee George Bush met during the day
to discuss ways to quell the furor, as campaign spokeswoman Alixe
Glen declared, ``Not a single thought is being given to changing
the ticket.''
   Criticism heard outside the Superdome was weighed against
delegates' enthusiastic demonstrations inside the hall. Quayle
added several lines to his acceptance speech to make his defiant
stand clear and the crowd erupted in applause.
   ``As a young man, I served six years in the National Guard. And,
like the millions of Americans who have served in the Guard...I am
proud of it,'' Quayle said.
   ``I'm proud to have Dan Quayle at my side,'' Bush told the
delegates as he accepted the top spot on the ticket.
   What should have been a triumphant day for the second-term
Indiana senator was instead full of hurried meetings and wild
rumors as the story of his military service unfolded.
   Some Republicans suggested Quayle's nomination might have been a
mistake.
   ``I don't like the fact that Quayle denied yesterday that
anybody had interceded on his behalf when apparently someone had,''
said Rep. Helen Bentley, chairman of the Bush campaign in Maryland.
``Quayle can do one of two things: admit this and that he was a
liar _ or he can withdraw from the race.''
   She backed off later, however, saying the issue was ``dead'' and
based on ``inaccurate news reports.''
   Rep. Tom Tauke of Iowa voiced similar views: ``If appropriate
information was sought and appropriate information wasn't
forthcoming, then if I were George Bush I'd reserve the right to
reconsider.''
   Quayle refused to answer questions about the uproar.
   ``I answered many questions last night,'' Quayle told reporters
as he entered the convention hall. ``I'm going to continue to
answer questions you raise about me, about issues, about anything
through this campaign.
   ``Tonight is George Bush's night. And in deference to George
Bush, I'm not going to get into all the details. I'll be around
tomorrow. I'll be around the next day to answer your questions,''
he added.
   Bush aides met during the day to hash out the campaign's
reaction to the controversy.
   ``We have chased down every single rumor. We haven't been able
to substantiate one single rumor,'' Bush press secretary Sheila
Tate said after a three-hour afternoon meeting.
   Asked if the campaign thought the matter had been put to rest,
Tate said, ``I believe so.''
   Others agreed.
   ``It's ridiculous to talk of dropping him from the ticket over
something like this,'' said Kansas Gov. Mike Hayden, a Vietnam
veteran. ``I know a lot of people whose families made calls to get
them into the Guard or the military. ... Dan Quayle volunteered.''
   The Indiana senator said Wednesday that he didn't know whether
family connections had been used to get him into the National Guard
and that suggestions that he joined to avoid the draft were ``a
cheap shot.'' A day later, he said through a spokesman that calls
``may have been made.''
   The Indianapolis News, a newspaper owned by Quayle's family,
reported Thursday that its former managing editor Wendell C.
Phillippi had interceded with Guard officials on Quayle's behalf.
Phillippi was a former commander of the Indiana National Guard and
worked for Quayle's grandfather at the newspaper. Later Phillippi
said he made only one call on Quayle's behalf.
   ``I did recommend Danny Quayle for the National Guard,''
Phillippi said. ``I just called the military department and said,
`Here's a good man, you ought to take him.' ... It was just as I
have done for many young men over many years. ... I was just a peon
calling the military department. I had no power.''
   There was some disagreement over whether there were long waiting
lists to get into the National Guard in Indiana _ as in other
states.
   John S. Anderson, adjutant general prior to 1969, said one did
exist, but John N. Owens, who followed Anderson in the job, said
Indiana units ``had vacancies galore.''
   Quayle, a hard-liner on defense matters, joined the National
Guard in 1969, when he had graduated from college and thus lost his
student deferment from the draft. Quayle was a private first class
in the Guard, serving as a writer in a public information unit
until 1975.
   Few guard units were activated and sent to Vietnam, and many
young men sought to join the guard to avoid being drafted and sent
to Vietnam. Of the more than 58,000 American casualties in the
Vietnam war, 97 were Guardsmen in mobilized units.
   Phillippi said Quayle inquired as to whether he might be sent to
Vietnam as part of a Guard unit.
   The issue of how he got into the Guard was raised during the
screening process run by the Bush campaign on all possible running
mates, said Bush aide Robert Teeter.
   ``The question was, I believe, was there any pull or some
influence in some way for him to get into the National Guard. My
impression is the answer is absolutely not,'' said Teeter. ``He, at
some point said, `I simply applied, like anyone else.''' said
Teeter.
   While the Bush campaign tried to play down the controversy,
other Republicans said it could be a continuing problem for the GOP
ticket.
   ``Let's face it, the question is whether a rich kid's family got
him into the Guard when other people were getting drafted,'' said
John DeCamp, a Vietnam veteran and Republican delegate. ``Some of
them like me got shot at a lot and a great many of them just plain
got shot and killed.''
   Ed Rollins, former campaign manager for Ronald Reagan, said if
Quayle misled the campaign, Bush would have ``a right to withdraw
the nomination. You cut your losses and do not bleed to death.''
   Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming said questions about Quayle's
military service were ``a bunch of crap. There are about 10 million
people in the National Guard who should be offended by all of
this.''
   But Rep. Bob Dornan of California, a hard-line conservative and
longtime Bush supporter, said Quayle must explain himself, much as
Richard Nixon did in 1952 to defuse reports of financial
impropriety.
   ``It requires a Checkers-like speech, and he must do it _ must
do it _ quickly, before this gets out of hand,'' Dornan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
