<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-19 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sure, there's the thrill of the presidential
race or the upcoming Olympics. But there's nothing quite like
cheering on thousands of rubber duckies, say devotees of an unusual
competition.
   About 15,000 of the fake fowl are expected to compete in a
charity race on the Illinois River on Sunday. People will pay $5 to
adopt a duckie in hopes that the tiny toy wearing their number will
win them an island vacation.
   ``It's awesome,'' said Myrna Parker, executive secretary of the
Alberta Heart and Stroke Foundation in Calgary, which rents its
150,000 ducks to other charitable groups. ``It's a sea of yellow.
Everyone yells at their duckies, they give them names.''
   ``They're like the ones you play with in the bathtub. They're
just adorable,'' added Darla Lane, a promotions assistant at Tulsa
radio station KTFX. The station is co-sponsoring the Oklahoma race
with the United Cerebral Palsy group of Oklahoma.
   The Canadian foundation borrowed the fund-raising idea from a
group in Ireland and launched a massive Labor Day race last year
featuring 47,000 rubber duckies. The Canadian group purchased
150,000 ducks and now leases the little birds for fund-raising
races elsewhere.
   ``They're booked right into 1990,'' Ms. Parker said.
   The Oklahoma race, featuring 15,000 rubber duckies traveling
three-fifths of a mile, has a goal of raising at least $30,000,
said Jana Linn, director of development with the state Cerebral
Palsy organization.
   The person sponsoring the winning duckie will win a trip to the
Bahamas, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN MATEO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret McMillan figures she might not
have been on hand to win a beauty pageant had she not given up
smoking _ sometime after World War I.
   The 104-year-old resident of a San Mateo convalescent home
topped a field of 10 spry contestants Thursday to win the annual
``My Fair Lady'' competition, beating out women who weren't even
born until the 20th century.
   ``I feel lucky,'' said Mrs. McMillan after being crowned at the
San Mateo County Fair. She won a tiara, a trophy, roses, gift
certificates from local stores and boxes of candy.
   Contestants were judged on poise, wit, personality, appearance
and their answers to questions about significant moments in their
lives and what they would do if they won $1 million.
   Asked beforehand her secret of longevity, Mrs. McMillan credited
``coming from good stock, luck, having a nip _ bourbon and water _
now and then, and not smoking. I did smoke at the beginning of my
life, but quit between World War I and World War II.''
   The My Fair Lady contest is open to wheelchair-using women
residents, age 80 and older, of convalescent hospitals in the San
Francisco Bay area.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most beach-goers aim for that smooth,
even tan, but some people are proud of spottier efforts.
   Categories at Thursday's Miscellaneous Sun Tanning Tournament in
this beach resort included the T-shirt tan, the ``Golden Dome''
award for bald-headed bronzing, and the ``Count Dracula'' division
for those who eschew the sun altogether.
   But those and other humorous categories _ including the
best-tanned back of the neck and the best-tanned soles of the feet
_ were tempered with warnings about the less-than-sunny risks of
tanning.
   ``It's going out of style to bake yourself to a crisp,'' said
Ocean City publicist Mark Soifer. ``Sunscreen products were given
out, and we kept repeating that people should be very careful and
not overdo it in the sun.''
   The one winner who did not have to worry about the sun was
Tinelle Attig of Egg Harbor City, who won the ``Count Dracula''
division for being the palest person on the beach.
   ``I asked what she did to get her tan and she said, `Nothing,'''
Soifer said.
   The judges included a local beauty queen, a representative from
Coppertone sun products and the city's recreation director, Soifer
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
