<TEXT>
   ,0177
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs
^Hal M. Freeman</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hal M. Freeman, who resigned his post as
Western regional manager of the federal Office of Civil Rights in
protest of Reagan administration policy on AIDS victims, died at
age 52.
   Freeman stepped down from the office February 20, 1986, because
the Department of Health and Human Services had refused to apply
the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 to AIDS patients.
   The publicity resulting from the resignation caused a
congressional inquiry and a change of policy. Freeman subsequently
went into practice in San Francisco as a psychotherapist.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Rufus C. Harris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rufus C. Harris, former president of Tulane
and Mercer Universities, died Thursday at 91.
   Harris was president of Tulane from 1937 to 1960, and led the
Baptist-affiliated Mercer, which has campuses in Macon and Atlanta,
from 1960 to 1980. That year the position of chancellor was created
for him, and he held it until he died.
   Harris persuaded Mercer's trustees to integrate the Mercer
student body in 1963.
</TEXT>
