<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN-VeepEmbarrassments     08-19 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN-Veep Embarrassments,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than Once No. 2 Has Made No. 1 Blush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential nominees probably would prefer
to run without having to share the ticket. Running mates can be
such a burden sometimes.
   George Bush's day of acceptance, dulled by the questions that
surfaced about how Sen. Dan Quayle joined the National Guard in
1969, is only the latest problem to attach to a party's ticket.
   But usually it takes a little longer.
   After Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower chose young California senator
Richard Nixon to run with him in 1952, the campaign was roiled by
reports that a ``slush fund'' had been set up for him in California.
   As the issue festered, it seemed Eisenhower would drop his
running mate, but Nixon regained public support with a broadcast
speech in which he denied the implications. He said everything he
owned could be stripped from his family, except their dog,
Checkers. The address became known as ``The Checkers speech.''
   It was Nixon's turn next to be embarrassed by his running mate.
In 1968, after choosing little known Maryland Gov. Spiro Agnew, the
campaign was rocked by Agnew's greeting a reporter on the campaign
as a ``fat Jap.''
   Agnew insisted that he had meant no offense to the reporter,
with whom he had been friends, and the issue went away.
   In 1972, the Democratic convention chose Sen. George McGovern of
South Dakota to run for president and Sen. Thomas Eagleton of
Missouri to share the ticket.
   Ten days later, Eagleton disclosed he had voluntarily entered
hospitals three times between 1960 and 1966 for ``nervous
exhaustion and fatigue.'' Although he supported Eagleton after the
disclosure, McGovern cooled on his running mate and the Missouri
senator withdrew _ the first time a major party candidate left a
national ticket after a convention.
   In 1984, Democrat Walter Mondale announced his choice of Rep.
Geraldine Ferraro of New York in the week before the convention.
   She won nomination by acclamation, but immediately questions
were raised about the finances of her husband, John Zaccaro, a real
estate investor, and about her financial disclosure forms filed
with the Congress.
   To quiet the storm, she released reams of financial documents
and held a news conference in New York that allayed most questions,
but the affair distracted the Democratic campaigners from issues
they wanted to emphasize.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--$4MillionLunch     08-19 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--$4 Million Lunch,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Gala Nets $4 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the Republicans' richest fund-raiser
of the year, and all the big names were there: the Bushes, the
Quayles, the Doles; Jack Kemp and a fistful of senators; Muhammad
Ali, Rosie Grier, Leo Nadeau.
   Leo Nadeau.
   ``You're wondering: Who the hell is Leo Nadeau?'' the
silver-haired man told 4,500 mystified guests at the New Orleans
Convention Center, most of whom paid $1,000 to rub shoulders
Thursday with brighter luminaries.
   The answer: He was George Bush's tail-gunner 45 years ago, when
Bush was a Navy bomber pilot during World War II. And of all the
speakers who paid Bush tribute, Nadeau is the only one the vice
president thanked with a hug.
   ``We were just a couple of kids,'' Nadeau told the crowd as he
introduced his old war buddy. ``But we became men overnight.''
   They shared the stage Thursday under more pleasant
circumstances, helping raise roughly $4.3 million for the
Republican National Committee's operating budget. That was twice
what the RNC collected at its 1984 convention gala.
   The take amounted to the RNC's best ever for a $1,000-per-plate
affair, though the committee pulled in $5.8 million at a
higher-priced dinner-dance in 1984, said spokeswoman Katherine
Murray.
   This event was done up in style, staged on a ``Road to Victory''
theme with a strip of black carpet leading from a huge mockup of a
riverboat to a huge mockup of the White House. The wine bottles
bore RNC Gala labels. The menu included chicken breasts with ``GOP
fresh tarragon.''
   Bush and his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, arrived
with their wives in an antique fire engine led by a marching band.
Looking on were Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and Rep. Kemp of New York,
who both ran against Bush and lost.
   And the real heavyweights: former boxing champion Ali, who
shared a table with Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah; and former
professional football player Grier, now a preacher. Grier gave the
invocation, first telling the standing assemblage: ``You can sit
down.''
   Gala chairman Lodwrick Cook took the microphone. ``Rosie,'' he
said, ``when you tell us to sit, we'll sit.''
   They paid to: in addition to the private and corporate donors
who shelled out $1,000 each, nine companies underwrote the party
with $100,000 donations.
   Bush rewarded the crowd with a preview of his acceptance speech.
He also stressed his loyalty to Quayle, who was embroiled in a
controversy over whether he used family connections to join the
National Guard and avoid the Vietnam draft in 1969.
   For his part, Nadeau spoke of his and Bush's wartime experience.
   ``There are millions of Americans like me, men and women who've
seen the face of war,'' he said. ``When we elect our next
commander-in-chief, we will have made sure he is someone who has
the courage and experience we can depend on for our lives and our
livelihoods.''
   Bush took up the theme. ``Leo Nadeau talked about a mission that
he and I shared. ... We had a mission. We knew what we had to do.
... And now I stand here as one of two people who will be president
of the United States of America. And I know that I've got a
mission. A new mission.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
