<DOCNO> AP880819-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--DamageControl     08-19 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Damage Control,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Forces Mobilize To Control Damage From Quayle Revelations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``There's nothing to this,'' said a George
Bush campaign aide, engaging in a classic exercise in political
damage control to quell the controversy over Republican vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle's military service.
   ``We have chased down every single rumor. We haven't been able
to substantiate one single rumor,'' Bush press secretary Sheila
Tate said Thursday after a three-hour afternoon meeting.
   Bush political aides were plunged into a wearying scramble by
the unanticipated questions raised about the Indiana senator,
questions that threatened to rob the campaign of the boost they
counted on getting from their national convention.
   They briefed the chairmen of state delegations to calm their
concerns and to assure them the whole matter had been overblown.
   During a series of meetings beginning Wednesday night and
continuing through Thursday, top Bush aides confronted the fact
that the Quayle flap also was endangering their careful plans for a
closing convention session that would have Bush firmly in the
spotlight as the new leader of the Republican Party.
   They discussed issuing a detailed statement ``citing chapter and
verse'' of how Quayle entered the Indiana National Guard in 1969
when many draftees were being sent to Vietnam, according to one
campaign aide who insisted on anonymity.
   Among the questions raised was whether Quayle, a member of an
influential publishing family, had sought and received special
treatment.
   But the idea of issuing a statement was dropped because it was
felt it would detract from Bush's acceptance speech.
   For the same reason, a Quayle news conference was vetoed.
   ``It's the vice president's night, why should Sen. Quayle hold
some big news conference?'' said Tate.
   When he arrived at the hall, Quayle refused to discuss the
matter with reporters.
   But the controversy could not be ignored.
   Influential Republicans were uneasy with the matter and
demanding answers.
   ``I don't like the fact that Quayle denied yesterday that
anybody had interceded on his behalf when apparently someone had,''
said Rep. Helen Bentley, chairman of the Bush campaign in Maryland.
``Quayle can do one of two things: admit this and that he was a
liar _ or he can withdraw from the race.''
   Later, she backed away from her comment, claiming she had been
responding to inaccurate news reports.
   Rep. Tom Tauke of Iowa said he was concerned that Quayle may
have misled Bush campaign officials when they asked about his
military service.
   ``If appropriate information was sought and appropriate
information wasn't forthcoming, then if I were George Bush I'd
reserve the right to reconsider,'' Tauke said.
   Bush aides moved swiftly to generate a swell of comment
downplaying the significance of the allegations.
   Campaign chairman James A. Baker III went on Cable News Network
to say, ``There's no substantiation. A lot of rumors, no
substantiation.''
   ``We're in the midst of a national convention, where you're
going to get a whole lot of rumors swirling, popping up every
hour,'' Baker said. ``But they pop up, nothing's produced and they
die. There hasn't been one thing. If you've got something I'd like
to hear about it.''
   During the closing convention session, a document was circulated
on the floor that cited news accounts quoting Indiana National
Guard officials as saying that no one needed special influence to
join in 1969.
   ``We would take anyone we could get,'' was a quote from former
Indiana Adjutant General John N. Owens.
   A second sheet that circulated was labeled, ``FACT SHEET: USE OF
NATIONAL GUARD.''
   ``When Dan Quayle joined the Army National Guard, guard units
were being called up and sent to Vietnam,'' said the material
compiled by the National Guard Bureau.
   Republican Party chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. echoed that
view and also took another common approach, suggesting that somehow
the accounts were an insult to the National Guard.
   Fahrenkopf said the debate over Quayle's service seemed based on
the idea that ``somehow it's not honorable to be in the Guard or
Navy or Army reserves and that's ridiculous.''
   One of the most effective parts of the damage control strategy
was to have Quayle refer to his service in his speech accepting the
vice presidential nomination.
   ``As a young man, I served six years in the National Guard, and,
like millions of Americans who have served in the Guard and who
serve today _ and I am proud of that,'' he said to cheers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
