<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're planning on watching the ``Today''
show anytime soon, don't expect to see co-host Bryant Gumbel
interviewing David Letterman. Or Cher. Or James Earl Jones. Or
Garrison Keillor. Or ...
   ``Meeting celebrities has never been something that thrills me.
I can't believe what (expletive) some so-called stars can be,''
Gumbel says in an interview in the Sept. 5 issue of US magazine.
   Gumbel holds a grudge against Letterman stemming from a 1984
prank when the ``Late Night With David Letterman'' host interrupted
a ``Today'' show taping by using a bullhorn to proclaim he was NBC
boss Grant Tinker and ``not wearing any pants.''
   ``I still think he's an (expletive) and many people interviewed
by him think so too. He never apologized and I have nothing to say
to him,'' Gumbel said before ripping into other performers.
   _On Cher: ``I have an aversion to professional celebrities who
appear on the cover of `People' every six months, and who run out
and do every little cheap gym ad.''
   _On James Earl Jones: ``When an interview with him is going
badly, I feel no compulsion to make him look better.''
   _On Garrison Keillor: ``A real jerk ... the worst.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Merrill, suffering from lung
cancer, has been hospitalized for treatment of a chest infection, a
spokeswoman said.
   The 73-year-old Merrill, who appeared in the 1950 Oscar-winning
movie ``All About Eve'' and later married co-star Bette Davis, was
rushed to Mercy Hospital Tuesday from his Portland-area home.
Merrill said he had undergone exploratory surgery at the hospital
last week and was released after two days.
   ``I didn't slow down after they let me out,'' he said. ``I'm
like any other little kid. So they've grounded me; they want to
keep track of me.''
   Hospital spokeswoman Leslie Gall said Thursday that Merrill was
being treated for a skin infection in his chest wall and was in
good condition.
   Merrill's stormy 10-year marriage to Davis ended in divorce.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day after his company filed for
bankruptcy protection, moviemaker Dino De Laurentiis' estranged
wife filed for divorce.
   The divorce papers filed Wednesday by Silvana De Laurentiis in
Superior Court cite irreconcilable differences and seek unspecified
spousal support.
   The couple was married July 18, 1949, and separated in September
1983, the petition said.
   De Laurentiis Entertainment Group filed for protection from
creditors Tuesday under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code,
which allows the company to operate while it reorganizes.
   De Laurentiis, who produced such films as ``Blue Velvet'' and
``Crimes of the Heart,'' owns 61.9 percent of the company. He
stepped down from management in February.
