<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York real estate tycoon Donald Trump says
half-seriously that he wishes media mogul Rupert Murdoch hadn't
sold the New York Post.
   ``Rupert, come back!'' Trump implored Thursday at a breakfast at
the Republican National Convention.
   Trump accused new Post publisher Peter Kalikow of picking on him
in the newspaper at the same time Kalikow persuaded him to buy
advertising for a department store chain Trump controls.
   ``You son of a gun, you're killing me,'' said Trump, who related
that a Post reporter called him about the same time as the
advertising request to ask whether the stores were closing.
   ``You don't know how devastating that is to employee morale'' to
see stories like that in the paper, Trump said.
   Kalikow, who bought the financially ailing paper in March, was
sitting a few feet away in the audience. Trump sounded at least
half-serious, and while Kalikow was laughing, he looked
uncomfortable.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Geo. A. Hormel & Co. has purchased Chicken
by George Inc., the Louisville, Ky., company founded by former Miss
America Phyllis George.
   Under terms of the agreement, Hormel will operate Chicken by
George as a separate division, Hormel Chairman R.L. Knowlton said
in a statement Thursday. The sale price was not disclosed.
   Founded by Miss George in 1986, Chicken by George has built a
strong business in Kentucky with a line of fresh, marinated chicken
breast entrees.
   Knowlton said Miss George will be actively involved in all
facets of new product development, marketing and promotion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writer Gary Giddins plans to change the date
Louis Armstrong was born _ at least in print.
   Giddins' biography of the jazz trumpeter, ``Satchmo,'' to be
published in November, will give Armstrong's birth date as Aug. 4,
1901. Armstrong, who died in 1971, celebrated his birthday on July
4 and said he was born in 1900.
   Giddins is not the first to question Armstrong's birth date.
James Lincoln Collier's 1983 biography ``Louis Armstrong: An
American Genius'' placed the correct birth year at 1898.
   Writing about his research in the current issue of the Village
Voice, Giddins said he found a baptismal record for Armstrong at
the Sacred Heart of Jesus Church in New Orleans that gave his birth
date as Aug. 4, 1901.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Buttram, best-known as the sidekick of
singing cowboy Gene Autry, has been enshrined in concrete with a
Hollywood Walk of Fame star in front of a sandwich shop that
features his name on its menu.
   More than 200 fans crowded in front of the Hollywood Boulevard
site Thursday to witness the star unveiling, including old friends
Iron Eyes Cody, George Gobel and Autry, who was leaning on a cane.
   ``This is the first time I've ever been speechless,'' said the
usually talkative Buttram in front of Checker's Specialty Sandwich
Shop.
   Buttram appeared in more than 40 westerns and portrayed the
rural con man Mr. Haney on the old CBS-TV series ``Green Acres.''
</TEXT>
