<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Westinghouse     08-19 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Westinghouse,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Age Discrimination Cases Settled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 4,000 former Westinghouse
Electric Corp. employees denied severance pay because of their age
could share $35 million in what is believed to be the largest
settlement of a discrimination case.
   ``We broke some new ground,'' Charles Shanor, general counsel of
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, said Thursday.
   EEOC's negotiators were armed with a federal court ruling that
Westinghouse violated the Age Discrimination in Employment Act when
it denied severance pay to employees who were eligible for pensions
after their jobs were eliminated in plant closings that began in
1980.
   The EEOC sued Westinghouse in New Jersey and Pennsylvania in the
early 1980s. The Pennsylvania suit was expanded in 1984 to include
Westinghouse employees nationwide, except those represented in the
New Jersey suit.
   A federal judge in New Jersey dismissed that suit, and the EEOC
appealed to the U.S. 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia.
In the Pennsylvania suit, however, a federal district judge ruled
in the agency's favor, and Westinghouse appealed that decision to
the 3rd Circuit.
   ``The district court held...that forcing a pension-eligible
employee to choose between the pension and severance is unlawful,''
Shanor said in a telephone interview from Washington.
   The resolution of the suits, if approved in federal court, will
probably be the largest cash settlement ever in a discrimination
case if it is approved in federal court, Shanor said.
   Westinghouse believes 4,000 former employees, who were primarily
blue-collar production workers, should share the $35 million, an
estimate the EEOC will check.
   ``If our checking...reveals a disparity then the settlement is
off,'' Shanor said.
   Westinghouse said it agreed to deposit the money in escrow for
distribution after various conditions are met.
   First, the 3rd Circuit Court must agree to suspend ruling on the
case until a U.S. District Court in Philadelphia rules on the
fairness of the settlement. The lower court is expected to convene
a hearing where the former employees can comment, said EEOC
spokeswoman Margaret Fernandez.
   Other contingencies include an agreement between the company and
the agency that a layoff policy being proposed by Westinghouse is
lawful, she said.
   Among other large discrimination suit settlements, Pan Am Corp.
agreed earlier this year to pay $17.2 million and offer training to
pilots it had barred from continuing to work as flight engineers
once they reached age 60, Mrs. Fernandez said.
   Shanor said he knew of at least two similar pending cases
against other companies, which he declined to identify.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
