<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Biographer Visits Ranch</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Reagan phone call to Bush at end of convention,
picking up 3rd graf pvs, ``Fitzwater said...White House.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan telephoned Vice
President George Bush to congratulate him after his acceptance
speech at the Republican National Convention, the president's
spokesman said.
   Marlin Fitzwater, assistant to the president for press
relations, said Reagan told the vice president, ``Congratulations.
It was a great speech, and we're all with you, George.''
   Fitzwater said the president and First Lady Nancy Reagan watched
the speech on television at their ranch north of here, where they
are vacationing.
   Reagan, who also watched Wednesday night's convention
proceedings on television, met earlier Thursday with the
prize-winning author who is writing his biography.
   Fitzwater said Reagan was meeting Thursday with Edmund Morris,
who won the Pulitzer Prize for biography for his book, ``The Rise
of Theodore Roosevelt.'' Morris, who has been given special access
to the president for the project, has declined to talk with
reporters about the book, explaining that was part of his agreement
with the White House.
   Fitzwater said Reagan did routine paperwork and went horseback
riding with Mrs. Reagan after breakfast.
   He signed five bills Wednesday, including one increasing the
amount of money for presidential transitions, beginning with his
early next year. The amount for the incoming president and vice
president is increased from $2 million to $3.5 million and the
amount for the outgoing president and vice president goes from $1
million to $1.5 million.
   The president goes to Irvine, Calif., next Tuesday for a
fund-raising luncheon for Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and will
continue on to Los Angeles, where he will likely make a joint
appearance with Bush on Wednesday.
   The Reagans will return to Washington on Sept. 8 and are
expected to visit the ranch once more, at Thanksgiving, before the
president's term ends in January.
</TEXT>
