<DOCNO> AP880819-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--LifeintheGuard     08-19 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Life in the Guard,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writing `Mushy Little Features' With Time for a Beer or Two</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDEL HUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle spent his six years in the
Indiana National Guard as a clerk-typist in the 120th Public
Information Detachment helping to turn out a quarterly magazine,
the Indiana National Guardsman.
   It wasn't difficult duty, recalled one member of the 12-member
unit.
   ``The magazine had a lot of mushy little feature stories in it
that didn't require too much effort,'' said James G. Newland Jr., a
reporter for The Indianapolis Star.
   ``We had some free time and it wasn't odd for us to drink some
beer and play cards during an extended lunch break or after
drill,'' Newland told the Star. ``We never failed to have a good
time.''
   Another member of the unit, Sam R. Graves III, former superviser
of the detachment, said Quayle was patriotic, pro-military and not
a draft-dodger.
   ``Politically, we are at opposite ends of the scale,'' said
Graves. ``But when I think of him, words like `integrity' come to
mind, `enthusiasm,' `patriotism'.''
   Quayle was nominated Thursday night as the Republican candidate
for vice president, and his membership in the Guard has come under
scrutiny following the disclosure that he may have used pull to get
in at a time when his contemporaries were being drafted and sent to
Vietnam.
   In Washington, Pentagon records showed that service in the
National Guard was not likely to lead to duty in Vietnam.
   Some 3.4 million servicemen and women were sent to Southeast
Asia during the Vietnam War. Only about 9,000 were in mobilized
Army and Air National Guard units.
   By the time the fighting ended, there had been more than 58,000
American casualties, of which 97 were guardsmen.
   Quayle had worked from 1965 to 1969 at his family's newspaper,
the Huntington Herald-Press, while studying political science at
DePauw University in Greencastle.
   He joined the Guard in May 1969 after his student deferment
expired. He started out as a clerk-typist.
   In 1973, Quayle was reclassified as a journalist, helping other
members of the 120th produce the award-winning magazine.
   Quayle met with the group at least one weekend a month and for
15 days of active duty during the summer.
   ``I do recall that on one occasion when he was there we had a
hell of a good time,'' said James A. Gillaspy, another former
member and now a reporter with the Indianapolis Star. ``He did his
job like the rest of us. And when the job was done, he partied like
the rest of us.''
   Graves objected to accounts that he said portrayed the group as
composed of slackers.
   ``It made the outfit look like all we did was sit around and
drink beer, and the kind of outfit in which you had to have
connections to get in,'' he said. ``There were times when we were
frenetic and other times when we had down time. But that doesn't
mean we were sitting around drinking all the time.''
   The same year he became a Guard journalist, Quayle was attending
law school in Indianapolis and working at a full-time job in the
state government. Graves said he and others occasionally missed
their Guard obligations but would make up for the absences later.
   ``In all those years in which I knew him, I was never once led
to believe that his family was moneyed or that he had any influence
to peddle,'' Graves said. ``He always did whatever he was told,
always with a certain amount of enthusiasm. He never quibbled.''
   On Thursday, retired Guard Maj. Gen. Wendell C. Phillippi, who
was managing editor of the Indianapolis News and worked for
Quayle's grandfather, publisher Eugene C. Pulliam, said he made a
phone call to help Quayle gain entry into the guard.
   Phillippi said Quayle asked him whether Guard units in Indiana
were likely to be sent to Vietnam.
   But Capt. Cathi Kiger, a spokeswoman for the Indiana Guard, said
that ``Across the board, we were under strength, so there were some
openings in the state.''
   She said records show the Guard's authorized strength on July
31, 1969, was 10,378, but that only 10,218 positions were filled.
   ``It's anything but a cushy job,'' said photographer Bob Jordan,
another former member of the group. ``I think a lot of people
thought it was.
   ``You tried to promote the National Guard and get as much ink,
like any other public relations outfit. You would try to promote
your own outfit, in that case the Indiana National Guard.''
   Quayle enlisted as a Private E-1, the lowest possible rank, and
rose to Specialist 5.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
