<HEAD>Highlights From Convention's Last Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the highlights of the
last day of the Republican National Convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   George Bush formally launched his quest for the White House,
depicting himself as the underdog in the race against Michael
Dukakis and pledging to ``run hard, to fight hard, to stand on the
issues.
   ``And I mean to win,'' he said in a prime-time address to the
convention. He began with a self-deprecating promise, ``I'll try to
keep my charisma in check.''
   Bush addresses a meeting of the Republican National Committee
today and then sets out on a six-day campaign swing through the
Midwest and far West.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE VICE PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A voice vote was chosen over a roll call to formally nominate
Dan Quayle as Bush's running mate. In accepting the nomination,
Quayle told the delegates: ``Just, just think, 82 days from now,
George Bush and I are going to win one for you, win one for
America's future, and, yes, win one for the Gipper.''
   Earlier in the day, Quayle appeared at a fund-raising luncheon
with the presidential nominee and declared, ``I can't wait to take
this campaign to the American people ... Let's go get 'em,''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>QUAYLE AND THE NATIONAL GUARD</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Quayle was swamped in controversy hours before his vice
presidential nomination after it was disclosed that a family
connection helped him join the National Guard at the height of the
Vietnam War.
   He referred to the controversy in his speech, telling the
convention: ``As a young man, I served six years in the National
Guard, and, like millions of Americans who have served in the Guard
and who serve today _ and I am proud of that.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BARBARA BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush used her national political convention speech to
extol the virtues of her husband and speak from the heart about the
death of a daughter.
   Mrs. Bush told the convention, ``You've nominated for the
presidency a man who is as strong and caring and decent as America
herself.''
</TEXT>
