<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--TheParty'sOver     08-19 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--The Party's Over,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Clean-Up Party Begins Shortly After the Gavel Sounds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moments after the last ``Bush '88'' chant
echoed through the cavernous Superdome and the last red, white and
blue balloons fell to the floor, a round-the-clock cleanup party
began.
   Republican National Convention delegates helped start the
process late Thursday by collecting home state signs and scavenging
``We Love George'' and ``Bush-Quayle'' placards as souvenirs.
   Standing at the ready beneath one of the network television
booths, 10 workers equipped with brooms and shovels waited for the
last delegate to leave so they could sweep up every piece of
refuse, every bit of confetti.
   ``We have to get started immediately after the session, we
really do,'' said Mary Mead, a spokeswoman for the convention. ``We
have to move fast.''
   Construction of the podium, stairways and wooden floors took
500,000 man-hours. It will take just 8,000 man-hours to rip down
the 1.2 million pounds of scaffolding, tear up the 150,000 square
feet of plywood and take out the 150,000 nuts, bolts and screws.
   The transformation from convention hall to football stadium and
special events center better be done on schedule, according to Ms.
Mead.
   ``There's a dual high school football game on Friday the 26th.
We have to be completely out of here on the 25th,'' she said.
   And if that isn't enough incentive, the New Orleans Saints host
the Pittsburgh Steelers that weekend in a nationally televised game.
   Pete Vicari, whose general contracting company built the
$560,000 podium, had 20 of his employees stripping the rostrum,
pulling up the carpets and removing the light fixtures late
Thursday.
   ``As of noon Friday, we'll just start demolishing and it will be
all hauled off to the dump,'' Vicari said. ``By Saturday, we should
be cleared out of the dome.''
   Fred Nodier of South Central Bell had half his staff working a
midnight-to-8 a.m. shift, tearing down the thousands of feet of
cable installed for the convention.
   The GOP parley required 9,000 lines of cable compared to the
last major event _ a Super Bowl and its 1,000 cable lines.
   ``It's monumental, but we have a good team,'' he said.
   The convention staff had its employees packing their files
together last weekend to ensure a speedy departure as soon as the
gavel was pounded to end the last session.
   ``It's just like when you put it together, you have to do it in
an organized fashion so you're not stumbling all over one
another,'' Ms. Mead said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
