<DOCNO> AP880819-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Quayle-At-A-Glance     08-19 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle-At-A-Glance,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights Of Controversy Over Quayle Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments related
to the controversy over the military service of Republican vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ISSUE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Whether Quayle, a conservative supporter of the military and a
member of the Senate Armed Services Committee, used the influence
of his prominent Indiana family to get a position in the National
Guard in 1969 and thus avoid being drafted for almost-certain
service in Vietnam.
   Also, whether he was totally candid with aides to presidential
nominee George Bush who questioned him about his National Guard
service and how he gained entry into the Guard. Of the more than
58,000 American casualties in the Vietnam war, 97 were Guardsmen.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>QUAYLE'S RESPONSE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Quayle told the national convention he was proud of his service
in the National Guard. His aides said there may have been calls
made on his behalf to get in, but they and he deferred all detailed
responses until today.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSH'S RESPONSE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush said he was proud to have Quayle on the ticket. His aides
circulated research papers on the convention floor which said that
there were vacancies in the Indiana Guard in 1969 and that no one
needed special influence to get in. The papers said that some Guard
units at that time were being called to duty in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DELEGATE REACTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Many rallied behind their vice presidential nominee and rebuked
the news media for focusing on the controversy. Some delegates said
they still want to hear a fuller explanation from the Indiana
senator. Others called it ``a tempest in a teapot,'' and predicted
the issue would quickly blow away.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATIC REACTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice president nominee Lloyd Bentsen, campaigning in
Texas, refused to criticize Quayle's service in the Guard. ``I'm
not going to question that,'' said Bentsen, a World War II bomber
pilot. ``I'm a strong supporter of the National Guard and always
have been. One of my own sons served in the National Guard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
