<DOCNO> AP880819-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Libertarians     08-19 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Libertarians,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Something Close to Anarchy at the GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the heart of George Bush's Republican
convention, some Republican rebels came to preach the gospel of
minimalist government.
   They were libertarians: believers in the smallest government
possible; the fewest government restraints on personal liberty and
freedom. They call it being ``fiscally conservative, socially
tolerant.''
   From a booth in a hotel marketplace selling convention
souvenirs, the Libertarian Republican Organizing Committee passed
out literature, searched for converts and, its officers said,
collected hundreds of names and addresses.
   Colin Hunter, owner of a computer software company in
California's Silicon Valley, is the organization's national
chairman.
   Essentially, Hunter and the libertarians embrace most of the
Reagan administration's economic programs but contend they have
fallen far short of perfection.
   Hunter and the libertarians would take the GOP out of social
issues almost entirely and they seek a noninterventionist foreign
policy, including deep cuts in defense budgets.
   Specifically, they advocate:
   _Fighting off a tax increase.
   _Fighting against protectionist trade legislation.
   _Making deep cuts in entitlement programs, including phasing out
Social Security and welfare.
   _Turning many government agencies and services over to private
enterprise.
   _Opposing all attempts to legislate morality.
   _Urging the legalization of drugs for adults.
   _Advocating a pro-choice policy on abortion.
   ``The emphasis is on individual liberty against the power of the
government,'' Hunter said in an interview.
   ``I've been extremely gratified by the response,'' he said,
adding that the most ``negative feedback'' his libertarian ideas
received at the Republican convention came from the supporters of
television preacher Pat Robertson.
   Hunter calls Robertson ``the Ayatollah.''
   Hunter says he founded his organization after coming to the
conclusion that the ideas of libertarianism could best flourish
inside the two-party system. He opposes the third-party strategy
represented by the national Libertarian Party as ``essentially
hopeless.'
   Hunter contends that the Republican party is not a monolith,
especially on social issues.
   ``Fifty percent of the delegates here are pro-choice,'' he
asserted, contending that the percentage among Republican voters as
a whole is higher than that.
   ``Other Republicans are afraid we'll turn the country over to
Jerry Falwell,'' he declared.
   The problem, he contended, is that the Republican Party has
``allowed the religious right to capture the reputation of being
the font of ideas. We think that the key ideological debate in
America is happening within the Republican Party.''
   He was asked about the proposal to legalize drugs.
   ``The parallels with prohibition are precise,'' he replied.
``There is now a massive crime wave. There are extremely high
profits involved. To us it's clear; the evils of making it legal
outweigh whatever. It will still be a vice, but not a crime.''
   He said aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua should end simply
because it has not worked, because the Contras have not ignited a
spark with the Nicaraguan people.
   ``We really have a giant welfare program for the Contras,'' he
said.
   Hunter said he did endorse U.S. aid to anti-Soviet insurgents in
Afghanistan, in part because it they had the obvious support of the
vast majority of the Afghan people.
   With all the changes his philosophy would impose, Hunter was
asked what laws libertarians would repeal if they had majority,
veto-proof control of both houses of Congress.
   ``The only law we would have to repeal is the law imposing
penalties for income tax evasion,'' he replied.
   An associate, Eric Garris, the organization's national director,
added: ``We believe that taxation is theft.''
   ``What we would actually do is reduce the size and scope of
government as quickly as possible, given the political situation
and given reality,'' Hunter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     08-19 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Says Government to Extend Cease-Fire; Radio Station to
Reopen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government said it will
extend its unilateral cease-fire with Contra rebels and is ready to
resume peace talks immediately, according to a U.S. senator who met
with President Daniel Ortega.
   Also Thursday, the government said that Radio Catolica can go
back on the air, but without news broadcasts.
   Monsignor Bismarck Carballo, spokesman for the Catholic
archdiocese in the capital, Managua, said Radio Catolica would
resume broadcasting today, 38 days after being ordered shut for
news coverage that allegedly incited violence.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who met Thursday with Ortega and
his brother, Defense Minister Humberto Ortega, said the Sandinistas
are willing to resume peace talks immediately with the
U.S.-supported rebels known as Contras.
   ``There are no preconditions on talks'' with the rebels, Dodd
said at Augusto Cesar Sandino Airport shortly before leaving
Nicaragua.
   ``They said they would extend (the cease-fire) indefinitely,''
said Dodd, a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and
chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Western Hemisphere Affairs.
   The truce began March 21, two days before the government and
rebels signed an agreement to negotiate a permanent end to the
7-year-old war. High-level peace talks broke off June 9, and a
unilateral government extension of the cease-fire was set to expire
Aug. 31.
   Ortega on Thursday renewed his proposal to begin a new round of
talks in Managua on Aug. 26. The rebels, citing restrictions on
their freedom of movement, said they would not return to the
capital. They also demanded that the president take part in any
future discussions.
   The Interior Ministry has authorized the Roman Catholic Church's
radio station to resume broadcasting. An Interior Ministry
spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Carballo sent a
letter Wednesday pledging the station will not broadcast news.
   The leftist government closed Radio Catolica indefinitely on
July 11, the same day it shut down La Prensa, the country's only
opposition newspaper, for 15 days. The orders came a day after
police violently broke up a demonstration by opposition groups.
   La Prensa has since resumed publication.
   The government said Radio Catolica's news program ``Church
News'' had ``incited violence, disorder and lack of respect for the
constitutional government.''
   Dodd also said he discussed with the Sandinistas the latest U.S.
Senate package to provide humanitarian aid to the Contras.
   ``Obviously they are not happy,'' Dodd said, adding that the
possibility of renewed U.S. military aid to the rebels was ``very
open'' and that the government ``should know about that.''
   U.S. military aid for the rebels expired in February. On Aug.
10, the Senate approved a $27 million humanitarian aid package for
the rebels with a possible second vote on $16.3 million in
stockpiled military aid later this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
