<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Television     08-19 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Television,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Self-Examination Marks Final Night</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last night of the Republican National
Convention presented the television networks two stories, but
little time to pursue them.
   ``News has broken out, gentlemen,'' ABC's Brit Hume proclaimed.
   The big story was the controversy over Sen. Dan Quayle's
National Guard enlistment, and the related questions about what
this possible blot on the GOP vice presidential nominee said about
the man at the top of the ticket.
   The other story was how well Vice President George Bush would
deliver his acceptance speech, which was praised in advance by CBS
anchor Dan Rather as ``an excellent speech ... as you read it on
paper.''
   As NBC anchor Tom Brokaw noted, Bush's speech, and Quayle's
which preceded it, took up a lot of time when the cameras were
compelled to focus on Quayle and Bush in their own words, with a
partisan crowd cheering them on.
   It was time when floor reporters could not raise new questions,
or variations of older questions, about whether strings had been
pulled to get Quayle into the Guard.
   It was an advantage the Bush campaign gratefully accepted.
Quayle did talk briefly to reporters, promising to answer all their
questions about the controversy, but not now.
   ``Well, give him credit,'' Rather said, praising Quayle for
facing the microphones even if he said nothing.
   ABC's reporters engaged in some self-examination about the
media's role in the Quayle story, which the network's George Will
called a ``journalistic feeding frenzy.''
   ABC's David Brinkley said the day's big story was at least
partly a function of the thousands of reporters on the scene.
   ``If this had happened in the middle of the desert, you would
never have heard about it,'' Brinkley said. ``It was the first new
thing, the first unexpected thing, the first news we've had.''
   And the network's Jeff Greenfield said it had taken ``about 3{
seconds'' for a backlash against the media to appear on the
convention floor. Recalling the Watergate hearings, Greenfield
suggested the key question for the Bush brain trust was ``what did
they know and when did they know it?''
   Thus, Quayle's acceptance speech was a test, one which CBS
commentator Kevin Phillips likened to Richard Nixon's ``Checkers''
speech in 1952, which saved his spot as Dwight D. Eisenhower's
running mate. ``I'm not so sure he turned the corner,'' Phillips
said of Quayle.
   On Bush's speech, however, the networks were unanimous. It was
at least a good speech, and many thought it the best speech of
Bush's career.
   ``He looked presidential,'' Walter Cronkite said on CBS.
   ``A splendid piece of work, well delivered and well written,''
said NBC's John Chancellor.
   ``It was a George Bush I hadn't seen before ... effective; not
eloquent. He was studied, he was poetic,'' Brinkley said. ``He
delivered a good speech very well.''
   ABC's Sam Donaldson was alone in taking issue with some of what
Bush said, accusing him of distorting the record of Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis on guns, the pledge of allegiance and
whether the nation is in decline.
   Despite the outbreak of news, all three networks showed a
weakness for trivia.
   CBS, which went on an hour earlier than the competition, was
alone with murky, long-distance pictures of Quayle's motorcade as
it arrived at the Superdome.
   Later, both CBS and NBC jumped quickly on equally unedifying
coverage of Bush's motorcade, while ABC stayed with an interview
with Bush campaign chief James Baker until it, too, succumbed to
the majesty of a vice-presidential auto ride.
   CBS again scored over the competition by having exclusive
pictures of Bush actually stepping out of his limousine.
   No one could resist the balloon drop. ``They've gotta be
hand-tied,'' Brokaw marveled.
   Rather at least put the balloons and the rest of the spectacle
in some perspective by recalling the attitude of President Reagan's
campaign advisers _ ``Just put up our pictures, and we'll take it
and win the election.''
   Perhaps with that in mind, CBS was alone in refusing to carry
Bush's short campaign film. Instead, it put up the same warm images
with commentary by Bill Plante.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0044 </DOCNO>
