<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels     08-19 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Overrun Rebel Camp, Kill Four, Capture Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops overran a rebel camp,
killing four men, taking two prisoners and capturing a cache of
arms and ammunition, an army official said.
   Lt. Col. Godfrey Bamwesigye said Thursday that the battle
occurred this week, but he didn't say when. He said the rebels were
army deserters who had been members of the Uganda Federal
Democratic Movement and the Uganda Freedom Movement.
   Both movements fought alongside President Yoweri Museveni's
National Resistance Army during a five-year guerilla war against
former civilian President Milton Obote.
   Obote was overthrown in a July 1985 military coup. Museveni
established a broad-based government that included several other
former guerrilla groups, including the Uganda Federal Democratic
Movement and the Uganda Freedom Movement.
   Since then, Museveni has had to fight at least eight guerrilla
groups trying to bring down his government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Quayle-Reaction     08-19 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle-Reaction,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Issue Stuns Convention, But Delegates Rally Around Their Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The question of whether Dan Quayle pulled
strings to get into the National Guard during the Vietnam war
dominated the last day of the Republican convention but by night's
end many delegates had rallied behind their vice presidential
nominee.
   Some delegates said they still want to hear a fuller explanation
from the Indiana senator. But others called it small potatoes and
predicted the issue would blow away quickly.
   Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas said, ``If the worst thing Dan Quayle's
ever done in his life is that his dad helped him commit six years
to America in the National Guard, he's almost eligible for
sainthood. He certainly isn't disqualified from being vice
president.''
   Gordon K. Durnil, the head of the Indiana delegation, called it
``an anchor-booth generated story. ... Tomorrow it will be over and
there will be something else.''
   William Brock, the former national GOP party chairman and labor
secretary, said, ``I think we had a 24-hour problem.''
   John Katopodis of Birmingham, Ala., a Jefferson County
commissioner, said he had ``an uneasy feeling another shoe is going
to drop.'' He said he wished Quayle had tackled the issue
``head-on'' in his acceptance speech.
   Quayle, 41, drew cheers when he said he was ``very proud'' of
his six years in the National Guard. He made no further reference
to the controversy. By joining the Guard, he was almost certain of
avoiding service in Vietnam.
   Eddie Mahe, a Republican strategist from Washington, said that
``15,000 people (got) to experience that inside-the-beltway feeling
we live with all the time.''
   More than a few delegates said that if Quayle's aim was to stay
out of Vietnam in 1969, he had plenty of company.
   In those days, said Gene Ward, the chairman of the Hawaii
delegation and a Vietnam veteran, ``everybody and their uncle was
trying to get an angle about how to get out of the draft.''
   ``They used to say you were bad if you went to Vietnam, and now
they're saying ... if you didn't, that you're somehow unpatriotic.
How times have changed!'' said Ward.
   Samuel Atkins, 43, a Watkinsville, Ga., lawyer, said the ``baby
boomers will understand, but the older generation may hold it
against him.''
   Rep. Helen Delich Bentley of Maryland, who initially suggested
Quayle might have to withdraw, said Thursday night the issue was
``dead'' and had been based on ``inaccurate news reports.''
   ``What's the big deal?'' asked Sen. Gordon Humphrey of New
Hampshire, a staunch conservative. ``He pulled some strings to
serve his country. He could have gone to Canada.''
   Rep. Bob Dornan of California said, ``It requires a
Checkers-like speech ... quickly, before this gets out of hand,'' a
reference to the speech that Richard M. Nixon delivered in 1952
when he got caught up in a ``slush fund'' controversy. Nixon,
running mate to Dwight D. Eisenhower, said he would not give back
one gift, a dog named Checkers.
   George Walker Bush Jr., the vice president's eldest son, called
the furor over Quayle's military service ``ridiculous'' and said he
joined the National Guard, too, in 1968.
   ``It was available and I went,'' said Bush, 42, who was a
stateside pilot. ``I thought it was service to my country and I'm
proud of (it).''
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Navy fighter pilot who spent 5{
years in a Hanoi prison, said serving in the Guard is honorable.
   ``If, however, there is clear evidence that the process may have
been manipulated to give some kind of special preference, then I
think it's a problem ... that needs to be resolved,'' McCain said.
   If Quayle had ``gone to Canada, I would have been on the floor
protesting,'' said Richard Geist, a state lawmaker from Altoona, Pa.
   Tom Burch, a former Green Beret who is chairman of the
250,000-member Vietnam Veterans Coalition, called it ``a tempest in
a teapot.''
   ``There was nothing unusual'' about opting for the National
Guard, and even if his family helped ``it wouldn't make any
difference,'' said Burch, a Virginia delegate. ``He didn't try to
evade the military.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
