<DOCNO> AP880819-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CorporateSchool Bjt   08-19 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corporate School, Bjt,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Hopes To Foster Learning Through Corporate Management</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new elementary school in one of the nation's
most criticized school systems will ``reinvent the wheel,'' its
founder says, by using corporate-style management to boost learning
like they do profits.
   The school, dedicated Thursday, has gained the blessing and the
backing of such giants of capitalism as McDonald's Corp. and United
Airlines.
   ``It's a compelling plan to educate young people _ not only in
Chicago but across the country,'' McDonald's spokeswoman Stephanie
Skurdy said after the dedication of the Corporate-Community School
on the city's West Side.
   The school will be run like a business _ meaning that if
principal Elaine C. Mosley, a former elementary school principal in
suburban Oak Park, is unable to produce a superior ``product'' _
students _ she could be replaced, said Joe Kellman, the school's
founder.
   The tuition-free school, slated to begin classes Sept. 6 with
150 students and seven teachers, is being subsidized by almost
three dozen sponsors.
   Sixteen of the corporations raised $2 million of the $3 million
needed to run the school for three years, officials said. The
annual cost is about $4,100 per student, about the same as the cost
to educate public school students.
   ``It's a model project, hopeful for urban reform in school
programs,'' said Elaine Younglove, spokeswoman for another sponsor,
United Airlines, which has pledged $300,000 in support over a
three-year period. McDonald's has given $75,000.
   ``We thought it was an opportunity. ... There's a high dropout
rate in Chicago, and that's one of our personal concerns, getting
that dropout rate down,'' she said Thursday night.
   Chicago schools last year were called the nation's worst by U.S.
Education Secretary William J. Bennett, who labeled the city's
educational bureaucracy ``the blob'' and said the system was in
``educational meltdown.''
   Nearly 45 percent of students who began school with the class of
1985 dropped out before graduating, and half of the city's public
high schools ranked in the bottom 1 percent of U.S. schools for
student scores on the American College Test, statistics have shown.
   The Corporate-Community School will try to start students out on
a better foot.
   `We're going to reinvent the wheel,'' said Kellman, 68, head of
the Globe Glass & Mirror Co. and founder of the Better Boys
Foundation. ``We're going to turn out inner city children with a
great education.''
   The first wave of youngsters _ most of them black or Hispanic _
were chosen randomly by computer from 2,000 applications for the
initial pre-school through third grade program. The seven teachers
were selected from 200 applicants from around the nation, said
project director Primus Mootry.
   Classes are to be organized by skill level rather than age, so
slower students are not predisposed to an early image of failure,
organizers said. The curriculum will emphasize basics of reading,
writing, arithmetic and spelling, as well as the development of
social and reasoning skills.
   Mootry said one teacher and one teacher's aid will be assigned
to each class of 25 pupils, and parental involvement will be
encouraged,
   ``The real challenge is to work without some of the constraints
of the public school system,'' which has 430,000 students, Mootry
said.
   Plans call for the school to be expanded over the next several
years to a 300-student facility with classes up to the eighth grade.
   Frank Gardner, Chicago Board of Education president, told
reporters the city's public school system will be watching the new
school carefully.
   ``We applaud this and if we can transfer anything to our
schools, we will take advantage of it,'' he said.
   Charles Ruder, a spokesman for corporate sponsor Sears, Roebuck
& Co., said, ``It is an experiment we thought we ought to be a part
of. ... Communities that we do business in _ it's important that
they be viable, and education is a key to that.''
   Other sponsors include Quaker Oats Co., Baxter International
Inc. and Walgreen Drug Stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
