<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Burma-Leader 1stLd-Writethru   08-19 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Burma-Leader, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0488-90,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Attorney General, A Civilian, Named As Party Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Combines Urgent series.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Maung Maung was named
Friday as chairman of Burma's ruling party, the country's first
civilian leader in 26 years, Japan's Kyodo news service reported
from Rangoon.
   Maung Maung, 63, was picked as chairman at an emergency meeting
of the central committee of the Burma Socialist Program Party, the
agency said.
   The agency quoted the state-run Radio Rangoon.
   Maung Maung is one of only two civilians in the top ranks of the
government hierarchy.
   He is considered a relative moderate, and thought more
acceptable than other figures to Burmese who took to the streets in
waves in the past two weeks to topple hard-line President Sein Lwin
and press demands for an end to a quarter-century of military
dominated, authoritarian rule.
</TEXT>
