<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Briefs,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First-Time Delegates Have Widely Different Goals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former child movie star Shirley Temple Black
said the high point of the Republican National Convention for her
was the floor demonstration for George Bush.
   ``I could have been doing the Shirley Temple Black workout
tape,'' the former actress and first-time California convention
delegate said of the Thursday night event. ``I had a flag in my
teeth, I was ringing a bell and I was up and down dancing, really
jamming, for 25 minutes.''
   Mrs. Black, 60, said her goal was to personally demonstrate her
support for her longtime friend Bush.
   ``I've watched the conventions on television for so many years.
It's much more exciting to be on the floor, but I could see it
better and hear it better back home,'' Mrs. Black said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Romney Says He Didn't Miss Much By Skipping Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Michigan Gov. George Romney says he
didn't miss a thing by skipping a trip to the Republican National
Convention.
   Romney, who himself was a presidential contender in 1968, gave
up his delegate seat to make room in the Michigan contingent for a
supporter of television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   In a telephone interview from Bloomfield Hills, Mich., Romney
said he had no regrets about the decision to stay home.
   ``I'm following the convention and probably I'm seeing more of
it than the people there. And I'm sober,'' he said.
   Since the nomination of George Bush was never in question, the
significance of one delegate's vote was diminished, he said.
   ``There's no decision I would have made anyway,'' Romney said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP National Chairman: Bush `Did What He Had To Do'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Frank
Fahrenkopf Jr. says George Bush ``did what he had to do'' in his
speech accepting the GOP presidential nomination.
   ``It was a tough couple of days, you know. The Quayle thing was
out there and there was a lot of pressure on him,'' Fahrenkopf said
after Bush's speech Thursday night to the Republican National
Convention.
   Questions circulated all day about the military service of
Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, who joined the
National Guard and thereby was out of reach of the draft during the
Vietnam War.
   Fahrenkopf said Bush ``did exactly what we intended to be done,
to draw the distinction between the two candidates, to draw the
distinction between the two parties, and give the American people a
choice.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Flashing Sign Touts Bush, Pans Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathryn McCluskey, an Oregon pre-school
teacher, brought a high-tech visual aide to the Republican National
Convention _ a hand-held, electronic sign board.
   She filled its memory bank with bits and pieces of anti-Dukakis
rhetoric and plugs for Oregon, and held it atop a candy-striped,
eight-foot pole on the convention floor Thursday night.
   The $300 miniature billboard is the type often found in car
rental agencies and the like.
   Some its messages: ``VOTE NO ON DUKAKONOMICS,'' ``FOUR YEARS
UNDER CARTER WERE ENOUGH,'' ``VISIT OREGON THE END OF THE RAINBOW.''
</TEXT>
