<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArtHeist     08-19 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Heist,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$500,000 Heist from Baltimore Art Gallery Termed `Well-Planned'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM LIOTTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at an art gallery say a
``sophisticated'' thief so carefully concealed the removal of
$500,000 in small Asian works during the Asian art curator's
vacation that staffers didn't realize they were gone.
   The curator, Hiram Woodward, discovered upon his return that
some 87 works were stolen during the vacation July 22 to Aug. 13,
said Walters Art Gallery Director Robert P. Bergman, who announced
the theft Thursday.
   Some of the objects had greater historical value to the museum
than monetary value, estimated at $500,000, Bergman said.
   ``Please don't confuse the monetary value with what is important
to us,'' Bergman said. ``Two of the pieces of porcelain were of
such detail and beauty, their thefts are crimes against our
cultural heritage.''
   Among the missing articles is the ``Peach Bloom Vase,'' an
18-inch porcelain vase dating to the 18th century, Bergman said.
   The artifacts were taken from locked Plexiglass cases on the
fourth floor of a separate wing of the museum, and the works that
were left behind were rearranged to prevent detection of the theft,
Bergman said. Staffers and patrons passed the displays without
noticing anything amiss, he added.
   Forty-seven ``major pieces'' of Asian art, primarily porcelain,
and 40 antique Chinese snuff bottles were taken, Bergman said at a
news conference.
   ``It was a very sophisticated and well planned sort of thing. It
was not obvious except to anyone who knows the collection piece by
piece,'' museum spokesman Howard White said.
   Woodward ``was walking around his galleries, as curators will
do, when he noticed pieces missing that he hadn't removed,''
Bergman said. ``He then checked with various departments who might
have removed them. When it was revealed that nobody had taken the
objects, he went back to the cases and it was evident that they had
been tampered with.''
   FBI Special Agent Rosemary Vicini said investigators could not
release any details of the investigation.
   A $100,000 reward has been offered by Lloyd's of London, the
underwriter for the museum's collection, for information that would
solve the theft.
   It was the first major theft at the gallery, which was one of
the greatest private art collections in the world when railroad
magnate Henry Walters bequeathed it to the city upon his death in
1931.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
