<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Protests,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Activists Met With Jeers At Superdome Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay rights activists who staged a
demonstration to seek more federal money to fight AIDS were
denounced by a small group of young Republicans who chanted phrases
such as ``please go quick, you're all going to die.''
   The two sides traded slogans Thursday during a demonstration
outside the Louisiana Superdome, where the Republican National
Convention was held.
   Other protests on the last day of the convention included one
aimed at vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle and another by
Palestinians denouncing Israeli treatment.
   About 40 gay rights activists lined up outside a Superdome
entrance as delegates and guests arrived to hear a speech by GOP
presidential nominee George Bush.
   The demonstrators, many of them members of the New York
City-based group Act Up, carried signs bearing messages such as
``Don't abandon people with AIDS,'' and distributed leaflets.
   A group of about 15 young Republican men and women quickly
gathered and began shouting slogans such as ``please go quick,
you're all going to die'' and ``no equal rights for sodomites.''
   About 15 police officers then lined up between the demonstrators
and the counter-protesters as the gay rights activists shouted
back, ``Act up, fight back, fight AIDS.''
   Some conventioneers laughed as they passed by and many stopped
to take photographs.
   Act Up member Neil Broome of New York City said he held out hope
``there are Republicans who care.''
   Shortly before the AIDS protest, four other demonstrators held
up a 12-foot-long banner with the facetious message: ``Draft
Dodgers for Quayle.''
   Quayle was at the center of controversy Thursday over reports
that he used the influence of others to gain admittance to the
National Guard to avoid serving in Vietnam.
   ``If it's OK for the vice president to buy his way out of duty,
then it's OK for the poor to refuse to fight,'' said John Oswald,
31, of New Orleans.
   After the gay rights demonstration broke up, about 10 people
identifying themselves as Palestinian students gathered outside the
chain-link fence ringing the Superdome.
   A spokesman for the group, who identified himself as Ali Ahmed,
a student at the University of Houston, said the United States
needs to put pressure on the Israelis to end their violent tactics
on the occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</TEXT>
