<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Indians-School     08-19 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indians-School,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Children to Attend Public School of Choice, Official Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's education commissioner says
about 50 Indian schoolchildren can continue to leave their
reservation for public school in another county, where their
families feel they are more welcome.
   ``The students on the Brighton Reservation should be able to
choose,'' Education Commissioner Betty Castor said Thursday after
signing a rule that ended a three-month dispute between two rural
districts hankering for the students.
   The precedent-setting decision came from Tallahassee, the state
capital, because the school districts, Okeechobee and Glades,
failed to reach an agreement. The state has never been called in to
settle a local territorial dispute, Castor said.
   Glades asked Castor to issue a ruling earlier this month as the
end of summer vacation approached. Both counties open schools
Monday.
   Ever since a dispute over what the Seminole tribe said was the
unfair disciplining of an Indian boy at a Glades County school
seven years ago, most families on the reservation have sent their
children 28 miles to Okeechobee Countty.
   They say they feel more welcome and get a better education than
in Glades County, where the reservation is located.
   Glades County, which has the smallest of Florida's 67 school
districts, decided in May it wanted Seminole children on the
reservation to attend school there, at least until the fourth
grade. Enrollment in Glades schools has declined in the last
decade, which means declining revenue.
   Castor said her decision was in the best interest of the
students.
   ``They have traditionally attended Okeechobee (schools), and it
is the clear choice of the students involved and of the Seminole
Indian tribe,'' she said.
   About 140 schoolchildren from the reservation have attended
Okeechobee schools since 1981, while only 20 Brighton youngsters
choose to go to Glades County schools.
   Jim Shore, an attorney for the Florida Seminole tribe, said
Thursday he could not comment on Castor's ruling until the tribe
got official notification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
