<DOCNO> AP880819-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Self-Service     08-19 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Self-Service,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Overturns N.J.'s 39-Year-Old Ban On Self-Service Gas
Stations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's 39-year-old law banning
motorists from pumping their own gas has been overturned by a
Superior Court judge, who said the safety considerations that led
to the law's enactment are now invalid.
   But Judge Martin L. Haines suspended his ruling for six months
to give the Legislature an opportunity to enact regulations
complying with his decision.
   Oregon is the only other state that prohibits self-service
stations.
   Proponents of self-service stations praised the decision, which
was announced Thursday. They said it could help drive down costs at
the pump by decreasing labor expenses.
   ``We're obviously pleased,'' said John F. Holtz, associate
director of the New Jersey Petroleum Council, which represents the
state's largest oil companies. ``We see it as a victory for
consumer freedom of choice.''
   But Jerry Ferrara, executive director of the New Jersey Gasoline
Retailer's Association and Allied Trades Inc., which represents
about 3,000 service stations in New Jersey, said he was
disappointed.
   The trade group said such a decision would lead to service
station layoffs and the closing of gas station repair bays.
   The state Department of Labor has lobbied against changing the
law, citing the possibility of fewer gas station jobs.
   Other opponents said the change would increase profits of
gasoline companies by lowering their labor costs.
   In his six-page opinion, Haines said the law violates the state
constitution because it exceeds the police power of the Legislature.
   Haines' ruling came on a lawsuit filed by Kirschner Brothers Oil
Co. Inc. of Haverford, Pa. The company, which owns about 20 service
stations in New Jersey, claimed the law is antiquated and that
customers ought to have a choice between self- and full-service.
   The 1949 statute, enacted primarily as a safety measure, was
affirmed by the state Supreme Court in 1952. Legislators who passed
the law were concerned that motorists would be in danger if they
pumped their own gas.
   Opponents of self-service stations cite newspaper reports of
fires and other accidents that have injured or killed motorists who
were trying to pump their own gas as evidence why the statute
should remain.
   Haines ruled June 29 that he couldn't overturn a law affirmed by
a higher court. But Kirschner asked that he reconsider, and, in his
latest ruling, Haines agreed.
   ``The principle is that a lower court is bound by precedent. In
this case, it does not apply because the facts have changed,'' the
judge said.
   Haines decided that safety is no longer an issue and that that
allows him to reverse his earlier ruling and overturn the state
Supreme Court's affirmation.
   ``The testimony before me revealed very different facts _
self-service stations are at least as safe as full-service
stations,'' Haines said in a telephone interview.
   The lawsuit was filed against the Labor Department, which was
represented by the attorney general's office. Becky Taylor, a
spokeswoman for Attorney General Cary Edwards, said the office had
not determined whether it would appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
