<1ST_LINE>r i PM-South-WestAfrica     08-19 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South-West Africa,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buerrilla Leader Conciliatory Toward South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the guerrilla
movement seeking independence for South-West Africa says he
believes South Africa is sincerely committed to ending its rule
over the territory.
   Sam Nujoma, president of the South-West African People's
Organization, made his comments in an interview with the Argus News
Service published Thursday in the South African company's
newspapers.
   SWAPO has been fighting since 1966 for independence in
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia. South Africa announced
earlier this month that it would begin implementation of a U.N.
independence plan for Namibia if agreement was reached on
withdrawal of Cuban troops from neighboring Angola.
   Nujoma was quoted as saying his guerrillas will observe a
cease-fire in Namibia starting Sept. 1 and thereafter will fight
only in self-defense.
   ``Let us believe that this time, the South African government is
serious,'' he reportedly said.
   According to the report, Nujoma made a major concession by
saying SWAPO would not delay the peace process by insisting that an
independent Namibia take possession of Walvis Bay, a South African
enclave which is only major port serving the territory.
   Nujoma also was quoted as saying he would not allow the African
National Congress, the main guerrilla movement fighting for
black-majority rule in South Africa, to maintain bases in Namibia.
   SWAPO is widely considered the likely winner of independence
elections envisioned under the U.N. independence plan.
   Nujoma, interviewed in Zambia, was quoted as saying a SWAPO
government might adopt a one-party socialist system if there was
sufficient public backing. But he reportedly said there would not
be sweeping expropriation of private property.
   South African President P.W. Botha, in a policy speech Thursday,
endorsed the peace initiative but said his government would insist
that the United Nations prove its impartiality before independence
elections could proceed in Namibia.
</TEXT>
