<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Marcos 2ndLd-Writethru a0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0538,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Says He Will Ask To Come Home To Defend Self</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``Justice Augusto...'' with one graf to UPDATE
with Solicitor-General saying Marcos' presence not necessary.
Pickup 6th graf pvs ``Maros told...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ferdinand Marcos
said today he will ask to come home to defend himself when a former
government minister testifies against him about the awarding of
allegedly questionable contracts.
   On Thursday, an anti-graft court ruled that the ousted president
had the right to be present when former public works secretary
Baltazar Aquino _ who is not related to President Corazon Aquino _
gives his deposition.
   The hearing Nov. 7 is not a trial but a ``perpetuation
proceeding'' to take testimony from Aquino, who court officials say
is gravely ill.
   Aquino is to testify about allegedly questionable contracts
granted to firms during Marcos' 20-year reign. Under Philippine
law, his testimony can be used against Marcos at a future trial,
even if the former secretary is dead.
   Justice Augusto Amores said Marcos could appear personally or be
represented by counsel and would have the right to cross-examine
Aquino. Solicitor-General Francisco Chavez said his office believed
``that his (Marcos) personal presence is not necessary'' during the
hearing.
   Marcos told reporters by telephone from Hawaii, where he lives
in exile, that he had not been informed officially of the Thursday
ruling.
   ``I directed my lawyer to seek the court order for me to come
home and defend myself in the proceedings. I want to represent
myself,'' said Marcos, who is a lawyer.
   Marcos has lived in Hawaii since his ouster in a 1986
civilian-military uprising. Mrs. Aquino has refused to let him
return, citing security concerns.
   But a spokesman for Mrs. Aquino quoted her as saying she would
``respect the decision of the court,'' even if it meant allowing
Marcos to come home.
   The court said Marcos had the constitutional right to appear
during the proceedings ``which cannot be denied to him in the
absence of more cogent reasons.''
   Marcos has never been formally charged with any criminal
offense, despite allegations of wrongdoing during his time in
office. Marcos has previously warned he would dismiss his lawyer,
Rafael Recto, and demand the right to represent himself if any
criminal charges were filed.
   In Thursday's ruling, the court authorized the Philippine consul
in Honolulu to serve notice of the proceedings to Marcos and to
publish the announcement in newspapers there for three consecutive
weeks.
   Marcos told Manila reporters that his former minister had been
pressured into agreeing to testify because of his poor health.
   Last May, Mrs. Aquino turned down a request by Marcos to return
here for the burial of his mother, Josefa, who died May 4.
   The body of Marcos' mother remains unburied as his supporters
agitate for the former president's return. Marcos said his mother's
burial would be ``my first duty'' after his return.
</TEXT>
