<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     08-19 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Businessman Puts Down $1 Million Deposit on PTL's Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian businessman seeking to buy the
PTL ministry's assets has put down $1 million toward the $113
million deal.
   ``The only reason Peter Thomas won't own it is if somebody comes
in with a higher offer,'' Thomas said Thursday.
   Earlier this month, he and PTL trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton
signed an agreement giving Thomas until Sept. 16 to decide whether
he wanted the assets. Those include the PTL satellite TV network
and the Heritage USA Christian retreat near Fort Mill, S.C.
   ``By Sept. 1, it's either a deal or it's not a deal,'' Thomas
said. ``I'm going back to Canada ... I'll be back down here when I
get a call from the trustee saying that my offer's been accepted.''
   Thomas did not elaborate on the conditions he had sought.
   Benton has set a Sept. 1 deadline to receive offers. So far,
Charlotte businessman George Shinn and deposed PTL leader Jim
Bakker have said they plan to submit bids, although Shinn said this
week he might change his mind.
   Next, Benton would recommend a proposal for U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Rufus Reynolds' approval. PTL must sell its assets to pay
debts, which might be as much as $130 million.
   PTL has been in bankruptcy proceedings since June 1987. In March
1987, Bakker resigned as PTL's president in a sex-and-money scandal.
   Thomas is offering $46 million in cash, including the $1 million
deposit, with the rest financed over five years.
   Pending court approval of Thomas's offer, PTL will pay him
interest on his $1 million at the prime interest rate, plus 2
percentage points. Currently, that totals 12 percent.
   If Thomas canceled his offer, the $1 million would become a
six-month loan to PTL at the same interest rate.
</TEXT>
