<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-US,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Stops in Cairo, Coveys Reagan Message to Mubarak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan sent a message to President
Hosni Mubarak reaffirming the U.S. commitment to help achieve an
overall Arab-Israeli peace settlement, a senior Egyptian official
said today.
   Osama el-Baz, Mubarak's top political adviser, said the message
was brought by Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who stopped in
Cairo today on his way to Pakistan. Shultz spent 70 minutes at
Cairo International Airport, where el-Baz met him. The two men
talked in the airport's VIP lounge.
   ``Mr. Shultz asked me to convey to President Mubarak a verbal
message from President Reagan stating the commitment of the United
States to press ahead with efforts to bring a comprehensive and
just peace to the (Middle East) region,'' el-Baz told reporters
after Shultz left for Pakistan.
   Since mediating the 1979 Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty, the
United States has been trying without success to initiate
Arab-Israeli negotiations on an overall settlement.
   Shultz made four trips to the Middle East this year but failed
to win acceptance of a U.S. peace proposal. The plan called for an
international conference as an opening to direct Arab-Israeli talks.
   The secretary, who will represent Reagan at Saturday's funeral
of Pakistani President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, made no statements
after meeting with el-Baz.
   In addition to the Arab-Israeli conflict, el-Baz said he and
Shultz also discussed the situation in Lebanon and efforts to end
the Iran-Iraq war.
   A U.N.-supervised, cease-fire between the two warring countries
is to go into effect at dawn Saturday.
</TEXT>
