<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0553,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Official Says He's Sure Crash Was Sabotage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with government official
discounting speculation on cause, Zia's grave dug. Pickup 9th graf
pvs, ``Rumors about...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government minister said today that
sabotage was almost certainly the cause of a fiery plane crash that
killed President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq and U.S. Ambassador Arnold
Raphel.
   But a government information officer discounted all speculation
on the cause of the explosion and crash, which also killed 28
others.
   The country, meanwhile, was preparing for Zia's funeral,
scheduled Saturday at the world's largest mosque, Faisal Masjid. A
grave was dug for him today on the lawn in front of the mosque.
   Across the border in India, authorities lifted curfews in two
towns on the India-Pakistan border after police clashed with
Moslems protesting Zia's death.
   India, which is mainly Hindu, and Pakistan, which is Moslem, are
long-time adversaries and have fought three wars since they both
gained independence from Britain in 1947.
   Police and paramiltary forces continued to enforce a curfew in
the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir, a strategic state claimed
by both countries, officials said. Many Moslems in the region
support the Pakistani claim and admired Zia, who earlier this year
put his country under Islamic law.
   Security forces today fired warning shots in the air to disperse
crowds that violated the restrictions, but no one was hurt, they
said. On Thursday, police killed four Moslems and wounded more than
100 others trying to set fire to Hindu homes, shops and temples.
   Pakistan's minister of communications and railways, Aslam
Khattak, told reporters that sabotage was ``a 1,000 percent
certainty'' as the cause of the military transport plane crash. He
did not elaborate.
   But a government information officer, speaking on condition of
anonymity, discounted all speculation on the cause, including a
newspaper report that a time bomb was hidden in a basket of mangoes
aboard the plane. ``Nothing is known yet,'' he said. ``The
investigators are still at the scene.''
   ``Rumors About Blast Cause'' was the headline in the
English-language opposition daily, The Muslim. ``All sorts of
reports and rumors are circulating in the federal capital in the
absence of an authentic official regarding the crash,'' it wrote.
   The moderate non-government daily, The Nation, asked in a
front-page headline, ``Who eliminated Zia and why?'' It said
unnamed civilian aviation experts ``surmise'' there must have been
an explosive device aboard because the C-130 is known as a sturdy,
reliable aircraft.
   The protocol section of the Foreign Ministry was arranging to
receive dozens of foreign dignitaries, including U.S. Secretary of
State George Shultz and Indian President R. Venkataram.
   The Faisal Masjid mosque, at the foot of the hills that overlook
the tree-lined federal capital, can hold more than 10,000 people in
its prayer hall and 200,000 on its grounds.
   The U.S. Embassy said today that a team of American
investigators would arrive at Bahawalpur, 330 miles south of
Islamabad, to help investigate the air crash that claimed the lives
of 30 people, including most of Pakistan's top military brass.
   Acting President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, the former Senate chairman,
has said he would not rule out sabotage but would await a report
from investigators.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said the body of Raphel and U.S.
defense representative Brig. Gen. Herbert Wassom, who was also
killed in the crash, would be flown Saturday to the United States
for burial.
   The White House announced Thursday night the appointment of
Robert Oakley, a National Security Council adviser on South Asia,
as new U.S. ambassador to Pakistan.
</TEXT>
