<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StandandDeliver     08-19 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stand and Deliver,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film Blamed For Falling Test Scores At East L.A. Garfield' High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College placement scores dropped sharply for
calculus students at the school featured in ``Stand and Deliver,''
as the youths apparently learned a different lesson _ real life is
tougher than the movies.
   Fifty-five of the 119 James A. Garfield High School students who
took the rigorous mathematics exam in May received a passing score
of three or higher on a scale of one to five, according to College
Board figures, which Garfield Principal Maria Elena Tostado
provided Thursday. That represents a passing rate of 46 percent,
down from 65 percent last year, when 84 of 129 students passed.
   The students' celebrated instructor, Bolivian-born Jaime
Escalante, was visiting relatives and promoting the movie in his
native land and could not be reached for comment on the test
scores. But Ms. Tostado said he blamed the lower pass rate on the
movie.
   ``He said the kids saw the movie so many times they thought
passing the test was going to be as easy as the movie made it out
to be,'' she explained. ``He said they didn't know it was so much
hard work.''
   In a recent interview with the Los Angeles Times, Escalante said
constant interruptions by visitors _ including Vice President
George Bush and his wife, Barbara _ were distracting and that ``the
kids are paying for it.''
   Harlan Hanson, director of the advanced placement program for
the College Board, said Garfield students still did exceptionally
well compared to students in other schools across the nation.
   The school, which serves a poor East Los Angeles community where
few parents have college educations, ranked sixth in the nation
among all schools that had passing scores on the beginning calculus
exam and 59th among schools that had passing marks on the advanced
calculus test.
   ``That's 59th out of several thousand,'' Hanson said. ``That is
by no means anything to be ashamed of. What they've got going is
great.''
   The Warner Bros. film, starring Edward James Olmos as Escalante,
told the story of the instructor's success in teaching calculus to
average students at Garfield in 1982 and their triumph over
accusations that they cheated on the advanced placement exam.
   A passing score on the exam entitles a student to college credit
at most universities.
</TEXT>
