<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IrishStowaway     08-19 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish Stowaway,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Sailors To Be Court-Martialed in Stowaway Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four sailors will be court-martialed and
four others face lesser punishment for their alleged roles in
helping an Irish teen-ager stow away aboard the destroyer Conyngham
last month, the Navy said.
   The charges involve Suzanne Twomey, 16, of Cork, Ireland, who
spent 10 days hidden aboard the warship in July.
   The Navy identified the four sailors who face court martial
Thursday.
   Seaman Apprentice David G. Peters is charged with conspiracy,
making a false official statement and bringing in and harboring an
alien. Seaman Apprentice Paul D. Davidson, Petty Officer 3rd Class
Donald L. Nichols and Seaman Anthony M. Drady are charged with
conspiracy, failure to report an offense, and bringing in and
harboring an alien.
   If convicted, the men could face up to six months in the brig,
forfeiture of two-thirds pay for six months, reduction in rate to
the lowest pay grade, and a bad-conduct discharge. The Navy said
all four courts-martial are expected to be in October.
   Citing federal Privacy Act provisions, the Navy did not identify
the other four sailors. They will face a non-judicial disciplinary
procedure in which the commanding officer of a naval unit disposes
of charges against enlisted men. If convicted, they could be
sentenced to 45 days of restriction and extra duty, reduction in
rank by one pay grade and forfeiture of half pay for two months.
   Miss Twomey was discovered July 22, one day before the ship
arrived in Norfolk, in a 2{-foot-wide, 15-foot-long, 3-foot-high
compartment above a refrigeration unit that contained electrical
wiring and pipes. She had been moved from a larger fan room where
she had spent most of her voyage, relying on crew members to bring
her food.
   She was deported back to Ireland to a facility for juveniles.
</TEXT>
