<2ND_LINE>PM-Home Delivery,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Delivers Baby By Recalling Colleague's Tale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLYOKE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse's description of about how he
delivered a baby on an airplane, with a practical assist from the
liquor cabinet, came in handy for a colleague whose pregnant wife
suddenly went into labor.
   Hospital orderly Fred Rosario delivered his baby Tuesday using
techniques he had heard the nurse describing the day before,
including sterilizing his hands with vodka.
   ``Quite honestly, I didn't know Fred was listening that
closely,'' said his colleague, Joe Alvernaz.
   Alvernaz, a nurse at Holyoke Hospital, had told his co-workers
Monday about the delivery the previous night aboard a flight from
the Azores. He described how he sterilized his hands and scissors
with gin and vodka and assisted while a doctor delivered a baby.
   Rosario went home and told the story to his wife, Cheryl.
   ``I told him `Don't worry, I'm not going to make you go through
that,''' she recalled.
   The next morning, however, she went into labor. ``My wife said,
`Fred, the baby's right there,''' Rosario said.
   A neighbor called paramedics while Rosario sterilized his hands
with a pint of vodka and used shoelaces to tie the umbilical cord,
as Alvernaz had done.
   Then he passed out. ``I sat on the couch, closed my eyes, and
the paramedics were there,'' he said.
   He and his wife named their 5-pound, 6-ounce baby Sarah
``because it means `fast,''' he said.
</TEXT>
