<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burundi-Massacre     08-19 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burundi-Massacre,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands Reported Killed In Ethnic Violence In Burundi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people were killed in the
central African nation of Burundi in ethnic clashes this week
before the army restored order, diplomats and opposition leaders
said.
   The government imposed emergency rules to prevent further
clashes.
   The fighting was between the Hutu, Burundi's majority tribe, and
the Tutsi, the minority tribe that controls the military and rules
the country.
   After an abortive coup attempt in 1972 in the former Belgian
colony, the Tutsi massacred 100,000 Hutu.
   More than 7,000 Burudians fled into neighboring Rwanda to escape
the killing this week, said Western diplomats in Rwanda. The
diplomats quoted refugees from both tribes as saying thousands were
killed.
   The government-owned radio, monitored in Nairobi, said today
that the most recent trouble began Sunday in the northern villages
of Marangara and Ntega.
   ``Some inhabitants of northern Burundi belonging to the minority
Tutsi tribe were killed in a selective manner,'' the radio said
without elaboration. It said an overnight curfew was imposed
throughout the country.
   The emergency order also prohibits throughout the country
meetings of more than five people without government permission, it
said. The order was signed by Maj. Pierre Buyoya, a Tutsi who took
power in a bloodless coup in September.
   Astere Nzisabira, Burundi's ambassador to Belgium, said in a
radio and television interview Thursday in Brussels:
   ``We suspect that some former Hutu refugees infiltrated the
country from some foreign countries. They incited the Hutu
population and called on them to massacre the Tutsi population.''
   In an attack on one area in northern Burundia on Sunday, ``they
massacred all the Tutsis,'' he said. He did not provide figures or
name the area.
   ``The authorities then intervened in a peaceful manner,''
Nzisabira said. ``But the following day, the murders resumed in
full swing. At that stage, the army had to intervene and restore
peace to the country.'' When asked if there were 400 victims, he
said the estimate was much too low.
   The Hutu People Liberation Party, a movement of exiled
government opponents, accused the military of massacring Hutus.
   ``There are thousands of Hutus corpses, the victims of Tutsi
soldiers, floating in Lake Tanganyika,'' the opposition group said.
There was no way to confirm the claim independently.
   Burundi, with nearly 5 million people crammed into an area about
the size of Maryland, is one of Africa's most densely populated
countries. About 85 percent of its people belong to the Hutu tribe,
while the rest are Tutsis.
   Since independence from Belgium in 1962, Burundi has been
wracked by protracted factional and ethnic struggles.
   For generations, the tall, lanky Tutsi held the short, stocky
Hutu in feudal serfdom. This led to one of the worst ethnic
slaughters in independent Africa.
   In April 1972, the Hutu tried to overthrow the government. The
coup was suppressed and the Tutsi retailiated by systematically
killing 100,000 Hutu, including most of the tribe's intelligentsia.
   In 1976, Col. Jean-Baptiste Bagaza staged a bloodless coup
ousting Michel Micombero, who had sanctioned the Hutu slaughter.
   Bagaza, like Micombero, was a Tutsi. Bagaza was overthrown Sept.
4, 1987, by Buyoya, who came to power vowing to end ethnic
differences.
</TEXT>
