<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     08-19 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Observers Take Border Positions; Iran Says Iraq May Not Want
Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. military observers took up positions
today along the Iran-Iraq border on the eve of a scheduled
cease-fire, and Iran's military leader warned that Iraq may not
really want peace.
   ``We are facing two paths, war and peace. We chose peace but we
are not sure about Iraq,'' said Hashemi Rafsanjani, acting
commander in chief of Iran's army as well as Parliament speaker.
   Rafsanjani spoke at a weekly prayer sermon at Tehran University.
His remarks were carried by official Tehran radio, monitored in
Nicosia.
   The Iranian leader warned that ``if the enemy wants to continue
the war, it will continue much more seriously.''
   U.N. observers, meanwhile, were deployed along the 730-mile
border between the two countries, ready to start monitoring when a
cease-fire goes into effect just after dawn Saturday in the
8-year-old war.
   ``Ninety-five percent of them are on the ground, and we're
receiving excellent cooperation from both sides,'' said a source in
the U.N. secretariat's office in New York. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   In Baghdad, U.N. officials said more than 100 observers were
deployed ``steadily and smoothly'' along the Iraqi border.
   Brig. Gen. V.M. Patil of India is to head the group of 150 U.N.
observers in Iraq while an Irish officer will head the group in
Iran. A Yugoslav officer, Gen. Slavko Jovic, will command the
entire operation, traveling between the two countries.
   The gulf peacekeeping force totals about 1,300 military and
civilian personnel, of whom 350 are unarmed military observers from
24 countries. The United Nations has budgeted $74 million for the
mission.
   On Thursday, the foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq are to meet
in Geneva for U.N.-sponsored talks mediated by Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   The official Iraqi News Agency announced today that Basra
International Airport will be inaugurated Saturday. The report was
monitored in Nicosia.
   Basra, Iraq's second largest city and its major port,
experienced some of the heaviest fighting in the Persian Gulf war.
The city suffered extensive damage and its airport has been closed
since the beginning of the fighting.
   The city is just 20 miles from the border, in an air corridor so
sensitive that Jovic, head of the U.N. observers, flew from Baghdad
to Tehran via Turkey.
</TEXT>
