<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     08-19 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspapers Blame U.S. For Blocking Syrian-backed Presidential
Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese newspapers today blamed
differences between the United States and Syria for preventing
Parliament from electing a pro-Syrian president.
   Also today, Syrian troops defused a car bomb near the Central
Bank office in Moslem west Beirut 10 minutes before the device was
set to explode, police reported. A police spokesman said the car
was packed with 33 pounds of explosives and parked in a gas station.
   The car bomb was the second found in the past two days in
Beirut. On Thursday, the Syrians defused another car rigged with
110 pounds of explosives in south Beirut's neighborhood of
Maamoura, the spokesman said.
   Beirut's independent daily An-Nahar said Parliament failed to
muster the quorum for the expected election of Suleiman Franjieh on
Thursday due to the ``United States' stand opposing the election of
a confrontational candidate.''
   The leftist As-Safir newspaper said the first round of
presidential elections ``fell by the American knockout strike.''
   An-Nahar, in an editorial, blamed differences between U.S. and
Syrian officials, calling the outcome in Washington's favor, ``not
because it opposes Syria's role in Lebanon, but because it objects
to the character of challenge that overwhelmed the elections
process.''
   The United States expressed regret Thursday at the failure to
elect a president and attributed it to the lack of a ``consensus
candidate.''
   Hard-line Christians opposed to Syria's role in Lebanon headed
off the expected election of Franjieh, a 78-year-old Maronite
Catholic, by preventing the required quorum for the vote. Only 38
representatives showed up for the session. Quorum for electing a
new president was set at 51 members.
   A ranking police officer said the Christian Lebanese Forces
militia on Thursday held some deputies and told others living in
Christian areas of the country they could not attend the meeting.
He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Lebanese Forces, headed by Samir Geagea, opposes Franjieh,
who was Lebanon's president from 1970 to 1976. Franjieh blames
Geagea for leading a 1978 raid that killed his eldest son,
daughter-in-law and 3-year-old granddaughter.
   Franjieh, Syria's closest Christian ally in Lebanon, repeatedly
has vowed revenge. Syria is the main powerbroker in Lebanon with
40,000 troops in eastern and northern provinces as well as west and
south Beirut.
   ``The election of Franjieh as president is the death sentence to
the Lebanese Forces,'' said a Paliament member, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   In Jerusalem, Israel radio reported Lebanese Christian and
non-Christian leaders appealed to Israel to intervene in the
elections, but Israel said it would not. The report quoted Uri
Lubrani, the Defense Ministry coordinator of Israeli policy in
Lebanon. It did not specify what type of intervention was requested
or specify who made the appeal.
   According to Lebanon's Constitution, a president should be
elected in two months before President Amin Gemayel's six-year term
ends Sept. 23.
   No new election date has been set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
