<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Hostage's Sister Protests New Demands of Captors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with newspaper saying British hostages
will be freed and ADD background on British hostages. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of American hostage Terry
Anderson protested new demands outlined by the captors of her
brother and called them unreasonable in a statement published today.
   Also today, the Beirut weekly Ash-Shiraa said the release of the
British hostages was imminent but said the release of other
hostages would take more time. The report, quoting an unidentified
west Beirut leader, said two separate negotiations to free the
hostages are under way.
   The report in Ash-Shiraa, which broke the story of U.S. secret
arms sale to Iran in November 1986, could not be independently
verified. Many of its previous stories about the hostages have not
been accurate.
   It said the kidnappers sought money and ``and at the same time
economic, military and political conditions set by Iran.'' It did
not elaborate.
   Peggy Say, Anderson's sister, said, ``I think it is grossly
unjust for you to hold Terry Anderson for ransom that includes what
amounts to a complete peace settlement in the entire region and the
end of centuries' old hostilities.'' The text of Mrs. Say's message
was published by Beirut's two leading newspapers, An-Nahar and
As-Safir.
   ``In the past three and a half years, I have tried my very best
to pressure my government to negotiate for Terry's release and the
release of the other hostages,'' Mrs. Say wrote.
   ``You have now presented new demands which are impossible for me
to put forth to my government,'' wrote Mrs. Say, who lives in
Kentucky.
   Anderson, 40, is the chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press and has been held longer than any of the 18
foreign hostages in Lebanon. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, which holds
Anderson and American hostage Thomas Sutherland, released a
statement Thursday that set four demands for the release of the
captives.
   Two of the demands were new: the unconditional withdrawal of all
the Israeli forces and their Christian militia allies from south
Lebanon, and U.S. compensation and aid for the reconstruction of
war-ravaged south Lebanon and Beirut.
   The group also demanded the release of all Lebanese and
Palestinian ``mujahedeen,'' or holy warriors, from prisons in
Christian east Beirut as well as in Israel and Israel's
self-designated security zone in Lebanon. Israel and allied
militiamen of the South Lebanon Army control a 10-mile-deep enclave
in south Lebanon to guard against cross-border guerrilla forays.
   Unlike many of its previous communications, the Shiite Moslem
faction did not specifically ask for the release of 17 suspects
held in Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and French embassies in 1983.
But the sweeping statement about prisoners seemed to incorporate
this demand.
   Islamic Jihad has admitted holding Anderson and Sutherland, 56,
acting dean of agriculture at the American University of Beirut.
Sutherland, of Fort Collins, Colo., was abducted June 9, 1985.
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals held by
pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists _ Anglican church envoy Terry
Waite, journalist John McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan, a Belfast
man with dual British and Irish nationality whose release is also
sought by the Irish government.
   The Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a
New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors claim
they killed him. His body was never found.
</TEXT>
