<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WomanSentenced     08-19 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Woman Sentenced,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Sentenced for Killing A Second Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was convicted of voluntary
manslaughter for shooting to death her second husband, 20 years
after she admitted shooting to death her first husband.
   A jury deliberated two hours Wednesday before convicting Hazel
Allison, 47, in the Jan. 11 shotgun death of Eddie Boyd Allison,
47, her husband of 17 years.
   Mrs. Allison, of Clover, had testified that she had been abused
by Allison and shot him in self-defense.
   Judge Hubert Long sentenced the woman to 30 years in prison, the
maximum sentence. She must serve at least 10 years before becoming
eligible for parole.
   Jurors, who could have found Mrs. Allison guilty of murder,
seemed stunned to learn after issuing their verdict that Mrs.
Allison had killed her first husband, Billy Byers Johnson, in 1968.
   ``We all had a feeling that something was being held back, but
we didn't know what it was,'' The Herald of Rock Hill quoted an
unidentified juror as saying.
   Long explained that Mrs. Allison's history was withheld during
the trial because of state trial rules limiting the use of prior
criminal records.
   Deputy Solicitor Larry Grant said Mrs. Allison pleaded guilty to
manslaughter in the 1968 case. She was sentenced to a two-year
suspended prison term and placed on probation for three years.
   She claimed self-defense that time also, Grant said. In both
cases, she said she and her husband had begun arguing after the man
returned home from hunting, and that she then shot him.
   In offering mitigating circumstances to justify a lower
sentence, Assistant Public Defender Roberta Wright commented, ``She
is, of course, a widow.''She also argued that Mrs. Allison
``suffered a series of physical blows, of physical abuse.''
   Grant, however, argued that Mrs. Allison gave ``no warning,
none, didn't say a word, just shot him'' _ and therefore was
disqualified from a self-defense acquittal.
</TEXT>
