<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0581 08-19 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0581,750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with Bentsen quotes; picks up 9th graf pvs,
Dukakis and Bentsen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen
said today that Republicans put on a convention for the far right
in New Orleans, ``a Mardi Gras for the Moral Majority.''
   ``The hard right drove the Republican agenda,'' Bentsen told a
news conference as he neared the end of a nine-day campaign trip to
his home state, where he planned to welcome running mate Michael
Dukakis tonight to the Texas hustings.
   ``What we saw was the Republicans putting on a convention for
the far right,'' Bentsen said. ``They had a Mardi Gras for the
Moral Majority.''
   Bentsen was asked about a report in today's Washington Post that
his blind trust invested in his son's business after being steered
there by the senator.
   He said he reported the trust's investment in his son's company.
``Frankly, I didn't have to report it,'' Bentsen said.
   He said his wife's position as a trustee on a mutual fund
affiliated with the manager of his trust in no way compromised the
blind trust. ``No, not at all, absolutely not,'' he said.
   He said his wife was one of the directors representing the
stockholders and not the management. ``It's almost an adversarial
relationship,'' he said.
   Bentsen told reporters his blind trust was approved by the
Senate Ethics Committee.
   Earlier, Bentsen's spokesman, Jack DeVore, said the trust was
handled properly and the senator did not know about the son's
investment until after it was done.
   Bentsen began the day by contrasting his running mate with the
opposition ticket of Bush and Dan Quayle.
   ``Mike Dukakis has reached out to the center and he is saying to
Democrats who voted for Ronald Reagan, `come home','' Bentsen said
in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America''.
   He said ``I thought George Bush had a well-crafted speech and
that he did a good job delivering it.'' But, he said, Bush did not
note that the national debt and the trade deficit have soared
during the eight years of the Reagan administration, evidence of
what Bentsen called a ``credit-card mentality.''
   Dukakis and Bentsen arranged to meet here tonight for a
fund-raiser and then visit the LBJ ranch and President Johnson's
widow, Lady Bird, on Saturday. The joint appearances were designed
to underline the importance Democrats place on the Lone Star state,
which Bush also claims as home.
   Bentsen flew to Texas a week ago and has been criss-crossing the
state on behalf of Dukakis, selling the ticket to skeptical Texans,
most of whom are more conservative than the Massachusetts governor.
   The Texas senator planned to continue that effort today before
supporters in Wichita Falls and during a visit to a Texas
Instruments plant in Sherman before returning at day's end to
Dallas.
   Bentsen began Thursday in Tyler in East Texas, explaining to his
long-time Senate supporters why he was seeking both re-election to
that seat and the vice presidency.
   He met in Kilgore with oilmen, a conservative group, and
promised that he would continue to fight for them in Washington as
vice president with the same verve as he has in the Senate.
   He also spoke before the East Texas Regional Development Group,
an audience of more than 500 businessmen and women, mostly
Republican.
   ``They were attentive and they were polite. I think we made some
headway,'' he said after the appearance. To win Texas' 29 electoral
votes, Bentsen says, Democrats who voted for Reagan must ``come
home to the Democratic Party.''
   When he flew to Dallas at day's end, Bentsen met the other end
of the political spectrum _ one that might find him a tad too
conservative. Both Bentsen and the Jesse Jackson supporters he
talked with said they were pleased with the encounter.
   ``It went quite well,'' Bentsen said. Although problems
remained, ``In campaigns, there are always those things. We did
very well.''
   John Wiley Price, a Dallas county commissioner and a Jackson
supporter who walked out of the Democrats' convention in Atlanta,
said Bentsen went a long way toward alleviating his concerns about
black participation in the campaign and bringing him on the
bandwagon.
   ``Sen. Bentsen agreed they can't win without Jackson, so he is
going to make sure these needs are going to be discussed,'' Price
said.
   Bentsen planned to leave Texas on Saturday, flying to Florida
for a Democratic Party dinner before returning to Washington.
</TEXT>
