<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GOP-RisingStars Bjt   08-19 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP-Rising Stars, Bjt,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winners, Losers Emerge From Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were relegated to supporting roles, but
some lesser known Republican faces were given convention exposure
this week and can be counted among the party's leaders for the
future.
   Names like Phil Gramm, who described himself as doing ``the
Lord's work in the devil's city.'' And Olympia Snowe, who wielded
the gavel with humor and aplomb. And Tom Kean, who scored the
Democrats for ``pastel patriotism.''
   Political conventions are expected to make and end political
careers, and this one made Dan Quayle what George Bush said he was:
one of the party's ``rising young stars.''
   Unless, that is, he proves to be a shooting star.
   If Quayle meets the challenge of his lofty new role, the young
and conservative junior senator from Indiana may pose a roadblock
for some of the party's other aspirants to the mantle of Ronald
Reagan.
   But while Quayle was battling to prove his worthiness against a
barrage of questions about his military record and experience, some
Republicans who were passed over for the vice presidential
nomination can already be counted among the winners and losers of
the convention.
   Gramm, the Texas senator who only five years ago was a Democrat
and is widely assumed to have presidential aspirations, is a
possible inheritor of leadership of the Republicans' right wing.
   He was given a prominent spot at the convention, delivering the
speech that placed Bush's name in nomination. Gramm did a credible
job, delivered some good lines _ and avoided the pitfall of
Democratic nominator Bill Clinton, the Arkansas governor who talked
on and on in introducing Michael Dukakis.
   Kean, the New Jersey governor and convention keynoter, had to
contend with a minor protest by Republican ideologues who objected
to such a prominent role being given to someone who didn't share
their opposition to abortion.
   Kean preaches what is called the politics of inclusion, and
bringing minorities into the party. In Republican Party politics,
his future depends in part on the party's willingness to accept
moderates.
   ``I thought Tom Kean did a good job,'' said Dan Casey, executive
director of the American Conservative Union, a conservative
organization. ``There was no down side at all.''
   Kean battles an image problem that results from an aristocrat's
accent. But he told a Superdome filled largely with affluent whites
that the party of Abraham Lincoln must reach out to the
``ill-schooled, ill-trained or ill-housed.''
   Snowe, the Maine congresswoman, was part of a parade of
Republicans afforded a moment on the platform. She demonstrated
that the party has a bench deep with potential leaders.
   John McCain brought the convention crowd to its feet for the
first standing ovation of the convention. A first-term senator from
Arizona who is solid with the party's conservative wing, McCain
recalled his 5{ years spent in a North Vietnamese prison.
   Pat Robertson, who as a candidate never lived up to the
expectations some had for his ``religious right'' movement, gave a
ho-hum speech. But he helped himself among the party's
establishment by maintaining a low profile and playing the good
soldier.
   Some who were passed over for the vice presidential nomination
looked like winners just because they were considered: Sen. Pete
Dominici of New Mexico, who has pushed his party to deal with the
deficit, and Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming, whose selection likely
would have angered conservatives.
   The convention had its losers, too.
   Jack Kemp is the most obvious. The New York congressman spent
eight years running for president and lobbied hard to become Bush's
running mate. Now he is giving up his congressional seat.
   ``We believe with all our hearts that there is a role to play
for Jack Kemp and our ideas in the future of the Republican
Party,'' Kemp said. Others aren't so sure.
   Bill Bennett, former Education secretary and a big draw on the
GOP fund-raising circuit, gave a flat speech in a monotone that the
delegates barely listened to.
   Former U.N. Secretary Jeane Kirkpatrick, who electrified the
1984 GOP convention by condemning ``the San Francisco Democrats,''
stuck to her style. But her words seemed to get lost in the
cavernous superdome.
   Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas gave a crowd-pleasing speech. But his
remarks about the vice presidential selection process _ while he
was being selected out _ sounded sour. Dole complained that the
selection process, in which the Bush campaign tried to heighten
suspense by keeping the nominee's name secret, was demeaning.
   The Superdome, where the convention was held, itself was a
loser. All were delighted at the spacious accommodations _ until
the convention began. On television it was fine, but inside
delegates could hardly hear. So much for conventions on football
fields.
   And there was another loser: Atlanta.
   Yes, the Republican convention was mostly dull. But New Orleans
can throw a party that the Democrats, who met a month ago in
Georgia, could only imagine.
</TEXT>
