<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionCity     08-19 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention City,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Should Benefit From GOP Convention For 20 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Orleans let the good times roll when the
Republican National Convention came to town, and it should reap the
benefits of a week of national exposure for 20 years, local
officials said.
   ``New Orleans has never looked better, Louisiana has never
looked brighter,'' said Jim Bob Moffett, head o the Fortune 500
company Freeport-McMoRan, and a key convention fund-raiser.
   The city _ public and private _ rolled out its plushest carpet
for the GOP visitors with sumptuous parties, native cuisine,
riverboat rides and Gov. Buddy Roemer reminding everyone the state
was polishing its tarnished image.
   ``Sooner or later the message was going to come across that New
Orleans is not strictly a party town or a place for good food and
music,'' said David Jones, president of the New Orleans Chamber of
Commerce. ``We are starting to do the right things to make this a
viable economic center.''
   Local boosters raved about the success of the four-day
convention, which ended Thursday, and by most accounts the
complaints were minimal.
   But then New Orleans handles Mardi Gras every year with 20 times
as many visitors and a different type of crowd, police said.
   ``At Mardi Gras ... it's a party crowd and there are a few more
untoward incidents,'' said New Orleans police Capt. John Hughes.
``It was very good as far as we're concerned.''
   Suffocating humidity and 90-degree temperatures made it too hot
to misbehave, Hughes said.
   New Orleans' subtropical weather and the sound system installed
by the Republicans in the giant Louisiana Superdome seemed to cause
the most dissatisfaction.
   Technicians began adjusting the system after Sen. Barry
Goldwater, the GOP's 1964 presidential nominee, said he couldn't
hear a word of President Reagan's farewell speech Monday.
   The complaints diminished during the week, but they didn't go
away.
   ``It is not the Superdome system,'' Dome manager Bob Johnson was
quick to point out of the special sound equipment installed by the
Republican convention team.
   There was at least one report of ``hotel hell'' from the New
York delegation, who found parts of their ceiling on the floor and
uncooperative sinks, tubs and toilets.
   ``I'm used to roughing it, but when you can't flush the
toilet,'' said Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, letting his sentence finish
itself. ``I just couldn't work without the basic needs being
fulfilled.''
   And some of the more conservative delegates were not charmed by
New Orleans' tolerance for the weird, the drunk and the sexy.
   ``Now that we have visited Sodom, where is Gomorrah?'' one
Washington state delegate was reported asking.
   But others were seduced by the history, the easy-going attitude
and the Mighty Mississippi.
   ``Even streetwise cab drivers (were) on their best behavior this
week. Lots of pleases and thank yous, complete with accurate meters
and air conditioning systems that work,'' the Daily Oklahoman noted.
   ``Our goal was to put together one of the most successful
conventions in history,'' said Jones, the chamber president.
   Lt. Gov. Paul Hardy said he was hard pressed to find anyone who
wasn't enamored of the French Quarter, the streetcars and the
oak-lined avenues.
   ``I don't believe that we could have spent $1 billion in
advertising and reaped the benefits equal to the fantastic free
press, the free media, we are receiving,'' Hardy said.
   ``It will probably have gains for Louisiana for the next 20
years,'' said Mervin Trail, a New Orleans businessman and another
key fund-raiser.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
