<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Radio-Snake     08-19 0130</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Radio-Snake,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snake Interupts Radio News Broadcast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Uganda had a late-breaking
development on its evening newscast, but the announcer didn't stay
on the air to let his listeners know what happened.
   Veteran newscaster Francis Bbaale was winding up the 10 p.m.
news bulletin Wednesday when a five-foot snake slithered into his
broadcast booth, the Ministry of Information said Friday.
   ``Oh my God! ... Good night!'' the excited newsman told
listeners just before the radio station went off with air without
explanation four minutes before the scheduled end of the 15-minute
broadcast.
   Station employees killed the snake. They did not say what kind
it was.
   Programming resumed Thursday morning, but officials didn't
explain the interrupted broadcast until Friday, after newspapers
carried reports on the incident.
</TEXT>
