<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GrandsonTrial     08-19 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grandson Trial,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Gets Life in Grandmother's Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTIGO, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager accused of raping and murdering
his 76-year-old grandmother when he returned home from a drinking
party was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to life in
prison.
   ``He didn't kill his grandmother; drugs and alcohol did,''
defense lawyer Richard Lawson said before a Circuit Court jury
announced its verdict Thursday against Jason Ungethum, 17.
   ``If Jason had intended to kill his grandmother, especially in
the way he did, he's the lowest form of life. That's not consistent
with the Jason who loved his grandmother,'' said Lawson, who had
argued for a second-degree murder conviction.
   District Attorney Brian Pawlak told the jury Lawson was using an
alcohol defense to try to cloud the issue. ``Alcohol simply allows
somebody with suppressed criminal tendencies to bring them to the
surface,'' Pawlak said.
   The first-degree murder conviction carries a mandatory sentence
of life in prison. Ungethum was also sentenced to five years for
sexual assault. He will be elgible to apply for parole in about 16
years.
   A Langlade County deputy sheriff testified that Ungethum
admitting quarreling with his grandmother when he arrived at her
apartment after a party Jan. 31.
   Ungethum drank at least eight beers and five shots of whiskey at
the party, Lawson said. There also was evidence he smoked
marijuana, took the drug mescaline and was susceptible to
blackouts, the attorney said.
   Mrs. Rock's body was found Feb. 2 by Sheila Ungethum, the
victim's daughter and the defendant's mother. The woman had
suffered blows to the head and been strangled and her throat was
slashed.
</TEXT>
