<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle-NewspaperTax 1stLd-Writethru a0622 08-19 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Newspaper Tax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voted For Newsprint Tax Break That Would Have Benefited Family
Business</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 4th graf, ``Quayle's immediate xxx to CORRECT name of
paper from Herald-Express to Herald-Press</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle, whose family controls a $1 billion newspaper empire, voted
last year to exempt newsprint from a new federal tax on most
imported products.
   Newsprint, the paper on which newspapers are printed, accounts
for as much as 25 percent to 35 percent of the cost of putting out
a daily.
   Although the Indiana senator could have decided not to vote on
the issue, as members sometimes do in cases involving a conflict of
interest, Quayle voted with the losing side when the Senate, by a
69-29 margin, killed the proposed exemption.
   Quayle's immediate family owns the Huntington (Ind.)
Herald-Press. His father is publisher; the senator is vice
president.
   Quayle's most recent financial disclosure statement shows he
owns stock in Central Newspapers, Inc., with a book value of more
than $250,000. The law does not require a more specific figure, but
newspaper industry anaylsts say his stock is worth millions.
   His wife has Central stock with a book value of $100,001 to
$250,000.
   The Wall Street Journal quoted Eugene S. Pulliam, son of the
founder of Central, as saying Quayle owns less than 1 percent of
Central stock. The Journal said a group of investors offered to buy
Central earlier this yer for $1.5 billion.
   Quayle is a grandson of the founder of Central Newspapers,
Eugene C. Pulliam. The group includes the Arizona Republic, Phoenix
Gazette, Indianapolis Star and Indianapolis News.
   Senators generally are required to vote on each issue facing the
Senate, although a member may asked to be excused. However, Senate
Rule XII, Paragraph 3 states: ``A member, nothwithstanding any
other provisons of this rule, may decline to vote, in committee or
on the floor, on any matter when he believes that his voting on
such amatter would be a conflict of interest.''
   In the book, Senate Procedure, page 1137: ``Under the newly
amended rule XII, relative to senators not having to vote when a
conflict of interest is involved, the senator from North Carolina
(Mr. Helms) on a vote in 1980 on an anmendment involving
broadcasting companies declined to vote since he owned stock in a
broadcasting company.''
   Quayle's vote on the newspaper exemption occurred July 21, 1987,
shortly before the Senate passed a bill overhauling U.S. trade laws.
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., offered an amendment exempting
newspapers from the import fee that would be used to pay special
unemployment benefits and other assistance to U.S. workers and
companies harmed by imports.
   ``Since 1913, newsprint has been duty-free,'' Daschle told the
Senate. ``To impose a duty at this time would be a terrible
precedent.... They are dependent upon the importation of a
significant amount of newspring.... It would have a devastating
effect.''
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., called the proposed exemption ``clearly
a special-interest amendment'' and said the newspaper industry's
case for such a break ``is no better than anyone else's.... If we
exempt the publishers,'' Heinz added, ``other industries will have
to make up that lost revenue.''
   Heinz disputed newspaper industry estimates that the new fee
would cost newspapers $40 million a year. He said a $4 million
estimate would be much closer to reality, since the trade bill
limited the amount of trade adjustment assistance that could be
paid, and, thus, the amount of import tax that could be imposed.
   Quayle did not speak on the amendment. Sen. Bob Packwood,
R-Ore., quickly moved to table it, and the Senate agreed, by the
69-29 vote.
   Quayle's Democratic opponent for the vice presidency, Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas, also voted for the newspaper exemption. But as
far as can be determined, Bentsen has no financial interest in any
newspaper.
   The 1987 trade bill eventually was vetoed by President Reagan
for other reasons. The revised version that Congress recently sent
to the president _ and still is awaiting his signature _ requires
negotiations with trading partners leading to a small fee on
imports.
   The president would have two years to negotiate a fee agreeable
to all trading partners. If the negotiations fail, the president
would have to impose it unilaterally or tell Congress why not.
Congress then could pass legislation imposing the fee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
