<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LawyerJailed     08-19 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lawyer Jailed,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer In Racketeering Trial Ordered To Jail Nightly So She'll
Show Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Wilmer as first name is correct.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilmer Grier is spending her days in court
defending her client in a mob-related drug and racketeering trial,
but she's spent the last few nights in a federal jail.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Owen cited Ms. Grier for contempt
for refusing to appear in court Wednesday, when she was treated at
a hospital for injuries suffered in a minor traffic accident.
According to court transcripts, he ordered her to spend seven
nights behind bars.
   The judge said Ms. Grier had been late to court repeatedly _ a
claim she disputed _ and said he wanted to guarantee her presence
at the trial of her client, Timothy Smith. Smith and four other
people are charged with racketeering and distributing heroin.
   Owen's action ``was an insult,'' Ms. Grier, 47, said Thursday.
``I didn't have any credibility with the judge, maybe because I'm
black.''
   Ms. Grier said she was dragged briefly by a taxi Wednesday when
her backpack got caught in the door. She went to a hospital and
told the judge by telephone that she was not coming to court
because she could not maneuver her crutches.
   According to the transcript unsealed Thursday, Owen also asked a
nurse at the hospital about the lawyer's condition. Ms. Grier then
went home instead of to court. U.S. marshals took her to court.
   Owen, known for strictness in his court, stressed that Ms. Grier
had refused to adhere to an order to come to court. He cited
repeated lateness and ordered her detention ``so I know where you
will be.''
   ``This has been a very difficult trial. It's, I guess, affected
all of us,'' Owen said in court Wednesday.
   Ms. Grier told Owen on Wednesday that she felt ``jinxed by the
whole case. Everyday something is happening to me with this case
and I can't get finished.''
   But the judge said he wondered ``whether this is some effort to
get this jury to the point where it is going to give up, whether
this is something that is in your makeup that I don't understand.''
   The case is in summation.
</TEXT>
