<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Spain-Appeal     08-19 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Spain-Appeal,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Against Release of 1981 Revolt Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court refused to release from prison an
ailing leader of the 1981 military revolt that tested the country's
fledgling democracy, court officials said Friday.
   The three-judge tribunal ruled against former Gen. Alfonso
Armada Comin, saying the heart ailment that has hospitalized the
68-year-old prisoner does not warrant a transfer to house arrest on
humanitarian grounds.
   Armada is serving a sentence of more than 26 years for
engineering a 1981 attack on Parliament intended to trigger a
military revolt against the government of then-Prime Minister
Leopoldo Calvo Sotelo.
   The attempt took place six years after the 1975 death of Gen.
Francisco Franco ended 36 years of authoritarian rule, and three
years after King Juan Carlos approved a constitution setting up
Spain's democracy.
   A pistol-waving officer stormed parliament with 200 fellow
paramilitary civil guards, while a second plotter ordered tanks
onto the streets of Valencia for an advance on Madrid that never
materialized. The revolt was foiled early the next morning when
Juan Carlos said on national television the coup would succeed
``only over my dead body.''
</TEXT>
