<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentCrusader     08-19 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Crusader,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newark Teen-ager Crusades To Save Neighborhood From Drugs,
Prostitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE MADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the situation got so bad around the
Miller Street Elementary School playground that students knew the
prostitutes' names, 13-year-old Chaunta Dooley took an aunt's
advice and spoke out in public.
   ``Her call for help and assistance activated a whole
community,'' Councilman Donald Tucker said of Chaunta's action at a
January school board meeting.
   It also got her story and picture in Newsweek magazine in July
as one of ``America's Unsung Heroes'' and a medal commending her
efforts from the City Council.
   Drug traffic and a shortage of textbooks have also come to
concern Chaunta.
   ``Most young people do not take on major adult activities. Most
are very much concerned clearly with their own individual life,''
says Tucker, the councilman who nominated Chaunta for the Newsweek
honor.
   ``I just want to completely demolish the prostitution out of
this neighborhood,'' Chaunta said recently on the porch of her
family's tidy home on a street of debris-strewn lots and abandoned
cars.
   She took her call for action to the City Council, too, and now
her neighbors organize marches to harass the prostitutes and meet
regularly to discuss ways to improve their blighted blocks in New
Jersey's largest city.
   Before the campaign started, there were three or four
prostitutes soliciting business on every street corner in the
neighborhood, which attracts out-of-town customers with easy access
to major highways and Newark International Airport, police Sgt.
Donald Blydenburgh says.
   ``We've given (the area) a little extra attention and it's
improved quite a bit,'' says Blydenburgh.
   Chaunta says her reception among the prostitutes is mixed: ``The
young ones tell us to mind our own business. But the older ones are
different. They tell us not to do it and that they wouldn't if they
didn't have to.''
   The eighth-grader has noticed that more teen-agers are getting
involved in cleaning up the neighborhood and says her activism has
not cost her any friends.
   ``All the kids are so proud of her,'' says Chaunta's mother,
Gail Dooley.
   Ms. Dooley thinks her daughter got involved in her crusade at
least partly because ``she grew up in a community-minded ...
extended family.''
   Chaunta has a 14-year-old brother, Duane, and enough relatives
living nearby to organize a baseball team, her mother says.
Roseville Presbyterian Church, which the family attends, also has
been influential.
   The police have given residents a direct number to call to
report crime in the neighborhood, and officers are quick to
respond, Ms. Dooley says.
   Chaunta also speaks to student groups about drugs. An honor
student, she plays clarinet in a high school band, serves on the
student council and the cheerleader squad and participates in a
school district program for gifted teens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
