<HEAD>Judge Investigated for Contacts With Teen-Age Boys Kills Self</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, `A handgun ...' with 3 grafs to give further
details on note, background on Little; Picks up 6th graf, `In 1982
...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A county judge who had been barred from handling
juvenile court cases because of improper contacts with delinquents
was found dead in the courthouse of an apparently self-inflicted
gunshot wound, officials said today.
   King County Superior Court Judge Gary M. Little knew that the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer was publishing a front-page story today
reporting that Little used his influence to have sexual relations
with young men in the 1970s, a friend of the judge said.
   Camden Hall, a lawyer and longtime friend of Little's, said the
judge called him twice Thursday threatening suicide. Hall said he
tried to get help for Little, whose body was found by a janitor
about 10 p.m. in an eighth floor hallway.
   A .38-caliber handgun and a note were found with the body, said
Police Sgt. Don Cameron, who declined to divulge the contents of
the note. The one-page, handwritten note was found on a hallway
bench and ``it gives intent,'' said Vaughn Van Zant, an
investigator with the county medical examiner's office.
   The cause of death was apparently a self-inflicted gunshot wound
to the head, said Kevin Gow, a medical investigator in the
examiner's office. An autopsy was to be performed later today.
   Little, 49, a former assistant state attorney general, announced
last month he would not seek a third term on the bench,
acknowledging that ``innuendo'' about his work with teen-age boys
was the reason.
   In 1982, the state Commission on Judicial Conduct privately
admonished Little for improper contacts with youths who had
appeared in his courtroom, such as buying them clothing and books.
Court rules bar such contacts. The commission's action was not made
public until 1985; Little was re-elected in 1984.
   In April 1985, after another complaint, Little was barred from
the juvenile court bench by the presiding judge and the Superior
Court executive committee. He was handling civil cases at the time
of his death.
   Hall said Little had been notified that the Post-Intelligencer
would publish a story today in which five men now in their mid- to
late 30s alleged that Little had used his position as an attorney
and teacher at a private school to coerce them into sexual
relations in the 1970s.
   The paper said Little refused to comment Thursday on questions
about his activities prior to being elected to the bench in 1980.
   ``If I was running for the bench, I think some of the questions
you ask me would be appropriate,'' Little said. ``But I am not. I
am leaving.''
   Hall said late Thursday that Little had telephoned him about 3
p.m., deeply distraught.
   ``He said he was going to kill himself,'' Hall said. Little
called again about 9:50 p.m. ``He said, `If you don't hear from me
in 10 minutes it will be done.'''
   After the first call threatening suicide, Hall called the county
crisis center and was referred to mental health professionals. He
said the professionals told him the best thing to do was to try to
have Little committed.
   Hall said he alerted Seattle police after Little's second call.
They arrived at the courthouse after the shooting.
   ``He said he felt he'd been hounded by the press and he just
couldn't take it anymore,'' Hall said.
   Officials at Lakeside School where Little worked said he left in
1973 on good terms and that they were unaware of any illicit
activity.
</TEXT>
