<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfires Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0640,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Continues To Threaten Helena Suburbs; Yellowstone Campground
Closed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Elsewhere, helicopters ...' to UPDATE with
fatal helicopter crash.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FAITH CONROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A forest and grass fire that killed cattle
and destroyed 10 houses grew by 7,000 acres overnight in the
mountains southeast of Helena, despite the efforts of 1,700
firefighters.
   ``It sounded like a train,'' said Barbara Duffy, whose cabin and
30 cows were destroyed by flames when the Warm Springs Creek fire
quadrupled in size Thursday. ``When we came out of the garage, we
saw this fireball coming at us through the trees.''
   Elsewhere, helicopters today ferried firefighters into a Wyoming
wilderness area near Yellowstone National Park to fight an 800-acre
blaze, and a helicopter involved in firefighting efforts in
Wyoming's Bighorn National Forest crashed today, killing one and
injuring three others. Firefighters also battled fires in
California, Idaho, Utah and other Western states.
   The Warm Springs Creek fire, in the Elkhorn Mountains, grew to
27,000 acres during the night, but on two fronts it took turns that
could help suppress it, said fire information officer Bob Krepps
said today.
   Westerly wind blowing at about 20 mph late Thursday ``pushed the
fire back into itself'' on its western perimeter, depriving it of
new fuel and relieving a threat to the 500 or so residents of the
Saddle Mountain subdivision about 10 miles southeast of Helena,
Krepps said. They had been warned that they might have to evacuate.
   On the fire's eastern edge, the flames moved out of the forested
high country and onto grassland. ``That's a real benefit to us
also,'' Krepps said, because of the lighter fuel.
   Although the flames advanced east to within about three miles of
the tiny community of Winston, about 15 miles southeast of Helena,
``There's good fire line in over there,'' Krepps said. ``I think
they're in pretty good shape this morning.''
   At least 40 people remained out of their homes while volunteer
fire crews helped cut fire lines around houses and other structures
west of Winston and near Montana City, a small town a few miles
south of Helena, authorities said.
   Fire officials said they were optimistic about a cooling trend
predicted for the weekend.
   Krepps said four homes and six summer cabins were burned early
Thursday when the fast-moving Warm Springs Creek took an unexpected
turn toward the north.
   Before the fire ballooned Wednesday night, about 1,700
firefighters had it 95 percent contained. The blaze began Aug. 9
when a four-wheel-drive vehicle caught fire. Eighty percent of the
fire has burned on the Helena National Forest.
   Hundreds of miles away in southeastern Montana, about 1,000
firefighters hoped to tighten the noose today around fires that
have burned 13,600 acres of timber and grassland near Lame Deer.
   Most of the three fires surrounding Lame Deer, a town of about
600 people on the North Cheyenne Indian Reservation, were contained
by fire lines Thursday night, said fire information officer Ron
Smith.
   In north-central Montana, nearly 950 firefighters were battling
a 4,800-acre fire on the Rocky Boys Indian Reservation. Containment
was predicted by Saturday night.
   In northwest Wyoming, Yellowstone officials closed the Norris
Campground on Thursday as a precaution due to a 69,000-acre fire
five miles to the south.
   The fire also forced the closure again Thursday of a 14-mile
road as trees scorched by the blaze toppled onto the pavement.
Another park campground remained closed because of a nearby blaze,
while a third was shut to provide a campground for firefighters.
   About 272,000 acres of the nation's oldest park have been
damaged by flames in recent weeks.
   In nearby Teton Wilderness today, 200 firefighters ferried by
helicopter battled an 800-acre wildfire, using pumps and hoses to
suck water from streams and ponds to spray on the flames.
   Meanwhile, in north-central Wyoming's Bighorn National Forest,
officials ordered the evacuation for a second time of the Apache
Oil Co.'s Paradise Ranch as a 3,000-acre fire, pushed by high
winds, jumped fire lines and threatened from a half-mile away.
   Firefighters in southwest Utah contained an 580-acre brush fire,
believed to be man-caused, that burned about 20 miles northwest of
St. George. Firefighters also controlled a 600-acre blaze in
northern Utah.
   In southern California's San Jacinto Mountains, crews worked to
contain an arson-caused wildfire that consumed 1,000 acres of brush blaze,
about 95 miles east of Los Angeles, was
about 40 percen
and timber. Thet contained Thursday.
   Firefighters in Idaho's Challis National Forest, meanwhile,
squelched a nearly 14,000-acre fire and were being sent elsewhere.
</TEXT>
