<HEAD>Man Sues Bowling Alley Over Perfect Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Lanes Bowling Center gave Rick L.
Gibbons a check for $100 when he rolled a perfect game last
September. But now Gibbons is suing West Lanes _ because of the way
it takes care of its lanes.
   Gibbons, of Council Bluffs, Iowa, filed suit Thursday in Douglas
County District Court alleging that a maintenance mistake kept him
from receiving certification of a perfect score from the American
Bowling Congress.
   The bowling center's owner said he's befuddled by the lawsuit,
which seeks unspecified damages and court costs.
   ``I just think it's wild,'' said co-owner Bud Simmonds. ``I
really didn't think he'd go so far as to file a suit.''
   Gibbons bowled a perfect score of 300 during league play on
Sept. 8, then applied for recognition by the American Bowling
Congress. But his application was denied after a certified
inspector from the Omaha Mens Bowling Association found that West
Lanes had ``dressed'' its lanes in violation of national
regulations, the lawsuit says.
   Dressing is the daily application of mineral oil to bowling
lanes, which can affect the path a ball takes down the lane.
   West Lanes used the short-distance dressing method in which oil
is applied along the first 24 feet of the 60-foot lane.
   But the inspector found that oil had been applied on too much of
the lane.
   ``Somehow the machine that hae Massine and then with Marie
Rambert, who encouraged him to try choreography and helped him win
his first commission, a small ballet called ``A Tragedy of
Fashion'' created for a revue in 1926.
   In retirement, Ashton continued to remain active as a consultant
and visitor to both The Royal Ballet and its touring sister
company, the Sadler's Wells Royal Ballet.
   ``He never really stopped,'' said Mary Clarke, editor of the
monthly The Dancing Times. ``He could always come up with a pas de
deux or a party piece for a special occasion. He was adored by
everyone.''
   Asked once what was the inspiration for his inventions, Ashton
replied, ``I don't know, that's fairly difficult to say. I am
fairly religious. I rather put myself in the hands of a superior
power ... I am almost like a wireless (radio).''
   Ashton was unmarried and the Royal Ballet said it did not know
if there were any survivors. No funeral arrangements were announced.
