<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teachers-TimeClocks     08-19 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers-Time Clocks,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYC School Chief Urges End To Teacher Time Clocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City's schools chancellor is telling
schools to consider getting rid of time clocks that many teachers
cite as hated symbols of their lack of professional status.
   Chancellor Richard Green has drafted a memorandum directing the
principals and staffs of each of the city's 974 public schools to
submit plans by Dec. 1 for keeping track of teachers' hours without
time clocks, he said in an interview Thursday.
   ``I'm very pleased,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the
United Federation of Teachers, the union representing the city's
61,000 teachers.
   ``I have called around the country. I don't know of any other
school district that has them,'' said Feldman.
   New York City teachers have been punching clocks since the early
1900s, when reformers thought schools should operate on a factory
model for the sake of efficiency, she said.
   The city's teachers are required to be in school at least six
hours, 20 minutes, the length of a school day.
   Green's predecessor, former chancellor Nathan Quinones, had sent
out two more weakly worded memorandums at the union's urging to
persuade schools to end time clocks.
   But more than 800 city schools still have them, according to
Feldman.
   ``We've had teachers docked for being a minute late. And the
time teachers spend after school doesn't count,'' she said.
   Green's directive differs from earlier ones in imposing a
definite deadline. It also orders principals to collaborate with
teachers.
   Green said he was ``asking principals to work with their staffs
to determine how they can account for attendance in the absence of
time clocks, or whether they want to sustain them. They will make
the decision building by building, and no one will ever be able to
say they didn't have a chance to participate in a work-related
issue that I think is symbolic.''
   Alternatives to time clocks include sign-out sheets and time
cards.
</TEXT>
