<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan     08-19 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Plans White House Meeting With American Indian Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is planning a
White House meeting with American Indian leaders who protested his
remark at the Moscow summit that the United States perhaps ``should
not have humored'' the Indians, the White House said Friday.
   The American Indian Action Group said presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater indicated Thursday that Reagan would ``make good
on his offer to meet with American Indian people.''
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Bob Hall confirmed Friday
that Fitzwater told the group that the president's staff had been
told to meet with the Indians to determine a date and time for the
meeting.
   The Indian group, which had previously announced plans to rally
and walk to Reagan's mountaintop ranch north of here Saturday, said
in a statement it had ``made a commitment'' to the demonstration
and would proceed with it.
   Hall said the staff-level meeting probably would be held in
Santa Barbara while Reagan is vacationing at the ranch. The meeting
in Washington will take place some time after Reagan returns to the
White House on Sept. 6, he said.
   On May 31, during his Moscow summit talks with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Reagan told Moscow University students,
``Maybe we made a mistake in trying to maintain Indian cultures.
Maybe we should not have humored them in wanting to stay in that
kind of primitive lifestyle. Maybe we should have said, `No, come
join us. Be citizens along with the rest of us'.''
   Congress granted American Indians full citizenship in 1924. It
was not until 1948 that a court decision gave them full voting
rights in Arizona and New Mexico in local and state elections.
   Reagan's remarks outraged Indian leaders. The president invited
them to meet with him ``at any time,'' but the American Indian
Action Group said he failed to respond to letters and telephone
calls from Indian leaders.
   ``During his administration, Reagan has never met with Indian
leaders,'' the group said. ``The remarks he made in Moscow were his
first reference to American Indians in eight years.''
   The group said about 200 Indians were expected to gather at
Refugio State Beach on Saturday and walk to the ranch.
   The White House described weather at the ranch as sunny and warm
and said the president was continuing with his usual routine of
paperwork, wood chopping and horseback riding.
   He plans to travel to Los Angeles on Tuesday for a five-day
stay, stopping en route at the Marine Operations Building of the
Port of Long Beach to sign legislation intended to reduce U.S.
trade deficits.
   He also plans to attend a fund-raising lunch in Irvine, Calif.,
for Republican Sen. Pete Wilson's re-election campaign.
</TEXT>
