<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     08-19 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, On Whistle-Stop Tour, Criticizes Bush's `Mission'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis took his promise of
economic opportunity to rural Illinois, Missouri and Arkansas on
Friday, and said George Bush and Republicans were ignoring ominous
trade and budget deficits ``because they don't know how to deal
with it.''
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, also took another
indirect shot at Bush and his running mate, Indiana Sen. Dan
Quayle, who is embroiled in a controversy over using family
influence to get into the National Guard at the height of the
Vietman war.
   ``The test of strong presidential leadership is strength, the
quality of the people you select to serve with you,'' Dukakis told
an early afternoon rally at the train depot in Bismarck. The crowd
appeared to outnumber the town's population of 1,600 people.
   In Belleville, Ill., at the start of his day, Dukakis recalled
Harry Truman's love of whistle-stop campaigning and then boarded a
train of his own _ ``The Duke Express'' _ to travel the day after
Bush accepted the Republican presidential nomination.
   ``Today we are going to begin a journey into the future,''
Dukakis said. ``While the vice president and the Republicans took a
trip down memory lane last night, we're looking to the future.''
   The Democratic nominee said Bush's convention address ``wasn't a
bad speech actually.'' But he attacked the vice president for
failing to say how he would deal with the red ink on the budget and
trade ledgers.
   ``He talked a lot about missions but I must have missed a
page,'' said Dukakis, who did not watch Bush's speech but reviewed
its text. ``There was nothing in there about the two biggest
economic challenges we face in this country,'' he said.
   ``We didn't hear a word from the Republicans on the budget
deficit or the trade deficit last night or this week. And we know
why. They don't know how to deal with it. They don't know what to
do with it. That's why we're going to have a Democratic president
and vice president.''
   The Massachusetts governor, at his rallies here and in
Belleville, mentioned his state's unemployment rate has been about
3 percent for several years while the jobless rates in the Illinois
and Missouri towns hover near 10 percent. Dukakis blamed Reagan
administration policies he said fueled prosperity in some regions
but ingored and exacerbated economic distress in others.
   ``They may be satisfied, but we aren't,'' Dukakis said. ``We can
do a lot better ... This January, we Americans are going to take
charge of our economic future.''
   At both rallies he mentioned the deficits, a lack of affordable
housing, the Pentagon procurement scandal, and the stewardship of
former Attorney General Edwin Meese III, saying Republicans ducked
those issues at their convention.
   Dukakis led the crowds in the refrain ``not a single word from
the Republicans'' after mentioning each of those issues.
   Dukakis boarded his 11-car Amtrak train in Belleville and headed
across the Missouri river, through St. Louis and down the
Mississippi River to Bismarck, a mining town where he visited a
depot-area diner and was joined by a former rival, Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt. Then it was all aboard for Poplar Bluff in
southeastern Missouri and Walnut Ridge in the farmlands of
northeast Arkansas. The total distance of the trip was 239 miles.
From there Dukakis was flying to Texas to campaign Saturday with
his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   The controversy over Bush's selection of the 41-year-old Quayle
as the GOP vice presidential nominee and Quayle's use of family
influece to get into the guard has prompted a revision of Dukakis'
stump speech.
   He has not criticized Quayle directly but for the past three
days has delivered a variation of this line at virtually every
campaign stop: ``Nobody has ever questioned the qualifications of
Lloyd Bentsento be vice president or the president.''
   Dukakis drew laughs from reporters in Bismarck when he joked
about criticism from Republicans that Dukakis and his wife, Kitty,
show too much public affection.
   ``It's true that Democrats sleep in double beds and Republicans
prefer twins,'' he said. ``That's why there are more Democrats.''
</TEXT>
