<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   08-19 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Will Defy Israeli Efforts to Destroy Local Committees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT SAHUR, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of local committee
said Friday they will defy Israeli attempts to stamp out the
informal system of self-rule that has sprung up during the
8-month-old Palestinian uprising.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin declared the ``popular
committees'' illegal on Thursday and threatened to deport prominent
activists.
   On Friday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said: ``These
committees incited disturbances and brought a lot of suffering upon
the (Arab) population. We had to stop their activities.''
   Palestinian intellectuals said the grass-roots organization is
far too extensive to be broken.
   ``It's a way of life now,'' said Saeb Erakat, a professor at An
Najah University in Nablus, which has been closed. ``I don't think
Rabin with all the military might at his disposal can do anything
about it except cause more suffering.''
   Hundreds of committees have been formed in villages and towns of
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and on almost every city
block.
   Organizing began last spring in response to leaflets issued by
the clandestine United National Leadership of the Uprising, which
is linked to Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization.
   In the mainly Christian town of Beit Sahur, organizers said
groups of 40 to 70 families sent one representative each to
neighborhood centers. About 12,000 Palestinians live in the town
near Shepherd's Field, where the Bible says the first word of
Christ's birth was announced.
   Neighborhood representatives elected committees of seven or
eight members, but Israeli authorities arrested eight prominent
Palestinians who tried to form an independent town council.
   ``The local committees provide an alternative authority to
occupation, and their ultimate aim is to cut ties between the
people and Israel's military government,'' said a 50-year-old
teacher who has been jailed several times for political activism.
He demanded anonymity to avoid arrest.
   Support for local committees appears strong in Beit Sahur. It is
fed by anger at Israeli soldiers, who are blamed for the death of a
17-year-old boy killed by a falling rock and the arrests of 120
residents.
   Townspeople turned in their identity cards in protest after
soldiers broke into living rooms to confiscate television sets and
took cars from driveways in raids against delinquent taxpayers.
   Strikes and refusing to pay taxes are two of the main
non-violent ways to join the rebellion, in which at least 248
Palestinians have been killed since Dec. 8. Four Israelis also have
been slain.
   Soldiers shot and wounded at least two Palestinians in the West
Bank on Friday.
   A commercial strike was only partially successful Friday in the
West Bank and was ignored in the Gaza Strip. The army delayed the
opening of West Bank schools and universities, which it considers
rallying points for violence, until at least Oct. 1.
   Committees in Beit Sahur, following a pattern in the occupied
lands, has mobilized Palestinians for such non-violent activities
as:
   _ Planting gardens to reduce dependence on Israeli markets and
to raise money for other activities.
   _ Organizing underground schools after Israel closed five
universities and 1,500 elementary and secondary schools.
   _ Giving money and food to families who have quit jobs in Israel
or whose breadwinners are in jail.
   _ Guarding neighborhoods from thieves after activists forced
Palestinian policemen to quit their jobs.
   _ Providing medical care for injured protesters.
   A 45-year-old professional who heads a committee said the army
arrested volunteers who obeyed leaflets ordering a cleanup in the
absence of city garbage collection, which was suspended for lack of
tax revenues.
   ``It's ridiculous,'' he said. ``Is it political for me to want
to plant vegetables, teach my son or clean the street?''
   A Defense Ministry announcement said: ``Every person who
continues to be a member of popular committees and every person who
assists these committees will face arrest and trial.''
   Moshe Negbi of Israel's Civil Rights Association said that meant
anyone carrying a leaflet, attending a meeting, performing a
service or contributing money to a committee could be jailed for 10
years.
   Answers to Rabin appeared in graffiti near Beit Sahur's
now-inactive city hall: ``Increased violence will only increase our
resistance'' and ``Form more popular committees.''
   The committee leader said local groups would have to be a ``bit
more cautious,'' even go underground, but ``we are not going to
stop cooperating with each other. ... People don't fear the
soldiers any more. We got rid of our fear.''
   Other grass-roots groups called ``strike forces'' paint slogans
on walls and distribute leaflets telling residents when to strike
and when to open stores.
   Masked teen-agers threaten or punish people who pay Israeli
taxes or go to work during a strike.
   A Beit Sahur doctor's car was burned because he paid an Israeli
license fee so he could use it to visit patients. A community
leader said he disagreed with the arson but his committee was not
consulted.
</TEXT>
