<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ProsecutorsShot     08-19 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prosecutors Shot,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Prosecutor Shot In Random Kidnap-Robbery Dies, Colleague In
Surgery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Last name Melneciuc in 9th graf is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA GORDA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two prosecutors shot during a
robbery died Friday, soon after he was taken off life-support and
hours after a man found sleeping on a beach was charged in what
police said was a random crime.
   Assistant State Attorney Norman Langston, 27, had slipped into a
coma shortly after the Wednesday night shootings and died at
Medical Center Hospital, said Penny Walker, spokeswoman for the
20th Judicial District State Attorney's office.
   ``He was a real all-American guy. The people who knew him and
loved him say they never knew anyone who didn't like him. He loved
the beach, he was real athletic. He really loved being here,'' said
Ms. Walker.
   His colleague, prosecutor Kathleen Finnegan, 28, was in stable
condition at Fawcett Memorial Hospital in Port Charlotte, where she
underwent surgery to remove bullets from her arms and shoulders.
   ``She does not know about Norman's condition. When she's stable
enough to be told,'' Ms. Walker said.
   Samuel Andrew Pettit, 26, was arrested on a Naples beach
Thursday night on a charge of unlawfully possessing a gun and was
later transferred to Punta Gorda, officials said.
   Pettit was charged with first-degree murder and attempted
first-degree murder, and also will be charged with two counts each
of kidnapping and armed robbery, the spokeswoman said.
   ``It's apparently a random robbery-kidnapping-shooting, if such
a thing can be random. There doesn't seem to appear there was any
knowledge of who he was taking,'' said Ms. Walker.
   The prosecutors were abducted at gunpoint outside a restaurant
and robbed, then were forced to to drive to an isolated location
where the gunman shot them repeatedly with a small-caliber handgun
before fleeing, said Charlotte County Sheriff's spokeswoman Tracey
Melneciuc.
   Ms. Finnegan was able to get to a tavern a mile and a half away
to call for help, Ms. Melneciuc said. Authorities have not said if
she drove or walked.
   Langston was hired as a prosecutor May 31, a year after
receiving his law degree from Nova University's Law School in Fort
Lauderdale, Ms. Walker said.
   Ms. Finnegan had worked for three years as an assistant public
defender before crossing the aisle to become a prosecutor last
January, Ms. Walker said.
</TEXT>
