<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OldestMan     08-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oldest Man,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Oldest Man Celebrates 111th Birthday</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SWANSEA, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Evans, regarded as the world's oldest
man, celebrated his 111th birthday Friday with his rules for a long
life: don't smoke, drink or swear, but treat yourself to honey and
a song.
   The chipper Welshman, who lives with his 77-year-old son and his
wife, told the BBC that much of his good health comes from a good
diet with plenty of vegetables.
   ``But some part of it is taking hot water in the morning ...
(with) a small bit of honey. I've been doing that since I retired
and that's going on 38 years (ago),'' the former miner told BBC
radio in an interview at his home in FForest-Fach near Swansea in
South Wales.
   ``Honey is great,'' said Evans. ``I get plenty of that on my
birthday.''
   Singing helps, too.
   ``I've been doing that since I was a little boy. Going to Sunday
school, I'd sing, plenty of it,'' he said, breaking into a Welsh
song.
   But Evans, who visited London for the first time last year when
he turned 110 and had a pacemaker fitted when he was 108, vetoes
some things.
   ``I say this definitely: no drink and no smoking of any kind.
And no cursing and swearing which is disturbing (to) the nerves,''
he said.
   Evans, who was born in 1877, began working in the mines when he
was 13 and stopped work at the age of 73 only when he was forced to
retire by his company.
   He has a wheelchair but prefers a walking stick, and gardened
until he was 95, planting potatoes and other vegetables.
   Anna Nicholas, spokeswoman for The Guinness Book of Records,
said Evans is considered the oldest living man because he has a
birth certificate to prove his age.
   The oldest living person is Jeanne Calment, from Arles, France
who was born on Feb. 21, 1875, which makes her 113, Miss Nicholas
said. Guinness only learned of Ms. Calment last month, and she will
appear in its 1989 record book.
   Anna Eliza Williams of Swansea, listed in the 1988 book as the
world's oldest person, died in January at the age of 114.
</TEXT>
