<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Quayle-Guard 3rdLd-Writethru a0583 08-19 1261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle-Guard, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0583,1,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Answers Questions About National Guard Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new; pickup 2nd prv: ``Quayle, who xxx'' minor
editing below to conform and tighten</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede NEW ORLEANS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle said today he broke no
rules to get into the Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam War
and would do the same thing again.
   At an outdoor news conference at his hometown, Quayle
acknowledged that a family friend who was an employee of his
grandfather's newspaper and a former commander of the Indiana
National Guard probably interceded on his behalf.
   The Indianapolis News had reported Thursday that its former
managing editor, Wendell C. Phillippi, had been asked about
entering the Guard by Quayle.
   ``Wendell Phillippi knew that I wanted to get into the National
Guard and I hope that he helped me and I think he did,'' Quayle
told reporters today. ``I would hope that he helped me and I expect
that.''
   Quayle said he initially called his parents to discuss his
desire to enter the National Guard when he was about to lose his
colleage student deferment.
   Asked why he did not just go down and fill out papers if his
entry into the Guard was as routine as he suggested it was, Quayle
said:
   ``I do what any normal person would do at that age. You call
home. You call home to mother and father and say `I'd like to get
in the National Guard.''
   He said he also talked briefly to Phillippi. ``I told him I
wanted to get into the National Guard. I would assume calls would
be made. I talked to Mr. Phillippi very briefly. I hope that he
helped me and I thihnk he did.''
   Quayle said he saw nothing wrong with what he did.
   ``I got into the National Guard fairly,'' he said. ``I did not
ask anyone to break the rules and so far as I know no one did.''
   Asked to assess the way he proceeded as a 22-year-old, he said,
``I would not have done anything differently'' if he had known he
would be running for vice president one day.
   Earlier today in New Orleans, Quayle had poked fun at the
controversy over his entry into the National Guard during the
Vietnam War by introducing himself to party leaders in mock
military fashion as if addressing a superior.
   Quayle, who appeared with George Bush at a Republican National
Committee meeting the morning after the GOP national convention
unamimously ratified him as the vice presidential nominee, said
jokingly that he had learned how to introduce himself on the
campaign trail.
   Then Quayle snapped to attention, and in loud, staccato-like
military diction, said: ``I stand at attention. Name: Dan Quayle.
Serial number 303 50 4096. Indiana National Guard. Six years and
proud of it.'' The audience applauded.
   Quayle proceeded to praise Bush, the presidential nominee,
before the two men headed out on the campaign trail, traveling
first to Indiana, Quayle's home state.
   The Indiana senator promised answers today to questions over
what influence his family used to secure his entry into the
National Guard. The issue tarnished Quayle selection as the No. 2
on the GOP ticket even before he was nominated Thursday night.
   Aides to Bush spent much of the day debating a response to the
furor and denying any thought of replacing Quayle on the ticket.
   ``There's nothing we feel Sen. Quayle misled us on,'' Bush
campaign official Rich Bond said today on NBC-TV.
   But critics were harsher.
   ``Let's face it, the question is whether a rich kid's family got
him into the Guard when other people were getting drafted,'' said
John DeCamp, a Vietnam veteran and Republican delegate from
Nebraska. ``Some of them like me got shot at a lot and a great many
of them just plain got shot and killed.''
   Rep. Bob Dornan of California, every bit a conservative, said,
``It requires a Checkers-like speech, and he must do _ must do it _
quickly, before this gets out of hand.''
   Dornan referred to a televised speech during the 1952 campaign
in which then-GOP vice presidential nominee Richard M. Nixon
successfully responded to allegations he had a slush fund while
serving in the Senate from California. The speech, in which he said
his family and dog, Checkers, were more important anything else,
kept Nixon on Dwight Eisenhower's ticket.
   ``I don't like the fact that Quayle denied yesterday that
anybody had interceded on his behalf when apparently someone had,''
said Rep. Helen Bentley, chairman of the Bush campaign in Maryland.
``Quayle can do one of two things: admit this and that he was a
liar _ or he can withdraw from the race.''
   But later Thursday, she backed off her strong criticism, saying
the issue was ``dead'' and had been based on ``inaccurate news
reports.''
   Quayle drew many defenders as well. And at the end of the day,
it was certain he had the most important supporter of all.
   ``I'm proud to have Dan Quayle at my side,'' Bush told the
delegates.
   For his part, Quayle said the focus should be on Bush in the
convention hall and refused on Thursday to answer questions about
how he got into the Indiana National Guard.
   ``I'm going to continue to answer questions you raise about me,
about issues, about anything through this campaign,'' he said
entering the Superdome. ``Tonight is George Bush's night. And in
deference to George Bush, I'm not going to get into all the details.
   ``I'll be around ... to answer your questions,'' he added.
   During his acceptance speech inside the hall, the second-term
senator added a reference to show an unbending stand.
   ``As a young man, I served six years in the National Guard. And,
like the millions of Americans who have served in the Guard ... I
am proud of it,'' Quayle said.
   Questions were first raised about his military service on
Wednesday, when he and Bush faced reporters for the first time
together. Quayle called suggestions that his choice of the National
Guard was a method to avoid the draft _ and service in Vietnam _
``a cheap shot.''
   Later Wednesday, he said he was not aware of any efforts by his
family or friends to win him a spot in the Guard.
   He joined the National Guard in 1969, days after he was
graduated from college and thus lost his student deferment from the
draft. Quayle was a private first class in the Guard, serving as a
writer in a public information unit until 1975.
   During the height of the draft and the Vietnam War, waiting
lists were long to get into the Guard in many states, which
exempted young men from the draft and carried only a small chance
of being sent to the combat zone of Southeast Asia.
   Of the more than 58,000 American casualties in the Vietnam war,
97 were Guardsmen in mobilized units. about entering the Guard by
Quayle.
   Phillippi, who worked for Quayle's grandfather at the
Indianapolis newspaper, said Quayle inquired as to whether he might
be sent to Vietnam as part of a Guard unit. ``He wondered if it was
subject to call,'' Phillippi said.
   ``I just called the military department and said, `Here's a good
man, you ought to take him','' Phillippi said. ``It was just as I
have done for many young men over many years. ... I was just a peon
calling the military department. I had no power.''
   Some Guard units were activated and sent to Vietnam, including
at least one from Indiana.
</TEXT>
