<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Judge'sRemarks     08-19 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge's Remarks,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Removes Himself From Criminal Cases After Questionable
Remarks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week after suggesting to a newspaper
columnist that a 12-year-old boy who was sexually molested ``might
have enjoyed it,'' a judge has removed himself from major criminal
cases.
   ``Extensive controversy can impair the judicial process in
criminal cases,'' Superior Judge Seymour Hendel said as he
announced his decision Thursday in a statement to The Day of New
London, whose columnist, Steven Slosberg, disclosed the judge's
remarks about two child molestation cases.
   William R. Evans, 39, had confessed to using money to lure the
12-year-old boy into sex acts. In the other case, Edwin Diaz, 22,
admitted raping two girls, ages 7 and 9.
   In each case, a prosecutor reduced multiple sexual assault
charges to a single count of risk of injury to a minor. Hendel
ordered both men to undergo sex offender treatment as a condition
of probation.
   In Slosberg's Aug. 11 column, Hendel was quoted as saying the
case involving the 12-year-old boy was ``not a grave case,'' while
the sexual assault of the girls was ``a very bad case.''
   Speaking about the Evans case, Hendel was quoted as saying:
   ``There was no force used. ... If it wasn't for the disparity in
age, we might not have heard about it. For all I know, the kid
might have enjoyed it.''
   Hendel also was quoted in the column as saying the Diaz case
``was second-degree (sexual assault). There was no force.''
   The remarks drew criticism from the National Organization for
Women and the New London Women's Center.
   Hendel said in the letter to the newspaper Thursday that he has
been open with the media in his 10{ years on the bench.
   ``The recent controversy is a direct result of my openness,'' he
wrote. ``The content of the column does not represent my position
and views in sexual abuse cases and in no way reflects my concerns
and attitudes in these very serious and complex cases.
   ``I deeply regret that as a result of this telephone
conversation and the ensuing column, families and victims who have
been involved in sexual abuse cases may have been caused additional
anguish.''
   Slosberg said the judge never denied the accuracy of the quotes
but said they were taken out of context.
   Judge Aaron Ment, Connecticut's chief court administrator, said
Hendel's decision wouldn't affect the flow of cases.
   Hendel's comments were not a matter of review for his office,
but would be handled by the Judicial Review Council, Ment said. The
chairman and the executive director of the council were on vacation
Friday, according to secretaries at their offices. Another council
member, Michael J. Daly of Fairfield, said he had not heard of the
matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
