<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Abroad,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Abroad: Comment on Republican Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is some of what newspapers abroad had to say Friday on the
Republican convention and Vice President George Bush's choice of
Sen. Dan Quayle as his running mate in the November presidential
election:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CANADA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ The Toronto Star (liberal): ``It's hard for a Canadian to
imagine that the Republican Party in the U.S. could move even
further right than it did during ... Reagan's time in office. But
it has. By choosing hard-line conservative Sen. Dan Quayle as his
running mate, Vice President George Bush has dispelled any illusion
that he's a political moderate.
   ``It's in foreign policy that a Bush administration's right may
cause reverberations in Canada and around the world. ... With
anti-communist rhetoric that echoes Reagan's `evil empire'
description of the Soviet Union, the Republicans seem to throw cold
water on negotiation as the way to settle conflicts.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEDEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Dagens Nyheter (liberal): ``The selection of Dan Quayle as
Bush's running mate is a way for the Republican Party to make up
for the lack of backbone that Bush has shown. ... If the extreme
right-wing voters of the party are to be mobilized in the election,
it is perhaps necessary that the vice president is a person of
their choice.
   ``Dan Quayle is one of Reagan's most loyal supporters, a
photogenic he-man who almost always votes with the extreme
right-wing of the party.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ Svenska Dagbladet (conservative): The choice of Quayle was
``surprising but not disagreeable. Bush has only one year left
before retirement age and lacks all political freshness, while
Quayle should be able to appeal to voters of his own age group.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HUNGARY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Magyar Hirlap (state-run): ``George Bush, although less of a
charmer than Michael Dukakis, much older than him and occasionally
dry ... so lagging behind him in the popularity race ... is still
the stronger side in political experience.
   ``Let us say he still stands a very good chance to become the
host in the White House. ... That explains his popularity in New
Orleans.
   ``Newcomer running mate Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana ... may fill
the gaps left by being young, good-looking, vigorous _ and a more
marked conservative than his potential future chief.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Le Monde (independent, left-leaning): ``If they could have,
the Republicans would have renominated Mr. Reagan. Instead, this
New Orleans convention ended with cries of `four more years,' on a
note of unanimous will: to continue.
   ```To continue,' therefore, will be as in the past, to promote a
`strong, free' America, and delivered above all from the temptation
to raise taxes. All of it is barely disguised in more tender colors
and more in the style of Mr. Bush: those of a new approach to
social problems and greater demands in governmental ethics.
   ``The Republicans can hope that the olive branches of `Pax
Reagania' which are blossoming a little bit everywhere, from Moscow
to Luanda, passing by Kabul, will blow away the last odors of
`Irangate,' the last humiliations of `Panamagate.'''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DENMARK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Det Fri Aktuelt: ``Anybody who tries to become president is
crazy. ... Seriously regarded, it shows how serious are the
difficulties that the Republicans' George Bush has. He lags behind
in the polls, because he has not at all succeeded in convincing the
Americans that he is something else than a faint echo of Ronald
Reagan _ totally without his outstanding ability to communicate
with the voters.''
</TEXT>
