<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Profile     08-19 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Profile,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ishaq Khan a Third World Economic Diplomat, Cautious Administrator</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ghulam Ishaq Khan, who became acting
president with the death of Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, is considered a
cautious administrator with moderate views on international
economic and financial.
   Ishaq Khan, 73, the chairman of the senate, moved into the
nation's top position in accordance with the constitution after
Zia's death Wednesday.
   He served as chairman of the powerful development committee of
the World Bank and with the International Monetary Fund in the
early 1980s, trying to reach solutions to a number of issues
creating friction between the Third World and Western nations.
   At the time, the Third World and the West were squaring off over
Latin American debt, plans for development of the impoverished
African Sahara Desert and programs to provide more resources to
undeveloped nations.
   Ishaq Khan was born Jan. 20, 1915, at Ismail Khel, about 160
miles southwest of Islamabad, close to the Afghan border.
   He majored in chemistry and botany at the University of the
Punjab in Lahore.
   He joined the civil service in 1940 in then-British India and
was serving in the North-West Frontier province when Pakistan won
its freedom in 1947. He became the secretary of Pakistan cabinet in
1970.
   Ishaq Khan was appointed governor of the State Bank of Pakistan,
the nation's central bank, in 1971. He later served as defense
secretary, during which time he caught the attention of Zia, who
was army chief of staff.
   Zia in 1979 made Ishaq Khan minister for finance, commerce and
planning.
   Six years later, the minister was elected to the senate,
becoming chairman on March 21, 1985.
   Under the constitution, the chairman of parliament's upper house
becomes head of the government when the president is incapacitated
or dies.
   The acting president speaks his native Pushtu, Urdu, and
English, and has traveled widely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
