<2ND_LINE>AM-People, SUB, a0669,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs first item, datelined Birmingham, to UPDATE that Jones
released.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer George Jones was hospitalized for
the fifth time in 13 months and was released Friday after being
treated for a severe sinus infection, a hospital spokesman said.
   Jones, 56, known for country standards such as ``He Stopped
Loving Her Today'' and ``The Race is On,'' arrived at University
Hospital on Sunday, said spokesman Hank Black.
   ``He said his head was hurting and his ears were ringing,'' said
Black. ``He told his wife he couldn't go on and had better go back
to the hospital.''
   Jones, who has battled drug and alcohol problems, received
intravenous antibiotics to combat the ``longstanding'' sinus
infection, Black said. He will continue to take medication.
   His string of trips to University Hospital started in July 1987
when he was admitted with a stomach ailment. In October he was
hospitalized with severe nausea, and two months later he was
treated for an unspecified problem, said Black. In May, Jones was
hospitalized for several days for double pneumonia, said the
spokesman.
   Jones formerly lived in the north Alabama town of Tuscumbia but
now lives in Texas.
</TEXT>
