<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeadlyForce     08-19 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deadly Force,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dallas Police Issue Deadly Force Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officials say a need to shed more light on
their operations prompted them to make public the department's
deadly force policy for the first time.
   The policy is an amended, simplified version of a plan that has
been in effect since 1984, according to police spokesman Ed
Spencer. The revised version takes effect Monday.
   The policy states deadly force can be used ``only as a last
resort'' and ``only when other, reasonable alternatives are
impractical or fail.'' It prohibits the use of deadly force to
protect property and forbids officers from firing warning shots.
   Dallas police have drawn criticism from minority group leaders
in the past year for being too quick to shoot at suspects. Last
summer a congressional subcommittee conducted a hearing into the
department's deadly force policy, prompted by two white officers'
slayings of two elderly blacks in unrelated cases. The department
hired outside consultants to review its policy.
   ``We just feel it's important for the community to know the high
standard the police place on the use of deadly force,'' acting
Assistant Chief Marlin Price said Thursday.
   Some police had argued that releasing the policy would let
criminals know what acts they could commit without fearing
officers' use of weapons. But city officials praised the revision
and releasing it to the public.
   ``I think it indicates their (the police department's) openness
and their willingness to let us all know what the rules are,'' said
City Council member Craig Holcomb, chairman of the city's Public
Safety Committee. ``Previously, even council members ... didn't
know what the deadly force policy was.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Stalin     08-19 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stalin,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Pledges to Root Out Those Who Supported Stalin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a Politburo commission studying the
bloody history of Josef Stalin's purges pledged in an interview
published Friday to root out those who blindly carried out the
dictator's wishes.
   Mikhail S. Solomentsev told the Communist Party newspaper Pravda
that since it began its work last October the commission had
cleared the names of 636 people who were shot or imprisoned by
Stalin.
   He also revealed that an investigation was under way into the
murder in December 1934 of Sergei Kirov, the popular Leningrad
party leader who opposed Stalin's absolute power. Some Western
historians believe Stalin was responsible for the murder but
accused his political opponents in order to destroy them.
   ``Many people are guilty of abuses: some of them were named,
some not,'' Solomentsev said. ``The measure of the guilt of every
one of them will be determined.''
   ``The personal guilt of Stalin and the people closest to him
before the party and people for the mass repressions and
lawlessness is dreadful,'' he said. ``But the guilt of the leaders
does not relieve of responsibility the voluntary executors, those
directly involved in the infringement of socialist law, those who
supported and blindly fulfilled inhumane instructions, committed
outrages.''
   Stalin ruled the Soviet Union from 1924-53, and some estimates
say he was responsible for as many as 20 million deaths. Although
the senior officials who helped him are nearly all dead, other
officials who started their careers in Stalin's last years are in
positions of responsibility throughout the country.
   The issue of clearing the names of those who were repressed by
Stalin and politically rehabilitating them is one of deep
significance for Soviets.
   For many of them, it means clearing a close relative.
   Clearing Stalin's victims also gives Soviets an indication of
what direction the leadership of Mikhail S. Gorbachev wants to take
the country.
   Soviets watch their leadership's evaluation of history closely
because it very often is an indication of the party's goals.
Gorbachev has said he wants to clear those purged by Stalin to show
Soviets they have nothing to fear from speaking their minds.
   Solomentsev, 74, is head of the party Control Commission, which
reviews charges of misconduct within party ranks.
   At a Communist Party conference in Moscow at the end of June,
former Moscow party chief Boris N. Yeltsin accused him of
tolerating corruption among party workers, and another speaker
suggested he should retire.
   After Stalin's death, Soviet leader Nikita S. Khrushchev
launched the first review of the repression, but Solomentsev said
the work was not completed and did not cover abuses committed
before 1934.
   He said the commission is reviewing Soviet archives and appealed
to the public for information to help complete a thorough review of
the terror. It already has received 3,000 letters and applications
from members of the public, he said.
   ``We are equally interested in the fate of prominent leaders of
the party and the Soviet state and the rank-and-file citizens:
workers, peasants, office workers, party, government and economic
functionaries, intellectuals,'' he said.
   Solomentsev said the commission had already cleared 636 people
and that many other cases were still under review.
   Among those whose names have been cleared this year of the
criminal charges made against them by Stalin's prosecutors are
prominent Bolsheviks Nikolai Bukharin, Grigory Zinoviev and Lev
Kamenev. Each was a rival for the power that Stalin took for
himself.
   They and many other prominent figures were shot or died in
prison camps during Stalin's purges of the 1930s.
   Sixty-eight people have been readmitted to party rolls,
including Bukharin, whose economic polices serve as a model for
some of Gorbachev's reforms.
   Restoration of party membership is the final act of
rehabilitating those repressed by Stalin because it establishes not
only that they were not guilty of criminal actions but that their
political views were acceptable within the party.
   Among Stalin's victims were hundreds of thousands of Balts,
Crimean Tatars and ethnic Germans accused during World War II of
collaborating with Nazi occupiers.
   Stalin also ordered the brutal drive for collectivization of
agriculture in the 1930s, when peasants who refused to leave their
land for state farms were shot as examples to others and hundreds
of thousands starved to death.
   The commission is reviewing requests of relatives to compensate
them for the suffering of their families by giving them better
apartments, benefits and returning confiscated property, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
