<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Massacre 1stLd-Writethru a0675 08-19 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Massacre, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quiet Grief On Anniversary Of Worst British Mass Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with Sylvester Stallone calling off
trip, no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HUNGERFORD, Britain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town of Hungerford grieved
quietly Friday, the first anniversary of the worst mass murder in
modern British history in which a man killed 16 people and wounded
13 others before committing suicide.
   The streets of the market town 60 miles west of London were
nearly deserted and most of its shops were closed. A small vase of
flowers sat on the Town Hall steps and its flag flew at half-staff.
   ``People just want to try to put the past behind them and look
towards the future,'' said the Rev. David Salt, the local Church of
England vicar.
   ``Most of the bereaved are away from the town today. They just
want to be with themselves at this time.''
   A former mayor, Ron Tarry, said ``today is hopefully the final
chapter in this tragedy. The people of Hungerford now hope they can
get on with their lives without being in the press and on TV.''
   Michael Ryan, a 27-year-old unemployed loner and gun enthusiast,
stalked the streets and parks of his hometown and surrounding
countryside for seven hours Aug. 19, 1987, shooting neighbors and
strangers with an arsenal of weapons.
   He killed 16 of them, including his mother, wounded another 13,
shot his dog to death, and burned down his mother's home and two
others before holing up in an empty school. When police surrounded
the building and tried to talk him into surrendering, he killed
himself.
   Ryan left no suicide note to explain the massacre. Neighbors
said he was deeply affected by his father's death two years earlier
and psychiatrists speculated he suffered from acute schizophrenia.
   Some of those affected by the tragedy are still receiving
counseling from a special family support unit set up within hours
of the shootings.
   ``It is a hard day for a lot of people,'' said the unit's
coordinator, Tony Stacey, a retired social worker. ``Many would
rather be out of town. Any reminder of what happened is going to be
hard for people.''
   Britain's rough-and-tumble popular press dubbed the killer
``Rambo,'' after the bellicose movie character played by actor
Sylvester Stallone.
   Stallone called off his trip to Britain, scheduled to begin
Saturday, said his London publicist Bernard Doherty. The visit was
intended to promote the movie ``Rambo III.''
   Doherty said the decision stemmed from changes in the movie's
pre-production schedule _ not British complaints related to the
anniversary of the murders.
   Mary Whitehouse, an outspoken media critic, had called
Stallone's planned visit ``insensitive.'' The local member of
Parliament, Michael McNair-Wilson, had also urged Stallone to
reconsider his schedule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
