<DOCNO> AP880819-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Vincennes-ThenAndNow     08-19 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes-Then And Now,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Defends Early, Erroneous Account of Shootdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vincennes Report Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said
Friday he is glad the Pentagon came forward with a detailed account
of the July 3 Iran airline disaster on the day it occurred even
though several key details were wrong.
   A final investigative report released Friday found that
inexperience and the stress of battle _ ``the fog of war'' _ led
the crew of the Vincennes to reach several erroneous conclusions,
which Carlucci and Adm. William Crowe, chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, in turn had reported as fact.
   The conclusions included:
   _The airliner was transmitting a signal identifying it as a
warplane.
   _The plane was outside a commercial air corridor.
   _It was descending and accelerating as it approached the
Vincennes, a flight pattern similar to that of an attacking fighter.
   Those mistakes have been at the heart of the controversy over
why the USS Vincennes mistook an Iran Air A-300 Airbus for an F-14
fighter and shot it down, killing all 290 people aboard.
   Carlucci told a Pentagon news conference Friday that ``on the
day that the incident occurred, Admiral Crowe appeared before you
and made available virtually every scrap of information that he had
in our possession. This was a deliberate decision.''
   ``And Admiral Crowe stated repeatedly that our initial
information was preliminary and very likely to prove false in some
instances. Nonetheless, we decided to go ahead with it, running the
risk that there would be stories that the Pentagon had put out
mistaken information,'' Carlucci said.
   On July 3, Crowe told reporters that Iran Air Flight 655 was
outside a commercial air corridor and was descending and
accelerating.
   The final report found that ``IR 655 was not an the exact center
of airway A-59, but was 3.37 nautical miles west of the centerline.
However, it was in the assigned airway.''
   And it said that ``at no time did IR 655 actually descend in
altitude prior to engagement.''
   Crowe also said on July 3 that the airplane was was emitting
electronic signals that led the Vincennes to conclude that the
plane was an F-14.
   Several days later, Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard told reporters
the Airbus had been broadcasting its position on a device known as
an Identification Friend or Foe (IFF) transponder in Mode 3, used
by both civilian and military aircraft, and in Mode 2, used only by
military aircraft.
   The final report said the Mode 2 reading was a mistake, and that
human error apparently led operators aboard the Vincennes to
receive an IFF signal from a military aircraft at the Bandar Abbas
airfield, from which Flight 655 took off, and mistakenly conclude
that the Airbus was military.
   That initial error led to the identification of the airliner as
hostile just over three minutes into its flight, and was not
corrected during the remaining three minutes and 40 seconds before
it was blasted from the sky by two SM-2 Standard missiles from the
Vincennes.
   Because the operator apparently failed to adjust the IFF
receiver aboard the Vincennes to account for the approach of the
aircraft, the report said, ``the Mode 2 transmission from an
aircraft on the ground would then be displayed'' and ``could have
been generated by a military aircraft (C-130, F-4, F-14) located on
the ground at Bandar Abbas.''
   The crew of the Vincennes may have made the mistakes, the report
said, because they were fighting Iranian gunboats, were heeling
over at a 32-degree angle while maneuvering to fight off the boats,
and had in their minds the attack by Iraq on May 17, 1987 against
the USS Stark in which 37 American sailors died.
   ``The fog of war and those human elements which affect each
individual differently _ not the least of which was the thought of
the Stark incident _ are factors that must be considered,'' the
report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
