<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LandlordBias     08-19 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Landlord Bias,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landlord Pays $12,000 for Discriminating Against Couple With
Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord who allegedly denied an apartment to a
couple because they had children has agreed to pay them $12,000
compensation, the Boston Fair Housing Commission said.
   ``A settlement of this type sends out the message that children
have fair housing rights _ and that in the city of Boston, we're
enforcing those rights,'' said the commission's executive director,
Ernest B. Gutierrez Jr.
   Gayle and Donald Guilford, both 34, had sought to rent a
three-bedroom apartment in Boston for themselves and their four
daughters, ages 1, 2, 12 and 14.
   A real estate agent told the Guilfords the apartment was
available, but, Gutierrez said, landlord Gary Gwozdzik rejected the
Guilfords, allegedly violating a 1982 city ordinance prohibiting
discrimination against families with children.
   The Guilford's attorney, Nadine Cohen, said Gwozdzik told the
couple ``that he would not rent to them because of their children.''
   But the landlord's attorney, Stephen A. Greenbaum, said his
client ``vehemently denies ever discriminating'' against the
Guilfords.
   Greenbaum said his ``client, who is an average working guy who
owns a total of five apartment units in the whole world, has to pay
his own legal fees, and he simply could not afford the cost of
litigating this case out through the Fairing Housing Commission and
the courts.''
   Greenbaum said Gwozdzik rejected the Guilfords as tenants
because he thought six people were too many for the apartment.
   Under state sanitary codes, three bedrooms are adequate for a
family of six.
   The settlement was reached Monday.
</TEXT>
