<HEAD>Pinochet Says Presidential Referendum To Be Held In Early October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet said Chile's
single-candidate presidential referendum will take place in early
October.
   Gen. Pinochet, who has ruled since a 1973 military coup, is
widely expected to be the lone candidate.
   In a separate appearance Wednesday, Pinochet also flatly
dismissed requests by the Roman Catholic Church for appointment of
a ``candidate of consensus,'' acceptable both to the government and
the opposition.
   The candidate will be nominated on Aug. 30 by the comanders of
the three armed services and the national police. If the candidate
wins, he will serve an eight-year term starting March 11, 1989. If
he is rejected, Pinochet will remain in power until an open
election on Dec. 14, 1989.
   As commander in chief of the army, the 72-year-old Pinochet will
participate in the candidate's selection.
   Other officials have hinted that Chile's first presidential
balloting in 18 years will be on Oct. 5.
