<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Pollution     08-19 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Pollution,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Algae Slicks Scare Off Tourists, Kill Fish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERO VALSECCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smelly, slimy slicks of algae along Italy's
northern Adriatic coast are scaring away tourists, killing fish and
sparking cries for an end to the dumping of untreated wastes into
the sea.
   Mayors of seaside resorts in the Romagna region _ with its
jammed beach establishments one next to the other _ say tourists
have fled and reservations for the rest of the season are down. The
algae problem is only getting worse.
   ``It's like swimming in mash,'' said Alberta De Lorenzi, a
Milanese who took vacation near the resort of Rimini. ``My children
swim in the hotel pool. The algae make tough going on
paddle-boats.''
   Authorities say the decaying algae won't make bathers ill.
   Algae thrive on raw sewage and certain chemical pollutants,
including phosphates from detergents. Both are being dumped into
the sea off the northeastern coast of Italy. The Po River is
estimated to carry more than 4,000 tons of phosphates into the
Adriatic every year.
   The multiplying algae consume the sea's oxygen, which in turn
kills the fish. The foul odor from the decaying fish makes the
beach even less inviting.
   This problem was especially bad off the coast at Chioggia and
Ravenna, a big tourist draw with its magnificent, well-preserved
mosaics. Other stricken areas include Venice and Pesaro, a music
festival town in the Marche region and a favorite vacation haunt
for West Germans.
   Some action is being taken.
   Environment Minister Giorgio Ruffolo said a bill would be
presented in Parliament that would set the volume of phosphates in
cleaning products at 1 percent instead of the current 2.5 percent.
   Mayors of Adriatic resort towns urged the government to enforce
laws that prohibit industry and farms from dumping untreated
pollutants into the sea.
   They also are demanding a state of emergency and more money to
clear the waters of decaying algae. Last month, the national
government set aside the equivalent of $2.2 million to help Venice
fight its algae problem.
   ``We risk ruining the tourist season and producing thousands of
unemployed,'' Nando Fabbri, the mayor of Bellaria, told Turin's
daily La Stampa.
   Bruno Casadei, professor of ecology problems at the University
of Urbino, not far from Pesaro, predicted the situation will worsen.
   ``Slow-moving currents and shallow depth will turn the Adriatic
into a permanent sludge,'' he said. Those factors make it difficult
for the sea to flush itself clean of the pollutants, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     08-19 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty People Killed In Civil War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil separatist fighting killed 20
people, with most of the deaths occurring when Indian soldiers
enforcing a peace accord stormed two rebel encampments, official
reports said Friday.
   Victims of those raids included 11 Tamils, who are fighting for
an independent homeland in the northern and eastern provinces of
the troubled island, and one Indian trooper, the reports said.
   A Sri Lankan soldier and six civilians also were killed during
the time period, the reports said.
   Tamils, who comprise about 18 percent of the country's 16
million people, say they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese who control the government.
   The 11 guerrillas were killed Thursday when Indian troops
stormed a rebel camp near Cheddikulam, about 135 miles north of the
capital of Colombo, said an official for the Indian High Commission
or embassy.
   India has 47,000 Indian soldiers in Sri Lanka to oversee a peace
agreement aimed at ending the 5-year-old civil war.
   About seven miles south of the first base, Indian troops stormed
an abandoned rebel camp in the jungle, said the Indian official,
who asked not to be identified. One soldier was killed and two
injured by hidden explosives.
   Indian officials said 10 Tamil guerrillas were injured and 60
captured in the two operations.
   Indian troops near Jaffna, about 185 miles north of Colombo,
shot and killed three Tamil civilians Thursday, said a spokesman
for the Sri Lankan Joint Operations Command.
   The troops opened fire after Tamil guerrillas ambushed an Indian
patrol, killing one soldier and seriously injuring three others,
the spokesman said.
   He said a Sri Lankan army lieutenant was killed and another
lietuenant seriously injured in an ambush by insurgents in
Trincomalee, about 145 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Sinhalese extremists killed three civilians Thursday in Elkaduwa
village, 80 miles south of Colombo, the spokesman said.
   The militants wielding guns and swords stormed a funeral home,
chose their victims and then hacked them to death, he said. They
also threatened to kill others who suppported the Sri Lankan
government.
   Authorities said the killers belong to the Sinhalese People's
Liberation Front, which has killed more than 420 people in the past
12 months. Most of the victims have been Sinhalese who support the
government of President Junius R. Jayewardeene and the
Indian-brokered peace accord signed in 1987 to try to end the
5-year-old civil war.
   Members of the front oppose the peace plan saying it grants too
many concessions to the Tamils.
   Moderate Tamils have been demanding self-rule in the north and
east. Extremists, however, want a separate state and have killed
more than 8,500 in their campaign.
</TEXT>
