<DOCNO> AP880819-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     08-19 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Will Permit Marcos to Come Home to Face Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said Friday
she will abide by a legal ruling that would allow former president
Ferdinand Marcos to come home in November to face an accuser in
court.
   Marcos said Friday he will ask to do so.
   Presidential spokesman Marcial Carreon quoted Mrs. Aquino as
saying she would ``respect the decision of the court,'' even if it
meant allowing Marcos to return.
   Marcos has lived in Hawaii since his ouster in a 1986
civilian-military uprising. Mrs. Aquino has refused to let him
return, citing security concerns. Her government put down a coup
attempt in January 1987, which she said was aimed at restoring
Marcos to power.
   An anti-graft court ruled Thursday that the ousted president had
a right to be present when his former public works secretary
testifies against him about questionable contracts awarded during
his 20-year presidency.
   The Nov. 7 hearing is not a trial but a ``perpetuation
proceeding'' to take testimony from former government minister
Baltazar Aquino, who court officials say is gravely ill.
   Baltazar Aquino, who is not related to the president, is to
testify about allegedly illegal contracts granted to Japanese firms
during Marcos' reign.
   Under Philippine law, his testimony can be used against Marcos
at a trial, even if the witness is dead. But Justice Augusto Amores
said the testimony could be used in court only if Marcos had the
opportunity to cross-examine the witness.
   The court said Marcos had the constitutional right to appear at
the proceedings, ``which cannot be denied to him in the absence of
more cogent reasons.'' Amores said Marcos could appear personally
or be represented by counsel.
   ``I directed my lawyer to seek the court order for me to come
home and defend myself in the proceedings,'' Marcos told Filipino
reporters by telephone from his exile home in Hawaii. ``I want to
represent myself,'' said Marcos, who is a lawyer.
   Marcos said his former minister had been pressured into agreeing
to testify because of his poor health.
   Solicitor-General Francisco Chavez said he opposed allowing
Marcos to come home and believed his presence was unnecessary if he
were represented by counsel.
   ``There are questions of national security,'' Chavez said.
``It's not a purely legal question.''
   Marcos has never been charged with any criminal offense, despite
allegations of wrongdoing while in office. Marcos has warned that
if criminal charges are filed, he would dismiss his lawyer, Rafael
Recto, and demand the right to represent himself.
   Philippine law allows defendants to be represented by counsel of
their choice and bars criminal trials in absentia. Government
sources say those regulations are largely responsible for the delay
in filing criminal charges against Marcos.
   Swiss authorities have expressed reluctance in lifting banking
secrecy laws until criminal charges against Marcos are filed. The
Philippine government believes Marcos stashed millions of dollars
in secret Swiss bank accounts, although he denies the claim.
   In its ruling, the court authorized the Philippine consul in
Honolulu to serve notice of the proceedings to Marcos and to
publish the announcement in newspapers there for three consecutive
weeks.
   In May, Mrs. Aquino turned down a request by Marcos to return
here for the burial of his mother, Josefa, who died May 4.
   The body of Marcos' mother is unburied. Marcos said her burial
would be ``my first duty'' after his return.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
