<HEAD>Bombs Injure Five Civil Guards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EIBAR, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded near civil guard patrol
cars in northern Spain, injuring five paramilitary guards,
officials said.
   A civil guard spokesman told Spanish National Radio that the
Basque terrorist group ETA was suspected in both attacks. He said
guards were searching for more bombs.
   The first explosion occurred as a three-car civil guard convoy
reached a crossroads near Eibar, 12 miles south of the Basque
coastal city of San Sebastian, a civil governor's office spokesman
said.
   Three guards were treated for burns as a result of the blast,
which scattered shrapnel and hurled the middle patrol car into a
cement wall, the spokesman said.
   Three hours later, officials said a second bomb exploded 25
miles west near the town of Aracaldo, as a civil guard vehicle went
under a bridge. That blast injured two guards, one seriously.
   ETA, which stands for Homeland and Liberty in the Basque
language, has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600
people since taking up arms in 1968. Most were paramilitary civil
guards, police and military officers.
   This year, ETA has claimed responsibility for attacks that
killed six people.
