<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--SuperdomeBreakdown     08-19 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Superdome Breakdown,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metamorphosis Under Way At Superdome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asssociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Louisiana Superdome's metamorphosis from
a place for presidential politics back to the world's largest
indoor football stadium was in full swing Friday.
   What took weeks to build for the Republican National Convention,
which ended Thursday night, will take a few days to tear down.
   ``It's almost sad,'' said Will Peneguy, a Superdome spokesman.
``We watched them put the podium up, there was so much detail work,
craftsmanship. It was sad even then knowing it was going to have to
come down.''
   A backhoe chomped down on the $560,000 podium, from which George
Bush had accepted the GOP presidential nomination the night before,
smashing it to smithereens in minutes.
   Greg Lane, operations manager for The Freeman Cos., watched the
backhoe operator demolish his firm's hard work without so much as a
sigh.
   ``We're in the convention business, so no, it's not (sad),'' he
said.
   It will take 8,000 man-hours to rip up the 1.2 million pounds of
scaffolding, tear up the 150,000 square feet of plywood and take
out the 150,000 nuts, bolts and screws that made up the podium,
stairways and wooden floors.
   The red carpets New Orleans rolled out for the GOP had been
pulled up from the Dome floor and the decorative trees were being
hauled out on trolleys.
   A few of Thursday night's red, white and blue balloons were
still mixed in with the broken-down scaffolding and scrap lumber
being carted off.
   Confetti dusted the floors and handmade Bush-Quayle signs were
crammed into garbage cans.
   ``I think it looks a lot different from last night,'' said Bobby
Franks, operations manager for South Central Bell Telephone Co.
``What you have here is a transformation from the Republican
National Convention look to the football stadium look, and it will
end up looking like the magnificent building that it is.''
   South Central Bell worked from midnight Thursday to 8 a.m.,
tearing down the thousands of feet of cable installed for the
convention.
   The convention required 9,000 lines of cable compared with the
last major Dome event, a Super Bowl with 1,000 cable lines.
   The Dome must be restored to its former self by Thursday, Lane
said.
   ``Everything's going right on schedule,'' Peneguy said. ``We'd
like it finished in time for the Gatorade Jamboree (a prep football
doubleheader) on Friday.''
   The following day, Aug. 27, the New Orleans Saints host the
Pittsburgh Steelers at the Superdome in their final preseason
National Football League game.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
