<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Czech     08-19 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Czech,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Defends Intervention in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's intervention that crushed
Czechoslovakia's ``Prague Spring'' 20 years ago saved the country
from irresponsible leadership and possible brutual repression of
communists, Tass said Friday.
   A commentary by the official Soviet news agency was the first
comment by the Soviets on the anniversary of the Aug. 20-21, 1968,
crushing of a liberalization campaign in Czechoslovakia by the
Soviet Union.
   ``Anti-socialist forces, taking advantage of political
irresponsibilty and opportunism of a part of the leadership of the
Communist Party of Czechoslovakia of that time, made an attempt ...
to tear Czechoslovakia away from the socialist community,'' Tass
said. ``The friends and allies of socialist Czechoslovakia could
not remain indifferent,'' it said.
   ``Czechoslovak society was threatened with a possibility that
accounts would be settled with upright communists in a brutal
way,'' Tass said.
   The commentary by news analyst Alexander Kondrashov was
consistent with past Soviet statements on the ``Prague Spring,''
but contrasted sharply with an article in the current issue of the
weekly Arguments and Facts.
   In the article, historian L.S. Yagodovsky compared the goals of
the Czechoslovak reforms with those efforts by Mikhail S. Gorbachev
in the Soviet Union. Yagodovsky also drew the conclusion that the
intervention by soldiers from the Soviet Union and Warsaw Pact
allies was necessary because Czechoslovak leaders could not control
the reform movement.
   Gorbachev is trying to loosen state control of the Soviet
economy, while encouraging more open discussion of current policy
and past mistakes.
   The intervention stopped the liberalization campaign begun under
Czechoslovak leader Alexander Dubcek, who was replaced the
following year by Gustav Husak.
   Husak ran one of the more conservative Soviet bloc organizations
until he stepped down late last year.
   Tass said calls from the West for the Soviet Union to admit it
made a mistake in Czechoslovakia ``have the aim to question not
only the policy of the U.S.S.R. and of Czechoslovakia but also the
entire process of positive changes in the world.''
   American leaders such as President Lyndon B. Johnson were
interested in tearing Czechoslovakia away from the Soviet Union
rather than the actual changes taking place in the country, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
