<DOCNO> AP880819-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0651 08-19 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conventions Behind Them, National Party Tickets Hit Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New material in top 12 grafs; pickup 5th prv, ``Adopting a
xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Dan Quayle went back home to Quayle's Indiana on
Friday where the young vice presidential candidate defended his
National Guard service in a news conference amplified for an
appreciative town folk.
   The tougher the question, the louder the boos.
   The more forceful the answer, the louder the cheers.
   ``I got into the National Guard fairly,'' he said. ``I did not
ask anyone to break the rules and so far as I know no one did.''
   The Indianapolis News had reported Thursday that its former
managing editor, Wendell C. Phillippi, had been asked about
entering the Guard by Quayle.
   Phillippi was a former commander of the state National Guard.
   ``Wendell Phillippi knew that I wanted to get into the National
Guard and I hope that he helped me and I think he did,'' Quayle
told reporters. ``I would hope that he helped me and I expect
that.''
   But the 41-year-old, two-term senator said he saw nothing wrong
with that and would do the same thing again.
   With the Republican ticket riding a wave of optimism out of the
just-ended GOP convention in New Orleans, the Democratic duo of
Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen were going their separate ways
before linking up Saturday in Texas.
   Bentsen said the GOP convention looked to him like a ``Mardi
Gras for the Moral Majority'' that ignored the concerns of working
people.
   Dukakis, meanwhile, was playing a similar tune on a whistle-stop
trip through the scenic hills of Missouri and Arkansas.
   Before leaving New Orleans, Quayle joked about the controversy
when he and Bush appeared at a post-convention meeting of the
Republican National Committee in New Orleans.
   Adopting a military posture, his shoulders sqaured, his back
straight, Quayle shouted in a clipped voice: ``I stand at
attention. Name: Dan Quayle. Serial number: 303 50 4096. Indiana
National Guard, six years and proud of it.''
   The audience laughed and cheered.
   The conservative senator from Indiana, has been dogged by
questions about whether he used family influence to get into the
National Guard at the height of the Vietnam War, virtually assuring
he would avoid combat.
   Dukakis, on a whistle-stop train tour through Illinois, Missouri
and Arkansas, lost no time jibing at Bush's performance in New
Orleans.
   ``Last night we heard a lot of talk about missions,'' Dukakis
said at a trackside rally in Belleville, Ill.
   ``He talked a lot about missions, but I must have missed a
page,'' he said. ``We didn't hear a word from the Republicans about
the budget deficit or the trade deficit last night, or this week,
and we know why. They don't know how to deal with them.''
   Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, was in Dallas
where he said the Republican convention was dominated by the ``hard
right.''
   ``What we saw was the Republicans putting on a convention for
the far right,'' Bentsen said. ``They had a Mardi Gras for the
Moral Majority.''
   Bentsen also was asked about a report in Friday's Washington
Post that his blind trust invested in his son's business after
being steered there by the senator.
   He said he reported the trust's investment in his son's company.
``Frankly, I didn't have to report it,'' Bentsen said.
   He said his wife's position as a trustee on a mutual fund
affiliated with the manager of his trust in no way compromised the
blind trust. ``No, not at all, absolutely not,'' he said.
   He said his wife was one of the directors representing the
stockholders and not the management. ``It's almost an adversarial
relationship,'' he said.
   Bush and Quayle were ebullient when they showed up for the early
morning meeting of the Republican National Committee.
   ``Now we start,'' said Bush. ``Now comes the beginning of the
end, and last night there was a shifting of the gears.'' The
nominee said that he had received a congratulatory telephone call
from President Reagan last night after accepting the GOP
presidential nomination.
   ``We are going to win this election,'' he predicted.
   Bush told the Republicans ``You have given us a tremendous
sendoff. I can't think of a better way to get out of town.''
   Republicans were generally upbeat and giving rave reviews to
Bush's big speech.
   ``He hit it. He hit it out of the park,'' exulted Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato of New York. ``For me, it was (a question of) survival, the
speech of his life and he did it.'' Massachusetts delegate Joyce
Hampers called it ``a grand slam.''
   Nebraska Gov. Kay Orr said: ``It was a sensitive speech because
he was so strong and yet so sensitive. He showed that he is attuned
to the American people. I believe he revealed a George Bush people
have not yet seen and had a chance to appreciate.''
   The GOP also got good news from the latest polls which said the
race was a dead heat after months in which Dukakis led by as much
as 17 points in most surveys.
   A CNN-USA Today poll of 1,087 registered voters Wednesday put
the race at 45 percent for Bush and Quayle to 43 percent for
Dukakis and Bentsen.
   A second CNN-USA Today poll, of 842 registered voters Thursday
night put the race at 45 for Bush-Quayle to 44 for Dukakis-Bentsen.
The spreads were within the polls' margins of error _ three points
in the first poll, four in the second.
</TEXT>
