<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Michigan     08-19 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Michigan,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Of Michigan Declared Eligible for Emergency Drought Loans</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Retransmitting a0740 to correct header</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers in all of Michigan are eligible to
apply for Farmers Home Admininstration emergency loans to help
cover part of their crop drought losses, the Agriculture Department
said Friday.
   Undersecretary Roland Vautour said farmers in all of the state's
83 counties have eight months in which to apply for the loans to
cover part of their actual losses.
   To be eligible, farmers must be able to repay the FmHA loans and
any other loans, must be unable to get credit elsewhere, and have
adequate security.
   Michigan is the 14th entire state designated eligible for FmHA
emergency drought loans. Others are Alabama, Delaware, Illinois,
Indiana, Iowa, Maryland, Missouri, New Jersey, North Dakota, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and West Virginia.
</TEXT>
