<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SteelPlant-Iraq     08-19 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Plant-Iraq,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Says Sale Not A Security Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's proposed purchase of an idle Texas
steel plant from USX Corp. appears to raise no national security
questions, a Commerce Department official said Friday.
   ``The technology is very old, very outmoded,'' said the
official, adding that department officials ``don't anticipate any
national security issues to be involved.''
   The official spoke on condition he not be identified.
   A Justice Department spokesman, Mark Sheehan, said the
department was taking a preliminary look at whether the proposed
sale warranted an antitrust investigation.
   Rep. Jack Fields, R-Texas, who strongly opposes the deal, said
Iraq's ambassador to the United States, Abdul-Amir al-Anbari, had
told him a $1 million downpayment already had been made to USX, a
Pittsburgh-based steel and energy concern.
   Fields represents a district near Houston that includes the
Baytown steel plant. He has asked President Reagan, the Justice
Department, the Pentagon and the Commerce Department to investigate
the proposed sale on grounds that it poses national security risks
and that it would unlawfully limit domestic competition.
   ``I am convinced USX is trying to keep the price of steel slab
and steel plate high,'' Fields said.
   William P. Ryder, a USX spokesman, confirmed that negotiations
to sell the steel plant to Iraq were under way, but he would not
comment on a New York Times report that Iraq was willing to pay
$100 million for the 20-year-old equipment.
   The Times report said Iraq had indicated it wanted the
steelmaking equipment to help expand production in its oil fields,
which are linked to an extensive network of pipelines.
   Efforts to reach officials at the Iraqi Embassy in Washington on
Friday were unsuccessful.
   Fields claimed two U.S. companies were ready to pay a price
comparable to the Iraqi offer. He identified them as Major
Financial Services Corp. of Tallahassee, Fla., and Birmingham Steel
Corp. of Birmingham, Ala.
   Fields said USX had ``made statements that have led me to
believe they ... really do not want to sell to an American company.
They want to remove capacity, it keeps their prices high.''
   Ryder said the company would not respond to Fields' claims.
   Fields said he was concerned that USX would be exporting ``state
of the art armorizing technology which is used for tanks and other
military applications.''
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Lt. Col. Keith Schneider said, ``On
the surface it is not a defense issue.''
   The plant, which once employed as many as 2,000 people, was shut
down two years ago amid labor turmoil and declining demand for
steel. It had produced up to 1.3 million tons a year of
large-diameter pipe used for U.S. oil and natural gas pipelines.
   The works includes electric furnaces for melting scrap, casters
to shape molten steel into slabs and a mill for making slabs into
oil drilling pipe.
   Fields said 750 people could be employed if the plant were
reopened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-19 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The usual lunch-hour rumble on the steps of the
New York Public Library was interrupted Friday by these sounds:
``Gulp. Gulp. Gulp. Gulp. Gulp.''
   And then: ``Definitely A. I like Rockland County water, but A
was better,'' said Caesar Ortonio, one of 75 people who drank five
3-ounce cups of water in a taste test to determine New York state's
finest H2O.
   The winner _ and the one selected by Ortonio _ came from the
South Huntington Water District on Long Island. The runner-up was
New York City, said Manoj Ajmera of the state Bureau of Public
Water Supply Protection.
   ``This is really to create public interest in our water
supply,'' Ajmera said before the games began. ``We've taken water
for granted for many, many years.''
   In the competition were Kingston, Millbrook, South Huntington,
New Rochelle and New York City; South Huntington and the city
advance to the next round. Missing from this regional race was
defending champion Hoosick Falls, which captured the first-ever
crown last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Mel Silverlake has been racing pigs
with names like ``Hambo'' and ``Magnum P.I.G.'' for three years and
has concluded the porkers are natural actors.
   ``I'm sure pigs are responsible for the phrase `he's a real
ham,' '' said Silverlake, a Medora, Ind., native and swine master
of Robinson's Racing Pigs. ``They know they're on, and they love to
entertain.''
   Silverlake, who travels the fair circuit with his wife, B.K.,
took his pigs and his makeshift track, Pork Chop Downs, to the
Indiana State Fair this week.
   ``They're not racing for the money, the flowers or the glory.
They're racing because they love it,'' said Silverlake, who
estimates he drew more than 21,000 people daily to the grandstand
at the Wisconsin State Fair in Milwaukee last week.
   Although Silverlake swears his pigs are innately competitive,
there's no doubt the troops are rallied by the 50-calorie cookie
waiting at the finish line.
   ``The pigs know the winner gets the cookie and the loser gets
the crumbs,'' says the swine impressario, decked out in red checks
and a handlebar mustache. ``That's the way it is in life, and
that's the way it is in the pig races.''
</TEXT>
