<DOCNO> AP880819-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StolenMail 1stLd-Writethru a0671 08-19 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen Mail, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0671,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tons Of Mail Stashed At Carrier's Home, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with news conference, CORRECT
estimate from six to five tons.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede MILTON, Fla.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal inspectors used a front-end loader
Friday to remove the last of some five tons of undelivered mail
found piled at and near the home of a rural mail carrier, and a
prosecutor said an indictment will be sought.
   ``I've seen this type of thing before, but never of this
magnitude,'' said postal Inspector Richard Jordan. ``Right now,
we're overwhelmed.''
   The Postal Service doesn't keep statistics on the size of such
thefts so there was no way to compare it to previous incidents,
said Dean Nichols, a postal inspector in Birmingham, Ala.
   An estimated 500,000 pieces of mail up to three years old were
discovered, said Pensacola Postmaster Ben Jasek. Most of it was
third-class bulk mail, but between 500 and 600 pieces of
first-class mail, primarily for customers who had moved and which
should have been forwarded, also were discovered. None of it
appeared to have been opened, Jordan said.
   Officials declined to release the identity of the carrier, who
worked out of a post office in Pensacola for three years but lived
in nearby Milton.
   Federal prosecutors will seek a indictment against the carrier
for obstruction of the mail, a felony with a five-year maximum
prison term, and possibly other charges, Jordan said at a news
conference.
   The carrier, who has worked for the Postal Service for 15 years,
has been placed on administrative leave without pay pending
completion of the investigation, officials said.
   ``This incident is a slap in the face to our customers, the
public,'' said Jasek, who became postmaster here only three weeks
ago. ``We are angry, dismayed and confused that one of our
co-workers could do such a thing.''
   The suspect, who is in his 50s, apparently acted alone, Jasek
said. He said the employee is unmarried but declined to answer
whether he lived alone. No motive has been established.
   Jasek said he was surprised the carrier's 500 rural customers
didn't notice their mail missing. The post office had never
received any complaints, he said.
   ``This is a fluke. All I can say is that rural carriers are kind
of their own entity,'' he said.
   The raid began Monday after a tip from a neighbor. By Thursday,
investigators said they had collected several truckloads of
magazines, catalogs, sweepstakes offers, circulars, free mail
samples and other items piled in the carrier's house, packed into a
storage shed and littering the surrounding woods.
   Jordan said more mail _ some of it three years old and badly
deteriorated _ was collected Friday.
   William Read, communications manager for the Postal Service's
New Orleans division, said the exact amount hadn't yet been
determined but that 16 hampers, each with about 260 pounds of mail,
hauled to a warehouse by Thursday was about the midpoint. The
recovered mail was trucked to a Pensacola warehouse.
   Investigators were sorting the mail and contacting each mailer
to see if they still want it delivered. Some of it will be held as
evidence and the rest will be destroyed.
   ``We hate to destroy it, but some is just undeliverable,''
Jordan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FedPolicy     08-19 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed Policy,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solid Majority of Fed Board Approved Tighter Credit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By an 8-3 vote, Federal Reserve policy-makers
decided in late June to push interest rates up further in an effort
to fight inflation, according to minutes of the discussions
released Friday.
   The further credit tightening was approved with the three
dissenters complaining that they believed the central bank was
moving too quickly in its inflation-fighting efforts.
   The majority of Fed officials, however, called for the central
bank to ``increase slightly'' its restraint on the reserves held by
commerical banks. Lowering the amount of cash banks have available
to back loans drives up the interest rates charged on those loans.
   Since late March, the central bank has engaged in a series of
credit tightening moves in reaction to a surprisingly strong
economy which has made job markets tighter and increased
inflationary pressures this year.
   Last week, the central bank boosted its discount rate by
one-half percentage point to 6.5 percent. An increase in the
discount rate is the most dramatic signal the central bank can send
of its intention to drive interest rates higher as a way of
dampening demand and thus fighting inflationary pressures.
   The increase in the discount rate was approved on a unanimous
vote. However, back in late June, Fed policy-makers were divided on
what their next step should be.
   Board governors Wayne Angell, Martha Seger and Edward Kelley Jr.
opposed the tightening move, arguing that the Fed should wait to
see the impact of its earlier tightening efforts before going
farther.
   But the majority contended that further immediate tightening was
needed, arguing that there were ``substantial risks'' involved in
not moving forcefully to combat inflation. Some Fed members argued
for an even bolder tightening step than the one taken, arguing for
an immediate increase in the discount rate, an action the central
bank eventually took on Aug. 9.
   Fed policy-makers met again behind closed doors on Tuesday to
assess monetary policy. The minutes of that meeting will not be
released until Sept. 23. But many private economists believe the
central bank decided to continue pushing interest rates higher in
an effort to slow an economy where demand pressures are bumping up
against tight labor markets and capacity restraints.
   These analysts, however, are not looking for a further boost in
the discount rate until after Nov. 8 because of election-year
pressures.
   The Fed tightening so far has pushed up a variety of interest
rates, including banks' prime lending rate, which is now at 10
percent, the first time it has been in double-digits in three years.
   Mortgage rates have been rising as well. The Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. reported Friday that fixed-rate mortgages now stand
at 10.71 percent, up from 10.57 percent last week. Analysts are
predicting fixed-rate mortgages will soon top 11 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1753EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u x NYBiz     08-19 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>NY Biz</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AM-Fed Policy,480</HEAD>
<HEAD>Solid Majority of Fed Board Approved Tighter Credit</HEAD>
