<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Turkey-HamRecall     08-19 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Ham Recall,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Star Foods Recalls Turkey, Ham Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Star Foods Inc., of St. Charles, Minn.,
has issued a voluntary nationwide recall of an estimated 200,000
pounds of turkey products and ham because they are undercooked, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   If eaten, the undercooked turkey could cause salmonellosis, a
form of food poisoning, and the ham could cause trichinosis, which
can be caused by microscopic parasitic worms in infected pork.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said no illnesses have been reported.
   The recalled products include turkey bologna, oven-cooked turkey
breast, white and dark turkey rolls, cured turkey thigh meat,
cooked turkey drumstick, and cooked ham.
   These products are manufactured in bulk for slicing and are sold
in 3{- to 18-pound packages, primarily to delicatessens, hospitals,
institutions, hotels and other distributors that slice the product
before using, he said.
   The turkey products can be identified by the brand name North
Star and bear the establishment code Est. P8191 inside the USDA
inspection seal on the label.
   Also being recalled are Pioneer Brand Oven Prepared Turkey
Breast and EMGE Brand Oven Prepared Turkey Breast With Broth, which
are prepared by North Star and distributed by EMGE Packing Co.,
Inc., Fort Branch, Ind. These products also bear the establishment
code Est. P8191 inside the USDA inspection seal.
   The hams can be identified by the North Star brand name and
haave the code Est. 8191 inside the USDA seal. The hams weigh 9
pounds.
   Officials said the recall applies only to products produced
before Aug. 3. Any consumer, deli or institution holding these
products should return them to the place of purchase.
   Crawford said that consumers who have bought such products
without the original packaging from a delicatessen or other
institution should ask the seller whether the product came from
North Star Foods, Est. P8191 or 8191.
   Salmonella bacteria may be present in turkeys at the time of
slaughter, and the consumption of undercooked or underprocessed
products could cause salmonellosis. Common symptoms may include
headache, abdominal discomfort, diarrhea and vomiting, Crawford
said.
   Hogs may have living trichane organisms in their muscle tissues
at the time of slaughter. And if the organisms aren't killed by
proper cooking or processing, the pork could cause trichinosis, an
``uncommon but potentially serious infection,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GunRecall     08-19 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Recall,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Department Recalls New Off-Duty Guns For Possible Defects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Police Department recalled 2,000 Smith &
Wesson .38-caliber revolvers, the newest gun used by off-duty
officers, to examine them for a possible firing defect, officials
said Friday.
   ``We found after repeated firings a problem could develop where
the hammer would freeze, rendering the gun inoperable,'' said Capt.
John C. Cerar, the head of the department's Firearms and Tactics
Section.
   The problem, which may affect 15 percent of the 60NY1-type
handguns, was discovered by department gunsmiths in late July, and
officers were ordered not to use the guns, Cerar said.
   ``In any police department it is standard procedure to issue a
notice of this type when any potential problem is encountered with
a firearm in order to avert the possibility of risk to an
officer,'' said Warren Tomek, director of quality assurance for the
Springfield, Mass., weapons manufacturer.
   Smith & Wesson said the flaw was due to an assembly problem and
estimated that less than 10 percent of the guns shipped to the
city's police departments were affected.
   Although the handgun is used as both a service and off-duty gun
in police departments throughout the country, ``the specific
problem is limited to the special design of the model 60's being
used in New York City,'' Tomek said.
   The gun used by the city's three police forces is specially
modified and is not sold on the market, Smith & Wesson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     08-19 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan's Ambassador Appeals for Help Against Locusts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's ambassador to Egypt appealed for
world help Friday to fight swarms of locusts that threaten 5
million acres of farmland in his country, adding to the dangers
facing Egypt's flood-ravaged southern neighbor.
   Ambassador El-Amin Abdel-Latif said his government now was
fighting rain, floods and locusts all at once.
   Torrential rains on Aug. 4-5 that caused flooding in northern,
eastern and central Sudan killed 91 people and left more than 1.5
million homeless. More rains expected in Ethiopia, at the Nile
River source, and the approaching annual Nile flood could worsen
the disaster.
   ``The biggest worry to the government now are the locusts,''
Abdel-Latif said in pre-recorded remarks broadcast Friday on
Cairo's state-run television. He said a locust invasion put 5
million acres of cultivated land in danger of destruction,
including 200,000 acres of cotton, one of Sudan's main crops.
   ``We hope our brothers in the Arab states and in the
international community will help to overcome this,'' he said.
   Sudan's agriculture minister, El-Fateh el-Teegany, said
Wednesday that the rains and floods made for good breeding grounds
for the locusts.
   In Rome, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization said Friday
it was sending thousands of tons of food to Sudan from emergency
sources of the World Food Program and asked other governments to
increase their help to Sudan.
   FAO Director General Edouard Saouma said in a statement that
following a drought and then floods, ``the Sudanese people are
faced with a life-threatening desert locust plague which could
destroy more vital food crops.''
   In Brussels, Belgium, the European Economic Community said
Friday it will provide $711,000 worth of blankets, water
purification tablets and other emergency aid to flood victims in
Sudan. It send a similar amount of assistance there earlier this
month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
