<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslems shouted slogans and threw stones
because officials banned their prayers Friday, fearing more riots
related to the death of President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq of Pakistan,
officials said.
   Police fired shots in the air to disperse the crowd, said
Srinagar Divisional Commissioner Shafi Pandit, the region's top
civil administrator in the region.
   Four people were killed Thursday in riots stemming from Zia's
death the previous day. Unofficial reports and rumors circulated
that his U.S.-built C-130 airplane, which either exploded or
crashed, may have been shot down by India.
   Pakistan claims this state on India's northern tip, known as
Jammu and Kashmir, and some people in the region support the claim.
Its majority is Moslem, like Pakistan, and most of India's 800
million people are Hindus.
   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since the subcontinent
was partitioned and became independent of Britain in 1947. Despite
its Moslem majority, Jammu and Kashmir became part of India at that
time.
   The Moslems at Friday's riot shouted anti-government slogans and
threw stones at passing vehicles after authorities banned Friday
prayers at the city's main mosque, Pandit said. He did not say how
many were in the group and said Moslems were allowed to worship at
other mosques.
   Curfews imposed on Srinagar and two other towns in Jammu and
Kashmir hours after Zia's death were lifted because of the Moslem
sabbath, Pandit said.
   Moslem demonstrators took to the streets hours after Zia's death
was announced and tried to burn Hindu houses, shops and temples,
authorities said.
   Soldiers were called out at Srinagar, the state's summer
capital, and the nearby towns of Anantnag and Baramulla.
   Four people were killed Thursday when police opened fire in
Srinagar to disperse curfew violators. At least 100 people were
injured in clashes in the city and in Baramulla and Anantnag,
police said.
   Police arrested 21 people on charges of rioting, Pandit said.
   On Friday, authorities escorted more than 2,000 foreign tourists
to Srinagar's airport, Pandit said. The travelers, mosat from the
United States, Britain and West Germany, were unable to reach the
airport earlier because of the curfew, he said.
   In London, the Foreign Office advised travelers to avoid
Srinagar.
