<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Policeman Kills Two Senior Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sikh policeman on Friday shot and
killed two senior officers who suspected he was involved in the
Sikh insurgency in Punjab state, and was shot dead himself minutes
later, authorities said.
   The policeman, Assistant Sub-Inspector Dalbir Singh, was killed
by another officer right after he fired, Deputy Inspector-General
B.S. Bhullar said.
   The shootout occurred at a police station in the town of
Patiala, 160 miles southwest of Amritsar.
   Elsewhere in Punjab, eight people were killed Thursday night in
attacks blamed on Sikh militants, news reports said.
   Bhullar said Sital Das, a senior superintendent of police, and
Baldev Singh Brar, a superintendent, were questioning Dalbir Singh
about his suspected ties with Sikh militants when he killed them
with his service revolver.
   Inspector Gurdip Singh, who was outside the room, opened the
door and shot Dalbir Singh, Bhullar said.
   Das and Brar were the two most senior police officers in Patiala
district.
   Radical Sikhs have been fighting for an independent homeland in
northern Punjab state since 1982. The community comprises only 2
percent of India's 800 million people but is in a majority in
Punjab, the country's wealthiest state.
   The insurgents claim that Sikhs are discriminated against by the
Hindus, who make up 80 percent of India's population.
   Many policemen in Punjab are Sikhs and some are known to be
sympathetic to the militants.
   The United News of India news agency said the Thursday night
victims included three Sikhs, one Hindu and four unidentified
people.
   The deaths raise to 1,729 the number of people reported killed
by Sikh militants in Punjab this year. Moderate Sikhs, accused by
militants of being traitors, make up more than half of the victims.
