<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burundi-Massacre     08-19 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burundi-Massacre,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Reported Slain In Ethnic Violence In Burundi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people were killed in the
central African country of Burundi this week in battles between
members of the rival Hutu and Tutsi tribes, government and
opposition officials said Friday.
   There were reports of systematic slaughter in two northern
villages and a lake filled with thousands of corpses. Several
thousand people were said to have fled the country to escape the
bloodbath.
   The government said the army had stopped the fighting between
the majority Hutu and the Tutsi, who control the military and
government.
   In April 1972 the Hutu tried to overthrow the government, but
the coup failed and the Tutsi retailiated by killing 100,000 Hutu.
   Official reports said most of the victims this week were Tutsi
but an exiled opposition group, the Hutu People Liberation Party,
accused the army of massacring Hutus.
   ``There are thousands of Hutus corpses, the victims of Tutsi
soldiers, floating in Lake Tanganyika,'' the opposition group said.
Neither claim could be confirmed independently.
   More than 7,000 Burudians were reported to have fled to
neighboring Rwanda. Sources in Rwanda, including diplomats, said
the refugees included members of both the Tutsi and Hutu tribes,
and both sides reported thousands of deaths.
   Fighting began Sunday near the northern villages of Marangara
and Ntega, the government radio reported Friday.
   ``Some inhabitants of northern Burundi belonging to the minority
Tutsi tribe were killed in a selective manner,'' it Foreign
Minister Cyprien Mbonimpa as saying.
   Although the violence was confined to a section of the north,
the government imposed a nationwide overnight curfew and prohibited
meetings of more than five people without government permission.
   The emergency order was signed by Maj. Pierre Buyoya, a Tutsi
who took power in a bloodless coup last September.
   ``We suspect that some former Hutu refugees infiltrated the
country from some foreign countries. They incited the Hutu and
called on them to massacre the Tutsi population,'' Astere
Nzisabira, Burundi's ambassador to Belguim, said in a radio
interview Thursday in Brussels.
   Authorities intervened ``in a peaceful manner'' after the first
day of violence, ``but the following day the murders resumed in
full swing,'' he said. ``At that stage, the army had to intervene
and restore peace to the country.'' He had no specific death toll,
but said the numbers were much higher than the initial estimates of
300-400 dead.
   Also Friday, Radio Kigali, the Rwandan government radio, said
its government was trying to provide food and shelter for the
influx of Burundians.
   Burundi, with nearly 5 million people in an area about the size
of Maryland, is one of Africa's most densely populated countries.
About 85 percent of its people belong to the Hutu tribe and the
rest are Tutsis.
   Ethnic struggles have plagued Burundi since independence from
Belguim in 1962. For generations, the tall, lanky Tutsi held the
short, stocky Hutu in feudal serfdom.
   In 1976, Col. Jean-Baptiste Bagaza mounted a bloodless coup that
ousted Michel Micombero, who had sanctioned the Hutu slaughter four
years earlier. Bagaza, like Micombero, was a Tutsi.
   Bagaza was overthrown Sept. 4, by Buyoya, who pledged to resolve
ethnic differences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
