<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-PLO,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Leader Talks Of Forming Palestinian Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior PLO leader said Friday that Egypt
had agreed to help persuade the United States not to veto plans for
a Palestinian provisional government in the U.N. security council.
   Egypt provided no confirmation of any such agreement.
   The official, Hani el-Hassan, also said in recorded remarks on
Egypt's state-run television that it would take years for the
Palestinian plans to materialize.
   Hassan, a political adviser to Palestine Liberation Organization
chairman Yasser Arafat, declared, ``When we (the PLO) announce a
state and a government, it doesn't mean we will see a result in one
or two weeks.
   ``We are talking about a stage that will bear fruit in the early
1990s, in three or four years.''
   Hassan was part of a three-man PLO delegation that left Egypt on
Thursday after four days of talks with President Hosni Mubarak and
other officials.
   He said on the weekly pre-recorded program ``Brotherly
Meetings'' that the PLO expects the United States to use its veto
power at the Security Council to block acceptance of a Palestinian
provisional government.
   Hassan said he discussed this with Mubarak and that the
president said he was ready to ``pressure the United States'' into
accepting the proposal.
   While Egypt did not confirm this, Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said at the end of the meetings that Egypt would put
all its resources behind the PLO.
   PLO delegation member Mahmoud Abbas said Mubarak agreed the PLO
should establish a provisional government with an internationally
acceptable political agenda.
   Washington refuses to negotiate with the PLO unless it
recognizes Israel and renounces terrorism. A U.S. veto could end a
PLO effort to win U.N. recognition of any government it might form.
   Hassan said he also believed that Saudi Arabia and Iraq stood
ready to pressure Washington to forgo a veto.
   The PLO is debating proposals designed to fill the vacuum left
by Jordan, which announced this month it was disengaging from the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and inviting the PLO to assume control
there.
   Jordan had maintained administrative and political links with
the neighboring territory it controlled before Israel seized the
area in the 1967 Middle East war.
   PLO proposals include declaring a state in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, a region bordering Egypt which the Israelis also
occupy. About 1.5 million Palestinians live in the occupied
territories, where a Palestinian uprising has been going on since
December.
   PLO officials have also talked about setting up a
government-in-exile or a provisional government headed by PLO
leaders. They gave few details on how these proposals would differ.
   Hassan made clear in the TV interview that the choice most
favored was a provisional government. However, he said all
proposals would be submitted for approval to the Palestine Natonal
Council, the PLO's legislative arm that functions as a
parliament-in-exile. The body is to meet in Algeria next month.
   The PLO leader also repeated earlier PLO statements that a
provisional government would recognize Israel in exchange for
Israel's recognition of a Palestinian state in the occupied
territories.
</TEXT>
