<DOCNO> AP880819-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Women-Priests     08-19 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Priests,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>70 Percent of Britons Polled Favor Woman Priests, Bishops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gallup poll published Friday reports that 70
percent of Britons surveyed think the Church of England should
accept women as priests and even consecrate them as bishops.
   An even higher percentage of Church of England members in the
poll, 75 percent, supported the idea, it said.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of the
Church of England, has warned that the issue could split not just
Britain's state church, but Anglican churches worldwide.
   The poll, published Friday in London's Daily Telegraph
newspaper, was based on interviews with 1,021 Britons this month.
   The Church of England has an all-male priesthood. In the last 11
years, a minority of the 26 self-governing Anglican churches in
other countries, including the 2.5-million member U.S. Episcopal
Church, have ordained more than 1,000 women as priests. The U.S.
church and those in Canada and New Zealand are considering
consecrating the first women bishops this year.
   Results of the Gallup survey contrasted with a close vote on the
women's role issue at the church's General Synod on July 5.
   The synod voted 299-216 to draft legislation allowing ordination
of women. The breakdown of votes was bishops 28-21, clergy 137-102,
and laity 134-93 with one abstention.
   The draft legislation must be debated and voted upon by all 44
of the state church's dioceses. It will then go back to the synod
for final approval and must then be passed by Parliament to become
law. The first woman could be ordained in 1992 or 1993.
   Asked if they thought the Church of England should accept women
as priests and bishops, 70 percent of the Britons polled agreed
that it should, 18 percent disagreed and 12 percent were undecided.
   The group included Anglicans, people of other faiths and
non-church goers. The response to the same question among only
Anglicans in the 1,021 people surveyed was 75 percent agreeing, 16
percent disagreeing and nine percent undecided.
   The paper did not indicate how many of the 1,021 were Anglicans
and gave no margin of error.
   On Aug. 1, the world's Anglican bishops, who represent 70
million faithful in 164 countries, voted 423-28 for a carefully
worded compromise on the issue. It was designed to keep their
churches together despite the deep divisions.
   Their compromise called for the churches to respect each other's
decisions, but it did not take a definitive stand on the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0204 </DOCNO>
