<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bandits-Aftermath 1stLd-Writethru a0756 08-19 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bandits-Aftermath, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Had Offered Use of Crack Anti-Terrorist Force</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th pvs `Asked about...' with report one
bandit admits killing boy. PICK up 9th graf `Federal Education ...'
Minor editing throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government offered its
elite anti-terrorist force to stop a 54-hour cross-country hostage
ordeal in which three people were killed, a spokesman said Friday,
but state officials chose another plan.
   The revelation came as criticism heightened of state officials'
handling of the terror spree by two bank robbers and a woman
accomplice.
   The incident ended Thursday in a gunfight with police on a
superhighway near Bonn that killed a hostage.
   Killed earlier were a 15-year-old Italian boy hostage, shot by
the criminals at a highway rest area, and a police officer who
perished in a car crash while pursuing the bandits.
   Michael Butz, spokesman for the federal Interior Ministry, told
reporters the GSG-9 anti-terrorist force was offered to North
Rhine-Westphalia state officials.
   Instead, the state officials assigned a police commando unit to
stop the robbers. The commandos rammed the getaway car and in an
ensuing gun battle, one of the hostages inside the car, 18-year-old
Silke Bischof, was killed.
   State officials said Friday they were sure she was killed by one
of the two bank robbers _ identified as Dieter Degowski and
Hans-Juergen Roesner _ and not by police gunfire.
   Asked about the state's decision not to use the GSG-9, Butz
replied only: ``The legal situation in which the states have
responsibility for police deployments must be respected.''
   At a preliminatry court hearing Friday night, Degowski admitted
that he fatally shot the Italian boy, according to the Cologne
radio station Rundfunk. It quoted a court official, who was not
identified, and gave no further details.
   Federal Education Minister Juergen Moellemann was among the
politicians who criticized North Rhine-Westphalia officials for not
making use of the GSG-9.
   The initials stand for Grenzschutzgruppe-Unit 9, or Federal
Border Guard Troops-Unit 9, which gained fame by rescuing 86
passengers held by terrorists on a Lufthansa airliner on Oct. 13,
1977 at Mogadishu, Somalia.
   Moellemann said the North Rhine-Westphalia state's interior
minister, Herbert Schnoor, and the interior minister for the
city-state of Bremen, Bernd Meyer, should resign.
   ``It is totally unconceivable why actions were not taken
sooner,'' Moellemann told the Bild newspaper. ``There were plenty
of opportunities to do so.''
   The ordeal began Tuesday morning, when two men robbed a bank in
the northwestern town of Gladbeck, escalated on Wednesday with the
seizure of a Bremen bus with 30 people on board, and ended Thursday
with the shootout.
   Most of the ordeal occurred in the city-state of Bremen and
North Rhine-Westphalia, but the gunmen also drove the bus across
the border into the Netherlands, then returned to West Germany.
   Schnoor said he took ``political responsibility'' for the
handling of the situation by North Rhine-Westphalia law officials
and he rejected allegations they bungled the job.
   He said on West German radio: ``It is impossible to foresee what
will be the end result before all the cards have been put on the
table.''
   Meyer spokesman Volker Backhaus also defended Bremen officials'
handling of the situation.
   ``There were times when Roesner and his female friend were
outside the bus giving interviews to reporters, but the other
gunman was inside the bus threatening the hostages,'' he said.
   Reinhard Schmidt-Kuentzel, a spokesman for the North
Rhine-Westphalia Interior Ministry, said that in the final
shootout, Miss Bischof was shot in the heart; a second woman
hostage was grazed by a bullet on the back; Roesner was shot in the
thigh, and Degowski and a female accomplice, Marion Irma Loeblich,
were unhurt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
