<DOCNO> AP880819-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle Bjt 2ndLd-Writethru 08-19 0963</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, Bjt, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0735,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Answers Questions About National Guard Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to add color and details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle insisted Friday that he
broke no rules to get into the Indiana National Guard during the
Vietnam War, but acknowledged that a family friend probably made
calls on his behalf after Quayle expressed interest.
   ``I got in fairly,'' the Republican vice presidential nominee
insisted at an outdoor news conference after a rousing rally in his
home town.
   A crowd of thousands that heard the questions over a public
address system jeered reporters and chanted ``Quayle! Quayle!'' in
support of the senator's responses.
   The 41-year-old Quayle had refused throughout the week to answer
media questions about whether strings were pulled to get him into
the Guard and avoid the draft during the Vietnam War.
   Friday's news conference was his first accounting of the chain
of events leading to his enrollment in the Guard. He portrayed it
as a normal occurance given his relationship with his family and
their friends.
   ``I did not ask anyone to break the rules, and so far as I know
no one did,'' Quayle said
   The Indianapolis News had reported Thursday that Wendell C.
Phillippi, former managing editor of the newspaper, which is part
of Quayle's grandfather's publishing chain, had called the Guard on
Quayle's behalf. Phillippi was a former commander of the state
National Guard and a family friend.
   ``Wendell Phillippi knew that I wanted to get into the National
Guard and I hope that he helped me and I think he did,'' Quayle
told reporters. ``I would hope that he helped me and I expect
that.''
   Quayle said he initially called his parents to discuss his
desire to enter the National Guard as a senior in college. He faced
the loss of his colleage student deferment upon graduation.
   Asked why he did not just go down and fill out papers if his
entry into the Guard was as routine as he suggested it was, Quayle
said:
   ``I do what any normal person would do at that age. You call
home. You call home to mother and father and say `I'd like to get
in the National Guard.'''
   He said his conversation with Phillippi was brief and that he
did not ask Phillipi to make any calls on his behalf. ``I told him
I wanted to get into the National Guard. I would assume calls would
be made. I talked to Mr. Phillippi very briefly. I hope that he
helped me and I think he did.''
   Quayle said he saw nothing wrong with that and added that he
resented questions implying that joining the Guard was less of a
military service to his country.
   ``The implication is somehow that Dan Quale, by voluntarily
signing up for the Indiana National Guard was somehow not patriotic
and I resent that,'' he said.
   Asked to assess the way he proceeded as a 22-year-old, he said,
``I would not have done anything differently'' if he had known he
would be running for vice president one day.
   Questions about the circumstances surrounding Quayle's
enlistment in the National Guard in 1969 continued to overshadow
George Bush's presidential campaign and dog Quayle just a day after
he was nominated for the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   Quayle said he did not offer to have Bush withdraw his name for
the vice presidential spot on the ticket, saying he did not think
there was any reason for that.
   Bush and Quayle had just concluded their first joint campaign
rally on the front steps of the courthouse when the vice president
walked away and Quayle approached reporters standing behind a rope
line.
   Quayle took a combative, hard line, with reporters, during an
extraordinary 20-minute impromptu news conference on the courthouse
lawn.
   The give-and-take was broadcast to people at the rally site with
an amplifier system, and Quayle supporters cheered his answers and
booed reporters seeking to question his military past. At one
point, the crowd started chanting ``Boring! Boring!''
   Quayle said he planned to make his military records available,
but didn't say when. He also said he did not believe he deceived
Bush campaign organization officials when questioned about this
during the screening process that preceded his selection for the
ticket.
   A high-ranking campaign official insisted to reporters that the
unusual news conference was ``not a set-up.'' He said the session
was amplified to the crowd because there were several reporters on
a separate platform who otherwise could not hear Quayle.
   Quayle, who said he had reservations about the Vietnam war, as
many people in his generation did, said he ``could have been called
to Vietnam as many Indiana units were, and if I had been called, I
would have gone.''
   ``No, I did not join to avoid service in Vietnam,'' he said.
Quayle said it was perfectly normal for a young man of 22 to talk
to talk about joining the Guard, or making any other decision.
   Asked if the uproar over his military background would harm the
prospects for the Bush ticket, Quayle said he thought it would do
the opposite, saying millions of people who have served in the
National Guard are offended by suggestions that he joined to avoid
duty in Vietnam.
   Quayle said he did not know whether there were any vacancies in
the Guard at the time he sought to join.
   During a joint appearance with Bush earlier Friday in New
Orleans, before members of the Republican National Committee,
Quayle said he had learned something about how to conduct himself
in that convention city. Then, he snapped his heels together, and
came to attention, and did a military precision-style delivery of
name, rank and serial number.
</TEXT>
