<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TurnpikeExplosives     08-19 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turnpike Explosives,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Challenges Government's Revised Indictment In Turnpike
Bombs Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese man arrested on explosives
charges and linked by investigators to a left-wing terrorist group
pleaded innocent Friday to a revised indictment.
   Yu Kikumura, 36, was arrested April 12 at a rest stop on the New
Jersey Turnpike after a state police trooper found three homemade
bombs in his car.
   After his arrest, U.S. authorities linked Kikumura to the
terrorist Japanese Red Army.
   Kikumura is accused of transporting explosives interstate
without a permit, transporting explosives interstate by an illegal
alien, possession of an unregistered firearm, using a false
passport and other charges. He could face 100 years in prison if
convicted on all counts.
   Defense attorney Ronald Kuby filed two motions with U.S.
District Judge Alfred J. Lechner asking that the charges be
dismissed.
   Kuby argued that prosecutors obtained the new indictment ``to
avoid the certain dismissal of at least four charges'' in the
original indictment.
   ``To all appearances, the government's action certainly seemed
designed to punish a pesky defendant for exercising his legal
rights,'' he contended.
   Lechner set a Sept. 9 date for arguing the motions. He also set
a trial date of Sept. 27.
   Kikumura was led into the courtroom under heavy security,
handcuffed and in leg irons, prompting a protest from defense
attorney Ronald Kuby. Lechner agreed to allow the leg irons to be
taken off, but Kikumura remained handcuffed throughout the
25-minute hearing.
</TEXT>
