<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DockWorkers     08-19 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dock Workers,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dock Workers Take Off Work Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,200 dockworkers stayed off the job
Friday in protest of Pacific Maritime's decision to hire non-union
workers for clerical positions at California ports.
   The workers planned to return Saturday.
   The dispute concerns 30 of 60 marine clerk positions that are
being made available to ``young college kids'' instead of
longshoremen with 20 years of experience, said Tom Lupher,
president of Local 10 of the International Longshoremen's and
Warehousemen's Union.
   ``What really gripes us is that some of them are children of the
employers,'' Lupher said. The decision to hire non-union marine
clerks was made without consulting the union.
   Local 10 represents 1,400 dockworkers.
   The Pacific Maritime Association, a collective bargaining group
for commercial shipping companies, said it was working to end the
dispute.
   ``Local 10 is engaged in an illegal work stoppage in violation
of the `no-strike' clause of the collective bargaining agreement
between the (union) and the Pacific Maritime Association,'' the
group said in a prepared statement. ``On behalf of its 120 member
companies, the PMA is pursuing available remedies to end the work
stoppage.''
   Although a specific time has not been set, the union is planning
a referendum on the matter.
   The clerical workers earn $20,000 to $25,000 a year more than
regular longshoremen, with many earning as much as $60,000 to
$70,000 a year, Lupher said.
</TEXT>
