<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-19 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Front Brings Storms; North Carolina Sizzles But Other Places Get
Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stationary front brought storms to parts of the Midwest and
East on Friday, and much of the northeast quarter of the nation got
a respite from high heat, but temperature records continued to fall
in North Carolina.
   The front, which extended from the mid-Mississippi Valley to the
mid-Atlantic Coast states, had temperatures to the north of it in
the 70s and temperatures to the south largely in the 90s.
   Some of the thunderstorms that developed along the front
produced heavy rainfall. Blinding rain was reported falling at
Prairie City, Ind., the National Weather Service said.
   Strong thunderstorms brought high winds, brief heavy rains and
small hail to the Virginias on Friday morning. Thunderstorm winds
blew down trees and power lines in a wooded area near Foster, Va.,
and trees were toppled by damaging winds in Tucker County, W.Va.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were reported in the lower
Mississippi Valley, the southern Plains, the Gulf Coast and
Florida. Thunderstorm winds gusted to 75 mph in parts of Pittsburg
County in southeastern Oklahoma.
   North of the stationary front, temperatures were in the 70s in
the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes, and the northern
Atlantic Coast states.
   Records were broken Friday in Charlotte, N.C., where the
temperature reached 100 degrees, breaking a record of 98 degrees,
and at Raleigh, where the 103 reading broke the record of 96. Both
old records were set in 1983.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.20 inches at Evansville, Ind.; 0.47 inch at Bowling
Green, Ky., and West Plains, Mo.; and 0.45 inch at Jacksonville,
Ark.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 102 degrees at Needles, Calif.,
Fayetteville, N.C., Goldsboro, N.C., and Raleigh, N.C. The
early-morning low for the nation was 35 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Saturday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms in the lower Mississippi Valley, the eastern and
central Gulf Coast, the Tennessee Valley, the southern Ohio Valley,
and the middle and southern Atlantic Coast states, Arizona, and the
front range of the Rockies in Colorado and New Mexico.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were forecast for parts of the Pacific
Northwest and the California coast as well as across the Great
Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley, Pennsylvania and New England; between
100 and 110 in the desert Southwest and valleys of California; and
in the 80s and 90s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
