<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat Deaths,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaths Are Believed To Be Heat Related</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people whose bodies were found in their
sweltering homes or in a car were believed to have died from the
heat, the Marion County coroner's office said Friday.
   The five, whose ages ranged from 52 to 82, were all found
Thursday, but authorities believe some of them died earlier in the
week.
   The temperature in Indianapolis reached 102 on Tuesday and
continued well into the 90s through Thursday, but the heat wave
eased Friday.
   The latest victim, Harriet Thornburg, 78, was found dead in her
apartment Thursday evening after an apartment manager called
authorities.
   Also Thursday, the bodies of Pauline H. Felton, 82, and her
niece, Georgia Jones, 69, were found in the two-story house they
shared. All doors and windows in the house were closed. An electric
fan was plugged in but was not operating.
   ``It is extremely hot in there,'' said Gary Gray, a Marion
County deputy coroner. He said the women probably had been dead
since Tuesday.
   Two other people whose bodies were discovered Thursday had
unusually high body temperatures, but autopsies had not been
completed, said chief deputy coroner Charles Green.
   The body of Adam Stevens, 52, was found on the front seat of a
car. Authorities said the car did not belong to Stevens, who may
have been using it as a place to sleep.
   Merle Smith, 82, was found dead on the floor of her residence.
</TEXT>
