<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chavez 1stLd-Writethru a0718 08-19 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chavez, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cast of Stars, Politicians to Join Chavez Sunday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th, ``It's very ...' to UPDATE with
actors demonstrating in Malibu, picks up 9th graf pvs, `The
union....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians and celebrities will break
bread with farm labor leader Cesar Chavez on Sunday to celebrate
the end of his 36-day fast against pesticides on table grapes, a
union spokeswoman said Friday.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, actors Martin Sheen, Robert Blake,
Edward James Olmos and others will attend the outdoor Mass at the
United Farm Workers' compound in Delano, about 150 miles north of
Los Angeles, said Lorena Parlee.
   Also planning to attend is Massachusetts Rep. Joe Kennedy II.
His father, the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy broke bread with Chavez
at Delano in 1968 to conclude a 25-day fast.
   Meanwhile, doctors Friday stepped up monitoring of Chavez on the
34th day of his water-only fast. Dr. Fidel Huerta said Thursday
that he feared Chavez might not be able to sustain the fast until
Sunday.
   Another physician, Marion Moses, who attended Chavez during the
1968 fast, will remain with him until he breaks this fast which
began July 17, Ms. Parlee said.
   Chavez had lost 31 pounds, she added. During the first weeks of
the fast, Chavez attended Mass nightly but hasn't appeared in
public since Aug. 11.
   ``To us, what he is going through is extremely painful for all
of us,'' said the UFW's first vice president, Dolores Huerta, who
is the doctor's mother.
   ``It's very hard on everyone because we all love Cesar and
respect him very much,'' she said. ``It makes us more determined to
work harder and do more than in the past to end the problem with
pesticides.''
   In Malibu, Sheen and a dozen protesters chanting ``boycott
grapes'' demonstrated Friday in front of a supermarket in support
of Chavez's claims that table grapes contain dangerous pesticides.
   Sheen, actor Max Gail and others marched a half-mile from
Sheen's home to a market, bearing banners reading ``Boycott
Grapes'' and ``Stop Toxic Death,'' and urging people not to shop
there.
   ``There is something seriously wrong,'' Sheen said. ``The bottom
line is the Earth can live without us but we cannot live without
the Earth.''
   The union charges five pesticides _ Captan, Dinoseb, methyl
bromide, Parathion and Phosdrin _ should be banned because its
studies say the chemicals cause cancer.
   The state Department of Food and Agriculture, as well as several
growers groups, dispute the union's claims and cite existing laws
aimed at protecting farm workers and consumers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-QuaylePoll     08-19 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle Poll,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Poll: Guard Controversy Should Not Be Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans believe that Dan Quayle's service
in the National Guard should not be a campaign issue, but voters
are split on whether it should be an issue if it turns out he used
family influence to get into the Guard, a poll released Friday said.
   The ABC News poll found in a random sample of 613 registered
voters Thursday night that 63 percent said the fact that the GOP
vice presidential candidate entered the National Guard at a time
when others faced possible service in Vietnam should not be a
campaign issue.
   About 23 percent said they thought it should be a minor issue
and 11 percent thought it should be a major issue, according to the
poll, which had an margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
   But if influence was used, 23 percent said Quayle's National
Guard service should be a major issue and 27 percent said it should
be a minor issue, while 47 percent said it should not be a campaign
issue.
   Seventy-four percent said Quayle's decision to join the National
Guard will have no effect on how they vote; 17 percent said they
are now less likely to vote Republican and 4 percent are more
likely to vote for the GOP ticket.
   But if Quayle got into the National Guard because of outside
influence, the number of those who would be less likely to vote for
George Bush and Quayle jumps to 31 percent, the poll found.
   Nearly three-quarters of those who say they are less likely to
vote for Bush if influence was used were probably going to vote for
the Democratic ticket anyway, the poll said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-KidneySale     08-19 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Kidney Sale,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Identifies Mystery Student Who Advertised Kidney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student who anonymously offered to sell
one of his kidneys to pay for his education was identified Friday
as an impoverished 22-year-old who was expelled from school because
of a $139 debt.
   The Daily Nation identified the student as Felix Abwora, whose
heart-rending plea received worldwide attention after his letter
was published in the Aug. 13 edition of the newspaper.
   ``I am a needy student from a poor family facing expulsion from
school for lack of school fees,'' the student wrote. ``My parents
are unable to meet the basic needs of our family as well as the
ever-increasing cost of my education since they are landless and
jobless.
   ``Since my efforts to get financial assistance for studies have
been unsuccessful, I now offer to sell one of my kidneys at a cheap
price, to whoever has kidney problems and may want to have a kidney
transplant.''
   Abwora signed the letter ``F.A. Fuko,'' a pseudonym made up of
his initials and the word for kidney in his Luhya tribal language.
The letter, dated July 28, gave no other details.
   The story was carried by international news agencies and
prompted worldwide offers of help for ``Fuko,'' who said he lived
in the small western Kenya town of Hakati.
   The Daily Nation said it was able to trace Abwora and to confirm
his story.
   ``The case of Abwora is very much genuine and his request is
highly recommended,'' area chief Bernard Ojiambo told the Daily
Nation. The chief said he had tried to organize a fund-raiser for
Abwora's education, but had no success.
   Until April, Abwora was a high school student at Makunde
Secondary School. But he said he was expelled when he fell behind
in his school fees by 2,500 Kenya shillings, or $139.
   Kenyan students frequently are in their 20s by the time they
finish high school because they often must skip several years for
lack of money.
   Abwora is one of seven children and one of his brothers, Nagila,
19, also has dropped out of school because he could not pay a $12
building fee, the Daily Nation said.
   The family lives on a four-acre homestead, but the newspaper
didn't say whether it was the family's property.
</TEXT>
