<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JudgeSuicide 1stLd-Writethru a0742 08-19 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Suicide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0961</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King County Judge Shoots Himself in Courthouse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new 3rd graf to UPDATE with suicide note details;
Subs 6th graf pvs, `Little shot...' to UPDATE that Little's father
killed himself years ago; SUBS 12th-14th grafs pvs, `The
Post-Intelligencer ...' with 6 grafs to add comment from newspaper,
suicide note material; picks up 15th graf pvs, `The judge ....'
^LaserPhoto SE2</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who killed himself in a deserted
courthouse hallway after he learned details were being published
about his alleged sexual misconduct felt hounded by the press and
unable to bear it anymore, a friend said.
   King County Superior Court Judge Gary M. Little was found dead
Thursday night of a self-inflicted gunshot wound to the head,
officials said.
   He left a note saying: ``I have chosen to take my life. It's an
appropriate end to the present situation.''
   In the past six years, Little has been officially criticized or
disciplined over improper contacts with juvenile defendants.
   But rumors persisted of more serious sexual misconduct, leading
a political challenger to raise those contacts as a campaign issue
this year and reporters from several news organizations to pursue
reports Little had used his influence to coerce young men into sex.
   Little, 49, a judge since 1980, announced last month that he
would not seek a third term, acknowledging that innuendo about his
work with teen-age boys was the reason. He said he planned to move
to California and work outside law.
   Little, whose father committed suicide when he was 8, shot
himself about an hour before the presses at the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer started printing Friday's editions, which
contained more than three full pages outlining allegations by five
men _ three of them former students of Little's _ that he had
coerced them into having sex with him.
   The Seattle Times also reported Friday that it had been
investigating Little, and had interviewed more than 80 people.
   ``He said he felt he'd been hounded by the press and he just
couldn't take it anymore,'' said attorney Camden Hall, a friend of
Little who spoke to him by telephone just minutes before the judge
died. ``It was too much pressure. The hounding wouldn't stop.''
   ``He was not only driven into disgrace but to death,'' said Hal
Foster, an art history professor and author who was interviewed
from Paris by telephone by the Times.
   Foster took Little's law class at private Lakeside School in the
1970s and said there was no sexual contact involving him and that
he wasn't aware of any with his classmates.
   ``He was tried out of court on suspicions about his sexuality.
That, to me, is reactionary. It's scary,'' Foster said.
   Post-Intelligencer Executive Editor J.D. Alexander said in a
news release that Little's death ``is a tragedy that touches the
community at several levels. Certainly the most tragic is the loss
of a human life.''
   The newspaper's investigation was warranted, the statement said,
because of a ``conspiracy of silence'' in ``key levels of the
community'' about Little's behavior.
   ``There was no indication of relief; no indication that the
system that had failed these victims would or could serve the
public any better in the future,'' the statement said.
   A janitor found Little's body. A .38-caliber pistol and a note
were found with the body, said Vaughn Van Zant, an investigator
with the King County medical examiner.
   The one-page, handwritten note, addressed to no specific
individual, was found on a hallway bench, Van Zant said. The
medical examiner would not release its contents, but the Times
reported the note said:
   ``I have chosen to take my life. It's an appropriate end to the
present situation. I had hoped that my decision to withdraw from
the election and leave public life would have closed the matter.
Apparently these steps are not satisfactory to those who feel more
is required, so be it. I will say one final time that I am proud of
my efforts and accomplishments as a Superior Court Judge. I am
deeply appreciative of those who have wished me well these past few
weeks.''
   The judge was disciplined twice concerning improper contacts he
had with youths who appeared before him in court.
   In April 1985, after a complaint, Little was barred from the
juvenile court bench by the presiding judge and the Superior Court
executive committee because of such improper contacts, such as
buying young defendants clothing and books.
   In 1982, the state Commission on Judicial Conduct also privately
admonished Little. The commission had received a complaint as early
as 1981 from the King County prosecutor's office that Little was
violating the Code of Judicial Conduct by having out-of-court
contact with juvenile offenders, and the prosecutor's office
followed up with a second report in 1983, The Times reported.
   The commission's action was not made public until 1985; Little
had been re-elected in 1984.
   Two of the men who told the Post-Intelligencer that Little had
sex with them when they were teen-agers said they gave long
statements to the commission years later, one in 1981 and the other
in 1985.
   But the commission apparently never acted on those statements,
because it had adopted a policy not to pursue allegations of
misconduct that allegedly occurred before the commission was formed
in December 1980.
   The commission's chairman, Colfax attorney Wesley A. Nuxoll,
said he thinks the commission's confidential proceedings are
necessary to encourage people to come forward with complaints and
speak freely about them.
   He also said he would have reservations about modifying the rule
against considering pre-1980 cases, and thinks ``it would be a
serious mistake'' to make all complaints public.
</TEXT>
