<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OrganHarvest     08-19 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Organ Harvest,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Loma Linda Suspends Organ Harvesting Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loma Linda University Medical Center
has quietly suspended a program to harvest organs of infants born
with most of their brains missing after 13 failed attempts to make
the program work, officials said.
   The hospital will honor prior commitments to attempt organ
harvesting in two unborn anencephalic infants, but no other infants
will be accepted in the immediate future, officials said.
   The decision last month to stop the program was never announced.
But Dr. Joyce L. Peabody, Loma Linda's chief of neonatology,
disclosed the decision during a discussion at an Aug. 10 bioethics
seminar in Oakland.
   A tape recording of the discussion was obtained by the Los
Angeles Times, which published details Friday.
   ``Certainly, if the only outcome you are looking at is the
number of solid organs transplanted, our program has failed and
failed dismally,'' Ms. Peabody said on the tape.
   Officials at Loma Linda refused to comment Friday. A spokesman
said a news conference would be called Monday or Tuesday.
   The program's future will be determined after completion of a
report Ms. Peabody is preparing for medical center officials, the
Times reported.
   Anencephalics are born missing sections of the brain and skull.
Most die at birth or shortly thereafter.
   ``It takes a particular amount of courage to acknowledge that
you may have made a mistake,'' said Leslie Rothenberg, a faculty
member at the University of California-Los Angeles Medical Center
and a medical ethics specialist who had criticized the Loma Linda
program.
   The program began last December, two months after renowned Loma
Linda surgeon Dr. Leonard Bailey transplanted a heart from an
anencephalic child declared brain dead in Canada.
   Anencephalics are used as organ donors in Canada and Western
Europe but Loma Linda had the only such program in the United
States.
   The hospital's guidelines for using anencephalics required that
the babies meet medical criteria that would declare them brain dead
within seven days of their entry into the program.
   Of the first seven babies taking part in the hospital's program,
one was a stillborn and five failed to meet the criteria.
   No suitable recipient could be found for the organs of the one
baby that did meet the brain-death requirements and was thus
eligible as a donor.
   Five of the next six babies reached ``imminent death'' within a
week of birth, but four were determined to be unsuitable as donors.
</TEXT>
