<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FederalHiring     08-19 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federal Hiring,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says OPM Acted `Arbitrarily And Capriciously'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Friday that the
Reagan administration had not justified its failure to replace with
new examinations a civil service test that was found to
discriminate against minorities.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here said the Office of
Personnel Management acted ``arbitrarily and capriciously'' when
did not provide figures to document its claim it would be too
costly to devise new tests.
   But the three-judge panel said OPM should be given another
opportunity to justify the decision to the judge who ordered the
agency to devise new tests for college graduates seeking
entry-level federal jobs.
   The decision came in a case brought by the National Treasury
Employees Union that challenged OPM's decision to hire employees
for entry-level positions under a non-competitive provision of the
civil service law.
   That provision gives government agencies discretion to hire
employees non-competitively.
   The employees union objected to the procedure because the
employees hired under the provision did not receive all the
protections afforded other civil-service workers.
   The dispute arose after the goverment signed a consent decree in
1982 to phase out the Professional and Administrative Career
Examination to settle a lawsuit claiming the test discriminated
unfairly against minorities.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green ordered OPM to devise new
examinations to cover specific jobs and to implement the new tests
in six months. She stayed her order to give the government an
opportunity to appeal the decision.
   The appeals court, in an opinion by Circuit Judge Douglas H.
Ginsburg, sided with Green's finding that she had jurisdiction to
examine OPM's decision and with the conclusion it was ``arbitrarily
and capricious.''
   ``OPM did not have any evidence, so far as the record reveals,
of how much it would cost to develop the necessary examinations,''
Ginsburg wrote in an opinion joined by Circuit Judges Patricia Wald
and Harry Edwards.
   ``Unable to point us to any data of the sort it would have
considered if it had considered cost in any meaningful way, OPM
urges us to defer to its `expert judgment regarding the cost of
developing new examinations.'''
   ``There is no indication, in the record, however, that OPM ever
made an expert judgment about what those costs would be,'' Ginsburg
wrote.
   OPM spokesman Dick McGowan said the agency would not comment on
the decision.
   In June, OPM Administrator Constance Horner announced a new
program of using campus recruiters to hire college graduates based
on their academic records and interviews. Horner said the agency
would also devise competitive examinations for students who did not
have high enough grades to be hired through interviews.
   The treasury employees union has filed a new suit to challenge
the proposal, contending it will not result in competitive hiring.
   The union's president, Robert Tobias, said Friday's decision
means that OPM ``can no longer ignore their obligation to develop
an alternative system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Strike     08-19 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Strike,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electrical Workers Strike To Protest Union Leader's Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,500 workers at the state
power company stayed out on strike Friday to demand the release of
an arrested union leader, a union source said.
   The source said 40 workers at the Institute of Electrification
and Hydraulic Resources were arrested Tuesday when they cut service
to three pro-government newspapers and a television station, which
together owed about $500,000 in unpaid bills.
   The cutoff was not authorized by management, the source said. He
spoke on condition of not being identified, fearing reprisals.
   He said 39 of those arrested were freed Thursday night, but the
general secretary of the electrical worker's union, Isaac
Rodriguez, remained in jail.
   Union members, who spoke also on condition of anonymity, said
the 39 were freed after union leaders met with Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces and Panama's de
facto ruler.
   The members refused to give details of the meeting, but said the
workers and government agreed to set up a three-member committee to
direct the utility with representatives from the armed forces,
management and labor.
   They said Rodriguez was on a hunger strike at Modelo Prison in
Panama City and that relatives and friends were kept from visiting
him.
   But a prison official told The Associated Press on Friday that
Rodriguez ``no longer is here.'' He did not say where Rodriguez was.
   The union source said that virtually all of the Institute's
5,500 workers walked off the job Tuesday after the arrests and
vowed not to return until Rodriguez is freed.
   The walkout delayed maintenance and repair work, but the
nation's power supply was not affected.
   The source said Rodriguez and the others cut electricity to
Editorial Renovacion, which publishes the newspapers Critica,
Matutino and La Republica, to protest administrative and financial
difficulties at the institute they say were caused in part by the
firm's failure to pay.
   Matutino did not publish Wednesday but resumed publication on
Thursday. Operations at the other newspapers were unaffected.
   The workers also tried to cut service to Channel 2 national
television, but it was not affected.
   The union members complained that the institute usually cuts off
service when the poor do not pay their bills, but extends credit to
big companies that are influential with the government.
</TEXT>
