<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Hostages     08-19 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Hostages,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Middleman Says U.S. Made `Horrendous Blunder'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli middleman in the Iran-Contra
arms-selling scandal said in an article Friday that the United
States made a ``horrendous blunder'' in trying to buy the release
of American hostages held in Lebanon.
   Yaacov Nimrodi, in 1985, helped arrange shipments of U.S.
weapons to Iran. Some of the profits went to Nicaraguan rebels,
known as Contras, fighting the Sandinista government.
   The scheme was carried out despite a U.S. ban on arms sales to
Iran, at war with Iraq, and the lack of congressional approval for
military aid to the Contras.
   Israel helped deliver the arms to Iran and said it was acting at
the request of the United States, which hoped to obtain the release
of Americans kidnapped in Lebanon by pro-Iranian extremists.
   The article by Nimrodi was published in the Jerusalem Post.
   He said that in 1985 he and Israeli collegues Al Schwimmer and
David Kimchi ``found the key to Iran, made the right connections
with the right people and put them at the disposal of the U.S.''
   ``Unfortunately a horrendous blunder was made,'' Nimrodi wrote
in a rare public statement on the arms deal. ``Instead of homing in
on the political dimension ... the contacts, in a most natural way,
were permitted to spill over to talks on the release of hostages in
exchange for U.S. arms.''
   Nimrodi said he believes President Reagan hopes to secure the
release of the American hostages before his term ends in January,
but added that focusing on the issue of the captives ``is apt to
raise the price the Iranians will demand and make the release of
the hostages more difficult.''
   ``It is to be hoped that today the American (and Israeli)
foreign policymakers have learned from past mistakes and will
navigate their contacts with Iran so as to restore Iran to its
natural place _ the place where it wants to be and ought to be _
much closer to the West,'' Nimrodi wrote.
   ``The West will then achieve, three years later, what we sought
to achieve then.''
   Eighteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are held captive
in Lebanon by Moslem militants. Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, has been held the longest.
He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Nimrodi, 61, lived in Iran for 25 years, first as an agent for
Israel's Mossad intelligence agency and then as a military attache
and a private businessman.
   Nimrodi wrote that for the first time since the Iran-Contra
scandal the United States and Iran appear on the verge of improving
their relations.
   He also said Iran's ``daring decision'' to agree to a cease-fire
with Iraq in their eight-year-old war ``indicates, more than
anything else, that beyond what appears to be the irrational,
uncompromising and fanatical policy of the Iranian rulers, a
significant amount of logic and pragmatism can be discovered.''
</TEXT>
