<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia Cartels ,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Cousin of Drug Dealer for Killings of Rivals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Luis Gaviria Rivero, cousin of
the head man of the Medellin drug cartel, has been arrested in the
investigation of the killings of five members of a rival gang, the
army announced Friday.
   Gaviria Rivero is a cousin of Pablo Escobar Gaviria, chief of
the Medellin cartel that has been fighting with the Cali cartel
over shipments of drugs to the United States, mainly New York.
   A statement by the army's 4th Brigade said Gaviria Rivero was
arrested Aug. 4 in a farm on the outskirts of Medelln after an
intensive search by agents of the military intelligence service.
   It said Gaviria Rivero is accused of participating in the July
11 slayings of five former military officers who were working as
gunmen for the Cali cartel with the assignment to kill leaders of
the Medellin ring.
   It is believed the two cartels, based in Medellin 150 miles
northwest of Bogota and Cali 200 miles southwest of the capital,
control 80 percent of the cocaine shipments to the United States.
   According to military reports, 78 people have been killed since
January in the fight to dominate the multibillion-dollar cocaine
market in New York.
   The feud began with the attempted bombing of Escobar Gaviria's
luxurious home.
   Military intelligence officials say 60 members of the Cali
cartel and 18 members of the Medellin mob have been killed since
January.
   Gen. Ruiz Barrera has told reporters the Medellin gangsters have
more experience in organizing assassination squads and hiring paid
killers for dangerous missions.
   Medellin killers have been blamed for the deaths of scores of
people involved in the campaign against drugs including a justice
minister, the federal attorney general, Supreme Court justices and
other judges.
   This week, a bomb destroyed a pharmacy in downtown Medelln owned
by Gilberto Rodrguez Orejuela who is believed to be a leader of the
Cali cartel. He is sought by the United States for drug trafficking.
   The Cali cartel once controlled New York's cocaine market, but
it has lost ground to the Medellin organization, according to
anti-drug officials here.
</TEXT>
