<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Investment     08-19 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Investment,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haiti To Revise Tax Laws To Stimulate Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haiti's military rulers have
announced they will revise tax laws in a move to stimulate national
and international investment in Haiti.
   ``Business recovery depends on the maintenance of social peace
of which the military government is the guarantor, and especially
on a restructuring of our institutions and a revision of our
laws,'' Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy said in a speech to businessmen
published Thursday by the state-run newspaper, L'Union.
   ``The code of investments is being updated ... Other codes which
are incentives for investment are under study. They concern
tourism, agriculture and commerce,'' he said.
   Joel Thebaud, executive director of Prominex, an investment
promotion firm, said the measure is ``very encouraging. It shows
(the government) has opened up to the private sector.
   ``The revision will mainly concern tax exemptions, to improve
conditions for both national and international investment,''
Thebaud told The Associated Press on Friday. ``This step will give
new life to the business world.''
   Namphy returned to power after four months of civilian rule
following an army coup on June 19 that sent President Leslie
Manigat into exile. Namphy had previously led a junta during the 24
months after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to France in
February 1986.
   Commerce Minister Col. Erick Brunel Lamour criticized the
international condemnation of Haiti's army rulers that followed the
June 19 coup.
   ``We are condemned by an increasingly hostile external
environment to promote ... the improvement of living conditions for
our courageous and good people which has been punished for not
revolting against our government,'' Lamour was quoted as saying in
an interview with L'Union.
   The United States suspended $60 million of its $90 million aid
package to Haiti after gunmen protected by soldiers killed at least
34 voters during the aborted Nov. 29 elections.
</TEXT>
