<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-TrainCrash     08-19 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Train Crash,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll In Train Crash Climbs To 25; Court Action Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet prosecutors have begun legal action against
railway officials accused of negligence in the crash of a
high-speed passenger train in which 25 people died, the Tass news
agency said Friday.
   Tass said damage was estimated at about $700,000 in Tuesday's
crash of the Aurora train carrying 760 passengers from Leningrad to
Moscow.
   Vladimir Ginko, first deputy railway minister, told Tass that
railway foreman T. Gavrilov incorrectly raised a speed limit that
had been imposed on the track near the town of Bologoye, 180 miles
northwest of Moscow.
   He said T. Khrustalev, head of the local railroad
administration, had not acted in time to countermand Gavrilov.
   ``Criminal proceedings have been instituted against the
culprits,'' Tass said.
   It did not say what charges were leveled against them.
   Tass said the death toll had reached 25, including 22 people
dead at the scene and three who died later in hospitals.
   It said 79 people remained hospitalized of the 107 initially
admitted.
   The Aurora, speeding south at 90 mph, went off the track, turned
over and caught fire Tuesday evening.
   Officials say a speed limit of 40 mph was ordered on the track
by an inspection crew that noticed a deviation in the rails, but
that the train's engineers were never told about the limit.
   They spotted the deviation but could not stop in time, Soviet
media reported.
</TEXT>
