<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-200Flavors     08-19 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-200 Flavors,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Mention of 200 Flavors of Ice Cream Scoops Up a Memory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Reagan mentioned 200 flavors of
ice cream on national television, it scooped up a 19-year-old
memory for Mark Hawley.
   Reagan, speaking Monday night to the Republican National
Convention in New Orleans, quoted from Hawley's essay on ``Why I
Love America.''
   ``I love America because you can join Cub Scouts if you want
to,'' Reagan read. ``You have a right to worship as you please. If
you have the ability, you can try to be anything you want to be. I
also like America because we have about 200 flavors of ice cream.''
   Reagan didn't mention Hawley's name, but said the words were
written by ``a young boy who wrote to me shortly after I took
office'' in 1981.
   Not quite right, says Hawley, now a 28-year-old mechanic for The
Boeing Co.
   ``I never wrote President Reagan,'' Hawley said in a telephone
interview Thursday. ``That (essay) was printed in Scouting Magazine
in the fall of 1969.
   ``It was part of a requirement for a Cub Scout badge, probably
citizenship or something.''
   Hawley, of the Seattle suburb of Burien, said he didn't watch
Reagan's speech, but heard a co-worker talking about the ``200
flavors of ice cream'' reference.
   He said he later received word from a Reagan aide that she had
been trying to track him down for two weeks.
  
</TEXT>
