<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialRemark     08-19 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Remark,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professor Suspended Without Pay For Racial Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMERICUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college professor who admitted he made a
racially and sexually offensive remark to a student was suspended
without pay Thursday for the fall quarter.
   Georgia Southwestern College professor Allen Towery, who
verbally attacked the student during a heated argument March 7, can
resume teaching when the winter quarter begins in January.
   ``At that time, I will allow Dr. Towery to return to teaching,
but only after he has submitted a correction plan which will
include measures to improve his performance in the specific areas
for which discipline is being administered,'' said school President
William H. Capitan.
   Capitan originally sought to have Towery fired.
   Towery, 49, a tenured associate professor of English, said he
was provoked into making the statement to Ginevra Dennis, 18. But
other students later complained about racist or sexist remarks he
allegedly made.
   Testimony at a disciplinary hearing in June showed Ms. Dennis
had gone to Towery's office to demand a ``withdrawn passing'' grade
in his class, rather than a failing grade.
   Capitan suspended Towery with pay shortly after the incident,
and later instituted dismissal proceedings.
   A five-member committee heard testimony in June, and cleared
Towery of violating a state Board of Regents policy. However, the
committee suggested that Towery be barred from teaching freshmen.
   Capitan considered the committee's recommendation, and decided
to suspend Towery.
   Towery said Thursday he would confer with his attorney, Gene
Black Jr. of Albany, before deciding whether to appeal.
   Towery declined further comment, but Black said he may seek a
federal court injunction blocking the suspension because it could
not be appealed to the regents before fall quarter classes begin
Sept. 15.
</TEXT>
