<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Duarte     08-19 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Duarte,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terminally Ill President Duarte Confined Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
suffering from terminal liver cancer, remained confined to his home
Thursday because of what a spokesman described as a low white
blood-cell count that would make him vulnerable to infection.
   Presidential spokesman Eduardo Colindres denied at a news
conference persistent rumors that the 62-year-old Duarte was in a
coma. A medical bulletin signed by the president's three doctors
described his condition ``as good and stable'' and said the low
white cell count was the result of chemotherapy.
   Colindres said medical bulletins will be issued daily.
   Duarte was flown to Walter Reed Medical Center in Washington in
June where surgeons removed more than half his stomach and
diagnosed terminal liver cancer. The doctors said then he had from
six to 18 months more to live.
   At Walter Reed, Duarte was given a first treatment of
chemotherapy for the cancer, and he returned again for a second
treatment during the first week in August. He flew back to San
Salvador Aug. 10.
   The medical report said the decline in the number of white blood
cells is ``a secondary effect that appears normally between the
10th and 15th day after the application of chemotherapy'' and that
Duarte was also being protected against infection with antibiotics.
   The president was confined to his home Wednesday.
   Foreign Minister Julio Londono of Colombia, visiting El
Salvador, called at Duarte's home Thursday to present him with the
Grand Collar of the National Order of San Carlos, Colombia's
highest civilian decoration.
