<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BombThreats     08-19 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb Threats,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Threats Delay Traffic At LaGuardia Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two telephoned bomb threats forced the
evacuation Thursday night of part of LaGuardia Airport's main
terminal, causing delays in some flights, the airport's operator
said.
   The threats prompted airlines to move planes away from the
terminal, and tied up vehicular traffic in and around the airport
as the police bomb squad arrived, said Lynn Tierney, a spokeswoman
for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   The first anonymous threat, at 7:07 p.m., said a bomb had been
planted in the TWA section of the main terminal, she said.
   The area was evacuated and the police bomb squad and Fire
Department responded. A package was found which proved to be ``a
hoax,'' Ms. Tierney said, adding she did not know what it contained.
   The area was reopened at 8:37 p.m., she said. During the
evacuation, TWA departures were held up and no arrivals were
scheduled.
   At 8:10 p.m., a second bomb threat was phoned in, this time
targeting the USAir section of the same terminal. By 8:24 p.m.,
that area was evacuated, Ms. Tierney said.
   USAir planes were backed away from the building during a search,
she said, and departures and arrivals were delayed.
   No package was found, the area was reopened and all operations
were back to normal by 9 p.m., the spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
