<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Rebels,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Kill Four in Highlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers thought to be Maoist rebels shot
and killed two irrigation engineers and two area officials after
forcing their car to a halt on an isolated mountain road, police
said Thursday.
   They said the killers, suspected of belonging to the
Mao-inspired Shining Path, checked the victims' papers to make sure
of their identities before shooting them Wednesday night.
   Officers said the four were killed on a rugged gravel highway
while bound from the farming district of Yanacancha to Huancayo,
the state capital 55 miles east.
   The engineers were employed by the Junin State Development Corp.
and were building an irrigation system for peasant farmers of
Yanacancha. Police said the other victims were the district's
justice of the peace and its public safety officer.
   The Shining Path has killed scores of local officials and
development workers in Peru's impoverished central highlands in an
effort to spark political and economic chaos.
   The government says more than 15,000 people have died in
violence surrounding the Shining Path's eight-year insurgency to
topple Peru's elected government and impose a worker-peasant state
modeled on Mao Tse-tung's Marxist China.
   Huancayo is in the 2-mile-high Andes Mountains, 125 miles east
of Lima.
