<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IncaBlaze     08-19 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inca Blaze,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Machu Picchu Reported Out of Danger From Raging Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke from a mountain wildfire burning near
ancient Inca ruins clouded the Andean capital of Cuzco on Thursday
as an estimated 550 fire fighters struggled to put out the blaze,
authorities said.
   Civil Defense spokeswoman Rebeca Anaya said the famous Machu
Picchu ruins, 40 miles northwest of Cuzco, were no longer in danger.
   No injuries or serious property damage were reported.
   The fire began near the ancient citadel Aug. 7 and has been
pushed by winds toward Cuzco, charring more than 7,500 acres of
forest and pasture and threatening other Inca ruins less renowned
than Machu Picchu, officials said.
   Cuzco, 330 miles southeast of Lima, faces no immediate risk but
smoke has intermittently swept through the city, according to
officials.
   Police said a peasant was arrested for starting the fire in an
attempt to clear land for crops.
   Officials said a daily tourist train between Cuzco and Machu
Picchu continued in operation but the Inca Trail, a path used by
tourists to trek to the mountaintop citadel in hikes taking several
days, has been temporarily closed.
</TEXT>
