<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Freeman     08-19 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Freeman,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hal M. Freeman Dies; Resigned Civil Rights Post Over AIDS Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hal M. Freeman, who resigned his post as
Western regional manager of federal Office of Civil Rights in
protest of White House policy on AIDS victims, has died of cardiac
arrest and complications of AIDS.
   Freeman, 52, died at Kaiser Hospital on July 30, his longtime
companion, Michael S. Macpherson, said Thursday.
   The duties of the civil rights office include preventing
discrimination against people who are handicapped. When he resigned
his post on Feb. 20, 1986, Freeman said he was quitting because the
Department of Health and Human Services had refused to apply the
Rehabilitation Act of 1973 to AIDS patients.
   ``The Reagan administration took the position at that time that
AIDS was not considered to be necessarily a handicapped position,''
Macpherson said.
   The publicity resulting from Freeman's resignation caused a
congressional inquiry and a change of policy.
   ``Persons with AIDS and ARC (AIDS-related complex) are now
protected by the Office of Civil Rights in accordance with federal
civil rights laws,'' Macpherson said.
   Freeman subsequently went into practice in San Francisco as a
psychotherapist.
   There was no funeral, Macpherson said.
</TEXT>
