<HEAD>Two Die As Suspected Drug Traffickers, Police Shoot It Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shootout Thursday between suspected
drug traffickers and Mexican authorities near this border city left
at least two people dead and five others wounded, including two
soldiers, according to reporters.
   Military and civilian police officials refused to release
details of the incident. But Fernando Romero of The Tribune of San
Diego was told by Tijuana police that the shootout occurred
Thursday morning at a ranch outside the city.
   The police officers, who refused to be identified, told Romero
that one of the alleged drug dealers was shot to death at the
ranch, called Los Olivos. The second man died at a hospital, police
said.
   According to an earlier report from Araceli Dominguez, a
reporter with the newspaper ABC, four people were killed and six
were wounded in the shootout, which he said involved army troops
and federal judicial police.
   Two wounded soldiers were listed in stable condition after being
moved from the Mexican Institute of Social Security Hospital in
Tijuana to the Naval Hospital in Ensenada, said Dr. Ariel Perez
Munoz.
   Three other men were wounded in the shootout nine miles south of
Tijuana, which occurred as the soldiers either raided or prepared
to raid the ranch, police sources told Romero.
   Those at the ranch may have been tipped off about the raid,
triggering the shootout, the sources said. Police also indicated
that a cache of weapons, including AK-47 assault rifles, may have
been seized.
