<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     08-19 0951</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0994</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The odds the government is putting on an end
to the drought over the next couple of months would likely be of
little interest to even the most dedicated riverboat gambler.
   The probability of getting enough rain to end the drought ranges
``from 1 in 500 for central Iowa to 1 in 1,000'' for at least three
other major drought regions, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration reports.
   In central Iowa, for example, the amount of rain needed by Oct.
31 to end the drought totals 22.42 inches. That amount can be
expected in the August-October period only once in 500 years, the
advisory said.
   The other three all came out to one chance in 1,000 of getting
enough rain by the end of October to declare the drought broken.
Those areas are northeastern Montana, near the North Dakota border;
the east slope of the Cascades in Washington; and Tennessee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regional disparities in personal incomes
widened last year as strong economic growth continued for coastal
states while states in America's heartland did not fare as well,
the government reports.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that the current economic
expansion is the first in 28 years in which regional differences in
incomes have grown larger rather than narrowing.
   The department said all 10 of the states with the highest
average personal incomes last year were on the nation's coasts:
eight along the Atlantic and two, California and Alaska, on the
Pacific.
   Seven of the 10 states with the lowest incomes were in the
South. Mississippi remained in last place with a per capita income
of $10,292, an increase of 6.5 percent over the previous year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House says it will not
provide information sought by congressional investigators about
alleged drug dealing by Panamanian ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega
unless the scope of the investigation is reduced.
   The announcement Thursday by President Reagan's chief spokesman,
Marlin Fitzwater, came as Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis accused the White House of ``stonewalling'' the probe by
the General Accounting Office.
   The inquiry could delve into Republican presidential nominee
George Bush's knowledge of the Noriega case.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jump in the syphilis rate to the highest level
in 37 years shows that minorities, and particularly heterosexuals,
have failed to heed the message about practicing safe sex despite
the AIDS scare, health officials say.
   The national Centers for Disease Control on Thursday reported
35,241 cases of syphilis in the United States in 1987. The rate of
14.6 per 100,000 people was up from an estimated 11.4 a year
earlier and equaled the 1982 rate as the highest since the rate of
16.7 in 1950.
   Reported U.S. cases of syphilis rose 30 percent in two years,
from 27,143 or 11.5 per 100,000 in 1985, the CDC said.
</TEXT>
