<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Digger'sDiner ADV23   08-19 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digger's Diner, ADV 23,0659</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday PMs, Aug. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Giving Away Diner, But No Takers So Far</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUTLER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bumper stickers bragged, ``Nothing could
be finer than to eat at Digger's Diner.'' Now it's a diner to go.
   Anyone willing to flip flapjacks and hamburgers _ and pay the
cost of moving it _ can have the 1940s-vintage restaurant free of
charge, says William ``Digger'' Young.
   He grew tired of the diner chores because he also was juggling
jobs as a mortician, Butler County coroner, and ``Clown on Roller
Skates'' at children's hospitals and nursing homes.
   ``It's just that I wore too many hats. I'd ... put an apron on
over my suit and pour coffee. You didn't catch me cooking, but I'd
be running the cash register. I liked to be where the money was,''
he said.
   Young, 55, got his nickname from the funeral business his family
has owned since 1896.
   His funeral home is next to the diner, painted brown and yellow
to match. But the location is purely coincidental. Unlike the
funeral business, Young's diner brought customers back, before it
closed a few years ago.
   ``We had great food. Some of my customers were seven days a
week. Some would have breakfast and their evening meals there,
too,'' he said.
   Young wants to use the land occupied by the diner to expand the
funeral home and has been trying to sell the all-steel building for
two years. When no buyers nibbled, he decided to give it away and
placed newspaper ads that offered it ``free for the moving.''
   So far, the response has been pretty dead because no one has
been willing to pay the several thousand dollars necessary to have
the diner dismantled and moved, Young said.
   ``When they find out what it will cost to move it, they don't
seem to want to go any further,'' he said.
   The diner is the all-American variety, a Jerry O'Mahoney Inc.
special from Elizabeth, N.J., with curvaceous lines, stainless
steel trim, vinyl-covered stools and formica counters. It arrived
in Butler on two flatbed trucks in the early 1940s and had several
owners until Young bought it seven years ago.
   The pie was homemade, the burgers thick and the cereal came in
little boxes.
   But now all that's left is the building. Young sold the
refrigerators and countertops to a pizza restaurant in Illinois,
the pizza oven to a Pennsylvania campground, and the stoves, grill
and cash register to a Youngstown, Ohio, restaurant.
   ``Nobody would come in and take the whole place,'' he said.
``Then it got to be that I just started stripping things apart.''
   Stale cake donuts, paper doilies and a baby's yellow rattle
litter the dirty floor, and the walls in the kitchen area are
coated with decades of grease.
   But Young says there's still plenty of life in the diner, which,
with its concrete floor and industrial-strength walls, seems built
to last.
   ``There's stainless inside, good stainless,'' he said, picking
through the rubble to reveal an old menu. ``Paint that steel and
polish the stainless and you have a pretty good looking building.''
   But more than anything, it was an institution in this bustling
western Pennsylvania city of about 17,000. As a teen-ager, Young
remembers well the lines that formed outside.
   ``People waited to get in. It was a very busy diner,'' he said.
   When Young ran the diner, it featured such culinary specialties
as the ``Digger Special'' _ a hamburger topped with a fried egg and
sauteed mushrooms, his favorite.
   Speaking of his decision to give the diner away, he said, ``I'd
like to see it used someplace, and I'd go past and say, `That used
to be mine.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday PMs, Aug. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
