<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Britain-BlackVoice ADV26   08-19 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Black Voice, ADV26,0833</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Radical Black Leader is Strong Voice in Britain's Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernie Grant was branded a public enemy three
years ago for defending black youths involved in a north London
riot in which a policeman was hacked to death.
   Today, far from being hounded out of public life, 44-year-old
Grant is a member of Parliament and perhaps the most influential
black politician in Britain.
   When Grant, Diane Abbott and Paul Boateng won seats for the
opposition Labor Party in the June 1987 election to become the
first blacks ever to enter the House of Commons, many hailed it as
a breakthrough for Britain's 2.4 million blacks.
   Those who feared that Grant's flamboyant radicalism would prove
disruptive have been confounded. With his greying beard,
gap-toothed smile and melodious Caribbean accent, Grant has emerged
as a charming conversationalist and a dedicated parliamentarian.
   ``I suppose some people must have expected me to act in a
certain way and they were probably surprised,'' he said in an
interview. ``But I haven't adjusted my approach to politics in any
way.''
   That approach holds that the 4-percent black minority ``are at
the bottom of the pile'' and becoming ``a powder keg'' in the inner
cities.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if there were another disturbance
tomorrow,'' he said. ``It's there and it's going to happen because
the government isn't paying any attention to it.
   ``We've got our backs to the wall, and we're fighting against a
very racist government that discriminates against black people.
   ``The problem I think black people are facing now isn't the
overt racism that to a large extent happened in the 60s ... but
it's the unconscious racism, the racism of the people that make
policy that will affect a large amount of black people adversely.''
   Grant emigrated from his native Guyana, a former British colony
on South America's northeast coast, to Britain in 1963. Here he
became the first black ever to head a municipal council, leading
the north London borough of Haringey for three years.
   He burst into national prominence in 1985 when an impoverished
housing project in the Tottenham area of Haringey erupted in riots
and the policeman was hacked to death _ the first ever to die in
British race-related unrest.
   Grant accused the predominantly white police force of sparking
the violence and, in his most controversial utterance, said the
blacks felt they had given the police ``a bloody good hiding
(thrashing).''
   He insisted he was not seeking to justify the killing but simply
explaining how other blacks felt about it.
   The effect was incendiary.
   The right-wing tabloid press called him ``Barmy Bernie,'' Home
Secretary Douglas Hurd branded him ``a high priest of race
conflict,'' and nearly 1,000 Haringey borough workers staged a
one-day strike demanding his resignation. His white girlfriend,
councilor Sharon Lawrence, received death threats.
   ``I've never denied it,'' he says now, ``I've never regretted
it, I've never withdrawn what I said. My position at the time was
to put forward the views of the young people.
   ``It defused the situation. A lot of the newspapers turned on
me. ... I was quite clear in what I was doing.''
   In the 1987 election, he carried Tottenham, where 37 percent of
the electorate are black or Asian, with a sharply reduced Labor
majority.
   In his maiden speech to Parliament, Grant said that unless young
blacks were offered better prospects, ``they will find other means
of expressing their frustration.''
   He claims police still harass black youths, using unnecessary
force and planting evidence.
   When he first arrived in Parliament, Grant said, he underwent an
initiation ceremony in which seven or eight legislators from the
governing Conservative Party gathered around him in the Smoking
Room and ``sort of baited me'' with racial innuendo.
   ``They were deliberately trying to create an incident, but it
didn't work,'' he said. ``I was quite cool.''
   When a doorman tried to eject him from the public gallery ``even
though he knew who I was,'' Grant threatened to withdraw from the
daily business of Parliament until the Speaker examined his
complaint. The doorman apologized.
   Grant has confronted Parliament with issues ranging from alleged
harassment of blacks in the armed forces to Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's ``hands-off'' policy toward South Africa.
   But he said he has problems with the Labor Party too.
   He charges that its hierarchical system keeps black politicians
out of the limelight and ignores his expertise in local government
and race relations.
   Nonetheless, Grant said: ``I'm quite happy, despite all the
faults of the place (Parliament), to be there. It's relatively easy
compared to the pressure I was under when I was leader of Haringey
Council. To some extent, the spotlight has been dimmed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Aug. 26</NOTE>
