<DOCNO> AP880819-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Bernstein Adv21-2Takes   08-19 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Bernstein, Adv 21 - 2 Takes,0893</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Leonard Bernstein: The Peter Pan of Classical Music Shines At 70</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   ``I don't like to be reminded I'm getting old. After 25, it's
all downhill.'' _ Leonard Bernstein, 1958.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN STEINBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He's gone through life like a volcano, erupting
in a torrent of creative energy as constant as his chain of
cigarettes. And his dramatic bursts and artistic drive have not
abated as he celebrates his 70th birthday.
   Leonard Bernstein, the
composer-conductor-pianist-teacher-television celebrity, will mark
the Aug. 25 birthday with four nights of performances at the
Tanglewood Music Center in Massachusetts, where he once studied
under the great conductor Serge Koussevitsky.
   ``I haven't slept very much in months,'' the stocky,
white-haired maestro said last week at Tanglewood. ``I have no
further request of the fates except time to write my music. ...
I've got a lot of music to write.''
   Bernstein, who's thrilled millions around the world with his
compositions, his podium pirouettes and his more than 400
recordings, has been active as he approached this milestone year.
From May until December, his schedule listed 63 conducting
performances in 25 cities in 10 countries. Three were in Moscow
last month, his first visit to the country of his parents in 29
years.
   The past year also has seen premieres of two Bernstein
compositions: ``My Twelve Tone Melody,'' for Irving Berlin's 100th
birthday, and ``Jubilee Games,'' to celebrate the 50th anniversary
of the Israel Philharmonic Orchestra, with which he has long been
associated.
   A decade ago, Bernstein's energy waned after the death of his
wife, Chilean actress Felicia Montealegre, and he slipped into
months of depression. But since then, he has divided much of his
time between his homes in New York and Fairfield, Conn., and
Austria, where he has often appeared with the Vienna Philharmonic.
   His life has been as dizzy a balancing act as his emotional
style on the podium: jabs, contortions and leaps that have
occasionally caused him to fall. His style at the podium has been
such a giggle that the music critic Virgil Thomson once said: ``He
shagged, shimmied and, believe it or not, bumped.''
   Bernstein himself has often maintained that conductors should be
actors.
   ``I don't mean that when the music is tragic you've got to act
like Barrymore in `Hamlet.' But you have to indicate to the
orchestra by your body and your face, which is all you've got, what
the shape of the phrase is,'' he said. ``If you don't use a baton,
you work harder, because then your arm has to take its place.''
   Bernstein was a wiry young man of 25, with bony face and dark
wavy hair, when he got the break that helped him become one of
America's titans of classical music.
   On Nov. 14, 1943, he filled in at the last minute for an ailing
Bruno Walter to conduct the New York Philharmonic on a national
radio broadcast. The triumph of the orchestra's newly appointed
assistant conductor was big enough to join the World War II
headlines on the front page of The New York Times.
   ``I had no sleep, no rehearsal, a splitting headache,''
Bernstein recalled in a recent interview with Life. ``I walked on
with an awful hangover and don't remember another thing until I
heard a thunderous ovation.''
   Bernstein has juggled careers as a composer and conductor. His
compositions range from the theatrical (``On the Town,'' ``West
Side Story'') to chamber music.
   In his compositions, as well as his highly acclaimed televised
series of young people's concerts, he skimmed the cream from
classical music and pasteurized it for the American palate.
   ``They write letters to me from the desert, from Montana, from
hundreds of miles off,'' Bernstein once said in an interview with
The Associated Press. ``They've begun to enjoy music. They aren't
scared of it any more. They thought it was too much for them, and
I've helped convince them it isn't.''
   While Bernstein's musical fame grew, his celebrity blossomed.
Media attention really focused when he threw became known as ``that
party at Lenny's'' _ his star-studded fundraiser for the Black
Panthers which was savaged by Tom Wolfe as ``radical chic.''
   Yet he has been shrewd in marketing his career, setting up
Amberson Enterprises in 1969 to manage films, TV specials and
videocasettes of his performances.
   Born in Lawrence, Mass., to a middle-class Russian-Jewish
family, Bernstein got a late start in music. He was 10 when his
Aunt Clara gave the family an upright piano. But he always had an
ear for music, recalled his mother, Jennie, in ``Bernstein: A
Biography'' by Joan Peyser.
   ``When he was 4 or 5, he would play an imaginary piano on his
windowsill,'' Mrs. Bernstein said in the book. ``When we finally
got a piano, he did what he now says he did: made love to it all
the time.''
   His father, Sam, however, hoped young Lenny would join his
beauty supply business. Bernstein persisted with piano lessons. He
went on to study under Walter Piston at Harvard University, and
under Fritz Reiner at the Curtis Institute.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Bernstein Adv21-1stAdd   08-19 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Bernstein, Adv 21 - 1st Add,0622</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: Curtis Institute.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   During his Harvard days, he met conductor Dimitri Mitropoulis,
who recognized his genius and encouraged him to pursue conducting.
He also met Aaron Copland at a 1937 concert. Later that night, at a
party for Copland's 37th birthday, Bernstein impressed the composer
with an impromptu performance without the sheet music of his
difficult ``Piano Variations.''
   With Copland's help, Bernstein, whose greatest works were for
the stage, pursued classical composition. He had written
``Jeremiah,'' the first of his three symphonies, before Artur
Rodzinski appointed him his assistant at the philharmonic in 1943.
   Koussevitzky, the Boston Symphony's influential music director
and founder of Tanglewood, advised his student to pursue classical
music. But Bernstein continued with popular music.
   The year of his philharmonic appointment, he wrote the ballet
``Fancy Free,'' which was a success. The plot, about three sailors'
24-hour shore leave in New York, was adapted for Broadway's ``On
The Town,'' winning five Tony awards.
   Soon to come were his chamber opera ``Trouble in Tahiti,'' the
movie score for ``On the Waterfront,'' Broadway's ``Wonderful
Town'' and ``Candide,'' and the immortal ``West Side Story,'' the
Romeo-and-Juliet tale set amid the fire escapes and street gangs of
Manhattan in the late 1950s.
   Bernstein's successful substitution for Walter also put him in
great demand as a conductor. He left the philharmonic to be guest
conductor at major orchestras, performing in the United States and
abroad. In 1953, he became the first American to conduct at Milan's
famed La Scala opera house, leading diva Maria Callas in
Cherubini's opera ``Medea.''
   In 1957, the year he completed ``West Side Story,'' Bernstein
joined Mitropoulis as co-director of the New York Philharmonic, and
the following year became the orchestra's first American-born
director.
   During his 11-year tenure, Bernstein led the orchestra on tours
of South America, Europe and Asia and on numerous national
television appearances in which he explained classical music to
Americans young and old. His TV appearances, which included the
``Young People's Concerts,'' won 11 Emmy awards.
   Bernstein has had his critics, who over the years called him
overrated as a composer and thrashed his ballet style on the podium.
   ``Bernstein rose vertically, a la Nijinsky, and hovered there a
good 15 seconds,'' The New York Times' critic Harold Schonberg once
wrote.
   But later, on the occasion of Bernstein's 1,000th performance
with the philharmonic, on Dec. 15, 1971, Schonberg wrote: ``At this
time it is only right to put reservations aside and salute
Bernstein for what he did and even for what he tried to do.
Bernstein was a figure that no conductor in history has matched.''
   Among those scheduled to participate at this week's concerts
with the Boston Symphony Orchestra are his son, Alexander, 33, a
teacher, and daughter Nina, a 26-year-old actress. He also has
another daughter, Jaime Thomas, 36, a rock musician and the mother
of Bernstein's only grandchild.
   Others include conductors Seiji Ozawa, John Williams, Michael
Tilson Thomas, and Lauren Bacall, Phyllis Newman, Betty Comden,
Adolph Green, Van Cliburn, Yo-Yo Ma, Elizabeth Taylor, publisher
Malcolm Forbes and Beverly Sills, who will be host. Tickets were
selling for up to $5,000.
   Despite the ado, Bernstein dreads facing his eighth decade.
   ``Everybody is much more excited about this 70th birthday
business than I am,'' he told The Miami Herald in June. ``I'd like
to ignore it.
   ``In fact, that number is just not in my vocabulary. I hate
those pictures of myself with wrinkles, white hair and glasses. I
look like the little old winemaker.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
