<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stadd   08-19 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st add,0527</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the crop-withering drought in
the United States, European farmers are unlikely to take many new
customers away from Americans in the fiercely competitive export
market, analysts say.
   The United States is expected to draw down on surplus stocks so
that it can continue its export push and hold onto clients.
   Meanwhile, the Agriculture Department said Thursday in
Washington that about 355 million bushels of government-owned feed
grains have been set aside as a reserve to meet potential demand
for emergency livestock use under the $3.9 billion Drought
Assistance Act.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regional disparities in personal incomes
widened in 1987, as booming coastal states continued to outstrip
wage gains in much of the rest of the nation, the government
reports.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that all 10 of the states
with the highest average personal incomes last year were on the
nation's coasts, eight along the Atlantic and Alaska and California
on the Pacific.
   Connecticut ranked No. 1 with residents earning $21,266 for
every adult and child last year, an increase of 8.8 percent over
1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines is in the market for a new
long-range aircraft and hopes to place an order by the end of the
year, but its size and the type of plane have yet to be decided, a
Delta spokesman says.
   The order, which reportedly could total $6 billion, would be a
record for commercial plane sales.
   Jim Lundy, a Delta spokesman, said Thursday, ``The size of the
order will depend on which airplane we select and what we see as
our long-range need.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roy Rogers fast-food chain will pull a
television commercial that school cafeteria workers found demeaning
for its portrayal of them as drab and lazy servers of unappetizing
food, a spokesman for the chain has said.
   A local of the State, County and Municipal Workers had objected
to the ad.
   Rick Sneed, public relations director for Marriott, which owns
the Roy Rogers chain, said Thursday the ad was intended to be a
spoof of the way cafeterias were years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela will issue $100 million of
Eurobonds Monday, marking the second time a developing nation
debtor ventures into the international bond market since the Third
World debt crisis began.
   The issue, registered in Luxembourg, was arranged by Samuel
Montagu & Co. Ltd., a part of Britain's Midland Bank group, Peter
Wallin, a Midland Bank representative in Caracas, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
