<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Banks Cool Off Dollar Advance; Stocks, Bonds Up Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dollar-selling by central banks helped pushed the U.S. currency
down in a day that saw small advances in the stock and bond markets.
   Analysts said the dollar's fall Thursday was limited by a strong
residue of bullish sentiment toward the dollar resulting from
relatively high U.S. interest rates.
   The Federal Reserve was said to have sold dollars to buy West
German marks twice in late trading Thursday in New York, when the
market was thin and more vulnerable to the action. European banks
had sold dollars earlier in the day.
   In addition to the banks' intervention, market watchers said the
dollar was hit by reports that U.S. Commerce Secretary William
Verity said U.S. exports and the world economy as a whole would be
better off if the dollar were trading at 1.8 West German marks. It
is trading around 1.9 marks.
   On Wall Street, a weak advance fizzled Thursday on profit-taking
in another slow trading session. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks closed with a 1.07 gain to 2,027.03. Broader
indices also showed marginal advances.
   ``I think it's just an apathetic market,'' said Peter J.
DaPuzzo, manager of retail equities at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
in New York.
   The bond market strengthened slightly. The yield of the
Treasury's 30-year bond, which moves opposite from prices, fell to
9.40 percent from late Wednesday's 9.41 percent.
   Coffee futures prices rose sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar &
Cocoa Exchange. Elsewhere, frozen pork belly futures soared the
daily limit.
   Oil futures prices closed mostly higher in moderate trading. On
the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
rose 10 cents a barrel to close at $15.57.
</TEXT>
