<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have moved higher in moderate
trading as traders maneuvered ahead of the expiration of near-month
contracts.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, rose 10 cents a barrel to close at $15.57 on Thursday.
Other contract months were mixed.
   Most futures prices of oil products traded on the exchange also
rose. Contracts for September delivery of wholesale heating oil
rose 0.22 cent to finish at 44.15 cents a gallon. September
unleaded gasoline rose 0.66 cent to 47.28 cents a gallon.
   Analysts attributed most of the rise in the September contract
to last-minute positioning by investors in advance of the closeout
of the contract on Monday.
   ``There is little news to spur the market,'' said Richard Kane,
a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. ``People are
positioning themselves on the September contract and waiting for
further direction.''
   Traders also were influenced by reports that crude inventories
on the coast of the Gulf of Mexico had declined by 6 million a
week, analysts said.
   ``It's important for the crude market,'' Kane said. ``Prices
firmed off of that.''
   Traders also were watching the gasoline market in anticipation
of some tightening of supplies in the near future, analysts said.

</TEXT>
