<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ThriftPlan-Investors Bjt   08-19 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thrift Plan-Investors, Bjt,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessman, Banker Invest $48 Million In Savings And Loan Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $1.3 billion federally-assisted merger of 12
troubled savings and loan associations demonstrates investor faith
in Texas and in the recovery of the thrift industry, according to a
Dallas businessman involved in the buyout.
   Lone Star Technologies Financial Service Corp., a subsidiary of
Lone Star Technologies Inc. of Dallas, and an investor group headed
by Chicago banker William E. Gibson have agreed to pay $48 million
for the thrifts, in a deal announced Thursday.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. is providing a $499
million note immediately to restore positive net worth to the
merged thrifts, and could spend a total of $1.3 billion in the
transaction.
   ``We're very enthusiastic about this innovative transaction
because we believe it helps to solve the Texas savings and loan
problem,'' said William Howard Beasley III, chairman and chief
executive officer of Lone Star Technologies.
   ``It demonstrated our faith in the institutions, in the future
of Texas and in the thrift industry as a whole,'' Beasley said.
   Lone Star and the Gibson group are the first investors from
outside the savings and loan industry to participate in a buyout
under the so-called Southwest Plan for aiding the region's thrift
industry, said Mary A. Creedon, deputy executive director of the
FSLIC.
   The thrifts were placed under receivership and combined to form
the new institution of American Federal Bank F.S.B.
   Gibson, an executive vice president with Continental Illinois
National Bank and Trust Co. in Chicago, will return to Dallas to
head the newly formed institution.
   He said his group had been considering investment in the Texas
industry long before formation of the Southwest Plan, a Federal
Home Loan Bank Board program in which regulators plan to merge or
close more than 100 of the 279 thrifts that operated in Texas on
Jan. 1. With Thursday's transaction, 24 have cases have been
resolved in Texas.
   The Gibson group ``took a look at what was going on in Texas and
what was going on in the thrift business and just felt that a new
approach was in order,'' Gibson said.
   ``There was an awful lot that was good about Texas and about the
thrift business but both had their problems. We just felt there was
some room for some new blood some new approaches, some new
expertise.''
   Gibson is a former senior vice president of RepublicBank Corp.
of Dallas. He and Beasley have a nearly 20-year friendship dating
back to their association in Washington. Beasley once served as a
special assistant to Secretary of the Treasury and Gibson served as
a special assistant to the Council of Economic Advisers.
   Gibson said he felt comfortable returning to Texas despite its
shaky economy and the shaky financial condition of the savings and
loan industry.
   ``We're going to be making loans, making loans sensibly. We're
not going to make acquisition, development or construction loans.
We're going to have more sound business practices.''
   Ms. Creedon said a large number of depositors, possibly more
than 100,000, would be affected by the transaction. But she said
all deposits, insured and uninsured would transfer to the newly
formed institution.
</TEXT>
