<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MusicMachine     08-19 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Music Machine,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mainframe Computers Make Sweet Music With New Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mainframe computers can write musical harmonies
in the style of Johann Sebastian Bach by using new software created
by a researcher-composer at International Business Machines Corp.
   Kemal Ebcioglu said Thursday he created the software to help
understand Bach's style more precisely _ and to help explore the
frontiers of computer science.
   The musical work led to the creation of a programming language
that could be adapted for other jobs requiring heavy computation,
such as deciphering the molecular structure of genes, Ebcioglu said.
   Although other computer programs can be used to compose music,
the IBM software is the only one to duplicate the Bach chorale
styles, Ebcioglu said.
   The program, called Choral, adds bass, tenor and alto parts to
chorale melodies that are written for soprano. It is not intended
as a commercial product because of its limited usefulness and its
huge appetite for computing power.
   Ebcioglu, who holds a master's degree in music and a doctorate
in computer science, said the software uses more than 350
compositional rules that he programmed into it based on years of
study of Bach's chorales.
   A chorale harmonization of 20 bars requires about 30 minutes of
computing time and 23 billion simple instructions on one of IBM's
giant 3090 series of mainframe computers, a measure of the
complexity of Bach's music.
   Choral would probably receive an above-average to excellent
grade in a college composition class, said Ebcioglu.
   ``It is unknown to what degree we can replicate human creativity
by a computer. But what we can do is impose much higher standards
on computer-created music,'' said Ebcioglu.
   Choral builds a harmonization stage by stage. It backtracks and
changes notes that it considers to be responsible for a dead-end
when the dead-end is encountered. In that way, it resembles an
animal negotiating a maze.
   Many kinds of scientific research involve similar searches.
Ebcioglu's new programming language, Backtracking Specification
Language, simplifies the search process.
   Bach's chorale style was relatively easy to replicate because it
is well-understood, Ebcioglu said. He said other natural candidates
for expert systems programs would be Antonio Vivaldi and Franz
Joseph Haydn.
   Compositional rules by themselves cannot produce beautiful
music, Ebcioglu said. Composers use additional knowledge _ talent _
for choosing among the many theoretically possible extensions of a
particular composition.
   Ebcioglu said he came up with a good approximation of talent by
building a large number of precise guidelines based on an
understanding of Bach's style.
   Ebcioglu works at IBM's Thomas J. Watson Research Center in
Yorktown Heights, N.Y.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Self-Service     08-19 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Self-Service,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Court Judge Overturns 39-Year-Old Ban On Self-Service Gas
Stations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge who struck down New Jersey's
39-year-old law banning self-service gas stations has given state
lawmakers six months to enact regulations complying with his
decision.
   Superior Court Judge Martin L. Haines of Mount Holly ruled the
safety considerations that originally prompted passage of the law
in 1949 no longer were valid, and that the law violated the state
constitution's limits on the Legislature's police power.
   In doing so, the judge went against a 1952 state Supreme Court
ruling upholding the law. But he contended the facts of the issue
had changed since then, thus allowing him to break with precedent.
   ``The testimony before me revealed very different facts _
self-service stations are at least as safe as full-service
stations,'' Haines said Thursday in a telephone interview.
   Self-service station proponents praised the decision, made
public Thursday but issued to attorneys on Wednesday.
   ``We see it as a victory for consumer freedom of choice,'' said
John F. Holtz, associate director of the New Jersey Petroleum
Council, which represents the state's largest oil companies.
   But Jerry Ferrara, executive director of the New Jersey Gasoline
Retailer's Association and Allied Trades Inc., which represents
about 3,000 New Jersey service stations, said he was disappointed.
   Ferrara said legalizing self-service would not bring any cost
benefits to motorists, would prompt gasoline stations to lay off
workers and would turn many service stations into gas-only
stations, closing their repair shops.
   New Jersey and Oregon are the only two states that still
prohibit self-service stations.
   Haines' ruling came in a lawsuit filed by Kirschner Brothers Oil
Co. Inc. of Haverford, Pa., against the state Department of Labor.
The company, which owns about 20 service stations in New Jersey,
claimed the law was antiquated and that customers should have a
choice between self- and full-service.
   Proponents of self-service also say it could help drive down
costs at the pump by decreasing labor expenses.
   Proposals to legalize self-service pumps are pending before the
Law and Public Safety Committees in both the Senate and Assembly.
   The law was enacted by legislators who expressed concern that
motorists were endangered by pumping their own gas. Opponents of
self-service stations still back their arguments with newspaper
reports of fires and other accidents that have injured or killed
motorists who were trying to pump their own gas.
   Opponents also say the change would increase profits of gasoline
companies. The labor department has lobbied against changing the
law.
   The state Supreme Court affirmed the statute in 1952. Haines
ruled June 29 that he could not overturn a law affirmed by a higher
court, but reconsidered when asked by Kirschner.
   Haines decided safety no longer was an issue, allowing him to
reverse his earlier ruling and break with precedent.
   The state attorney general's office, which represented the Labor
Department, has not decided whether to appeal the decision, said
spokeswoman Becky Taylor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880819-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-19 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower In Thin, Erratic Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly in thin, erratic trading
in Europe today with market players unsure about the currency's
next direction.
   Gold prices drifted higher in quiet trading.
   Foreign exchange dealers in Italy said enthusiasm for the dollar
waned, especially after concerted intervention by major central
banks on Thursday, which pushed the U.S. currency lower.
   Dealers said they didn't expect the dollar to make any major
moves.
   ``Given (higher U.S.) interest rates, whoever has dollars will
hold onto them,'' said one trader in Milan.
   In Frankfurt, some dealers predicted the dollar will recover
quickly, but others said the market must still consider the
possibility of another round of central bank intervention.
   ``It's not at all clear where the dollar will move now,'' said a
trader at a major West German bank.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.53 yen to a closing 133.40 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 133.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8945 West German marks, down from 1.8980; 1.5930
Swiss francs, down from 1.5955; 6.4243 French francs, down from
6.4340; 2.1350 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1438; 1,403.55 Italian
lire, up from 1,402.75; 1.2270 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2298.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7030 from $1.6989 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $431.30 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $432.40. Both were up from Thursday's late bid
of $431.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $432.50, up from $431.00 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.93 to close at a bid $434.21.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.68 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $6.66.
</TEXT>
