<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-19 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Loses Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed
firmer at the end of the trading week today, while the U.S. dollar
lost ground against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 49.50-point
loser Thursday, bounced back to gain 80.06 points, or 0.28 percent,
closing the day at 28,209.42.
   Volume traded on the first section was an estimated 1 billion
shares, up by 250 million shares from the previous day's session.
   ``Volume came back to its normal level after thin trading
earlier this week, but share prices have been moving very little
because the market is lacking specific direction even though it's
stable,'' said an analyst with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``Dealers are now searching for what to buy, and they're unable
to decide on any one thing,'' said the analyst, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Among the winners in today's trading were steels, heavy machine
and real estate issues.
   After opening lower, the dollar continued to decline and ended
the day at 133.40 yen, down 0.53 yen. The currency was traded
between 133.15 yen and 133.50, down from Thursday's range of
133.73-134.10 yen.
   An exchange dealer at a bank in Tokyo attributed the lower
dollar to a ``wait-and-see mood'' prevailing in the market.
   The stock and foreign exchange markets will be closed in Tokyo
Saturday. The Tokyo Stock Exchange is closed on the second and
third Saturday of each month and there are no foreign exchange
dealings on Saturday.
</TEXT>
