<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0816EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NudeDefiance     08-19 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nude Defiance,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Club Members Strip to Swim in Protest of Court Coed Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Male members of the San Francisco Press
Club are defying a judge's order to give female members the same
access to an indoor pool by continuing to swim in the nude.
   Before the ruling a month ago, the Press Club allowed men to use
the pool daily from 7 a.m. to 9 p.m., but women were limited to two
hours on Thursday and four on Sunday. About 180 of the club's 1,800
members are women.
   A female club member filed a discrimination suit against the
club, prompting Superior Court Judge Maxine Chesney to order it to
immediately end its practice of restricting the hours female
members could use the pool and locker room.
   Despite her victory in court, Irene Vacchina, a Press Club
member since 1979, said locker room attendants still tell her she
can't go in when the men are there.
   ``I feel cheated and hurt by the club. It is illegal for them to
take my money and then give me unequal treatment,'' she said. Dues
are $780 a year.
   The club's acting manager, Joyce Cirimelli, said she has posted
a copy of the judge's ruling in the pool area and a notice saying
that members who want to swim must wear bathing suits, but many men
are still swimming in the buff.
   The men ``act like it's their kingdom down there,'' she said.
   Vacchina's lawyer, Kathy Mount, said the club could have avoided
the problem if it had chosen a different way to comply with the
order. Instead of opening the pool to both sexes, the club could
have let women and men use the pool the same number of hours but on
different days.
   Press Club members who disobey the ruling can be found in
contempt of court and fined or jailed, Mount said.
</TEXT>
