<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0848EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MexicoToday     08-19 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico Today,0323</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari
Thursday pledged to institute agricultural credit reforms as part
of an overhaul of federal farm policy.
   Salinas, the victor in the contested July 6 presidential
elections, said his administration will give peasant farmers
credits in cash rather than in in-kind goods.
   He also pledged to create communal retail outlets for peasant
crops and eliminate the need for peasant farmers to market their
goods through middlemen.
   ``Justice, Production and Productivity'' mark the three central
themes of the next administration's farm policy, Salinas said.
   The president-elect takes office Dec. 1.
   Salinas made his comments in chairing the inaugural session of
an agricultural policy study group sponsored by the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Commerce Department officials warned
Thursday the government was ready to slap fines, revoke business
licenses and issue arrest warrants for those retailers found
violating pricing policies under the second phase of an
anti-inflation program.
   Victor Campos Chargoy and Efren Ocampo Lopez, directors of the
department's price inspections and vigilance division, said the
government could bring fines of more than $40,000 and close
businesses up to three months for violations of official price
guidelines under the Economic Solidarity Pact.
   The government announced Aug. 14 it was extending the program to
Nov. 30. The pact has frozen wages, the peso currency exchange rate
and prices for government-regulated goods and services.
   The national sales tax for essential foods and medicines, as
well as on rents, will be lowered as part of the pact's second
stage, the government announced.
   The Economic Solidarity Pact was unveiled in December as
inflation soared to a record 159.2 percent last year. On Aug. 10,
the central bank announced the pact had succeeded in bringing
consumer prices down to a 1.7 percent increase in July, the lowest
monthly rise in seven years.
</TEXT>
