<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0937EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MiddleEast-Oil     08-19 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Middle East-Oil,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Forecast To Remain Weak, OPEC's Output Share Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices are expected to remain at their present
low levels through the early 1990s, according to a study published
Friday by analysts of Business International, a Geneva-based
consulting firm.
   Oil prices will start to recover when members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, especially the
Middle East producers, recover some of the world market share that
they began losing to non-OPEC members in the early 1980s, the study
said.
   OPEC's output will increase to 21.4 million barrels a day in
1992 from an estimated 18.4 million this year, the study said.
   The current self-imposed ceiling on the output of 12 of the OPEC
members is 15.06 million barrels a day, although the countries have
been exceeding their quotas. Iraq, the 13th member, has refused to
join in the quota sharing program since 1986.
   ``Oil prices will remain at their current weak levels,'' a
summary of the study said. ``This will undermine revenues and
increased indebtedness in parts of the region.''
   In spite of weak oil prices, the annual economic growth of the
six major economies in the region, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Algeria,
Iran, Iraq, Turkey, was predicted to average 2.7 percent during
1988-1992, as compared with 0.5 percent during the five preceding
years.
   The study warned Western companies doing business in the Middle
East to brace for tough conditions in the next few years, but said
it expected a recovery after 1990.
   ``Market conditions will become increasingly favorable to
initiatives by foreign investors and the private sector,'' it
added. ``In all the countries, liberalization policies will open
new avenues for local and foreign investors.''
   The study said that no solutions were expected for the long-term
regional political conflicts. Even a formal cease-fire in the Gulf
war ``is not expected to reduce the level of militarization of the
Iran-Iraq border or of the Gulf as a whole,'' it added.
</TEXT>
