<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Davis-MetroBank     08-19 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Davis-Metro Bank,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Davis Pumps Millions Into Bank To Keep It Out of Trouble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Marvin Davis transferred $8.3 million
into Metro National Bank of Denver to meet minimum federal
standards and to prevent the bank's failure.
   ``With this additional capital, the bank will continue serving
its depositors and, at the same time, have the opportunity to
develop a long-term program, responsive to the needs of the Denver
business community,'' Davis said in a prepared statement after
transferring the money on Thursday.
   Davis, the primary owner of the $77 million bank in Denver's
17th Street financial district, made the contribution to Metro's
capital just after the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. held an
auction for the bank, in which the FDIC tried to find a buyer for
the bank.
   The infusion of capital brings the bank's capital-to-assets
ratio to 7 percent, the minimum required by regulations, and
boosted Davis' contributions to Metro to $32 million, a spokesman
said.
   Davis, who divides his time between Los Angeles and Denver, has
bailed the bank out of problems before.
   The bank has been hit hard by energy, real estate and penny
stock-related loans. It was on the brink of insolvency last month
after the Colorado Supreme Court refused to strike a $940,000
judgment against the bank in a case involving a defunct penny stock
brokerage, regulators said.
   On March 31, Metro's capital had fallen to 1.64 percent of
assets, after the bank lost $610,000 during the first three months
of the year. It lost $12.9 million in 1987, according to Sheshunoff
Information Services Inc.
   Problem loans totaled $11.3 million, or more than 20 percent of
the bank's total loan portfolio, officials said.
   The bank's problems have forced officials to reduce its size by
more than 50 percent since 1984, when it had $181 million in assets.
</TEXT>
