<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMUnit-Layoffs     08-19 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Unit-Layoffs,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bearings Plant To Cut Work Force By 550</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Motors Corp. unit plans to lay
off about 550 workers at its plant here and move its spindle
bearing operations to Ohio, officials of New Departure-Hyatt
Bearings said.
   When the move is completed, about 500 workers will remain at the
bearing manufacturing plant in Bristol, where 3,500 people worked
just 10 years ago, company officals said Thursday.
   The GM subsidiary, which recently phased out 675 jobs after
eliminating production of commercial bearings, also may sell its
plant here and seek a smaller site, Mayor John J. Leone said.
   The move to Sandusky, Ohio, was ``purely a business decision,''
said Jerome Bishop, director of media relatins at the components
division. He said the two plants in Sandusky and Bristol gave the
company 40 percent more space than it needed to run the separate
spindle bearing operations.
   Bishop said there was no guarantee the company, celebrating its
100th anniversary in Bristol this year, would stay in Connecticut.
   ``We're in an extremely competitive worldwide market and we must
remain competitive with all our product lines,'' he said.
   Bishop said 130 of the 330 workers in the spindle bearings
operation will be offered jobs in Sandusky. The other 200 workers
will be offered a cash settlement, early retirement or placed in a
company job bank, which pays workers their full salaries to remain
available for spot duty.
   New Departure's decision to move some operations is another blow
to an industry beleagured both in Connecticut and in the United
States.
   The International Trade Commission reported to Congress earlier
this month that international competition, declining profits and
decreasing investment have dangerously weakened the industry.
   In Connecticut, the bearings industry employed 16,000 people in
the mid-1960s, but that number dropped to just 7,600 by 1984.
</TEXT>
