<DOCNO> AP880819-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers     08-19 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspapers Contend With JOA Reversal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While attorneys considered what to do about an
order holding off a joint operating agreement between The Detroit
News and Detroit Free Press, laid-off employees reoccupied the
desks they had just vacated.
   Workers expressed confusion and resignation at the holdup of the
agreement scheduled to take effect Thursday.
   Some, like artist Annie Lazurek, who had been laid off Wednesday
after 22 years at the Free Press, said they were returning to
protect severance benefits.
   ``What choice do I have?'' Lazurek asked.
   A temporary restraining order late Wednesday by U.S. District
Judge Joyce Hens Green halted the joint operating agreement granted
by Attorney General Edwin Meese III before he left office last week.
   That blocks the merger at least until a Sept. 8 hearing.
   The Detroit Newspaper Agency, which was to begin handling the
combined functions of the two papers Thursday, remained in limbo
and executives scrambled to put back together the separate
operations they had dismantled.
   Newspaper attorneys haven't decided how to respond to Green's
order, said William Keating, chief executive of the agency.
   ``It's unbelievable. My desk is cleared except for one pen,''
said Tom Szczepanski, a Free Press account executive who would have
reported to the same job in a different location under the JOA.
   Robert DeCooman, 60, had accepted early retirement and had seen
his son laid off Wednesday after 16 years with the News.
   The two, among an estimated 500 people at the News and Free
Press whose positions would be eliminated under a JOA, thought they
had left the newspaper for the last time, only to be notified to
return to work Thursday.
   ``This is terrible,'' DeCooman said. ``I'm so sick of this
because the last two years of my life have been absolutely nothing
but turmoil.''
   ``It's like an emotional roller coaster,'' said his son, Richard
DeCooman. ``If I refuse to come back, where does that leave me?''
   Free Press General Manager Robert J. Hall said Wednesday was
``one of the worst days of my life.''
   ``The employees of the Free Press have lived under uncertainty
and on an emotional roller coaster for the past 28 months,'' Hall
said. ``And to put this on top of all that is more than most people
should be called on to endure.''
   The Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., and the News, owned
by Gannett Co. Inc., asked the U.S. Justice Department in 1986 for
a limited antitrust exemption to allow the JOA, citing substantial
losses at both papers and saying the Free Press probably would fail
without the arrangement.
   Opponents such as Detroit Mayor Coleman Young and unions
representing the newspaper employees dropped their opposition after
Knight-Ridder said earlier this year that it would close the Free
Press if a JOA were denied.
   The new ruling came in a suit filed by a group of newspaper
readers and advertisers called Michigan Citizens for an Independent
Press.
   ``Where were they two and a half years ago, or even six months
ago?'' asked Lucy Page, a classified advertising sales
representative at the News.
   Page said she had first been happy because she was to keep her
job under the JOA. ``But then I went out and saw all the people who
were getting moved and all, and by the end of the day I just
couldn't be happy.''
   Bringing the new suit were state Sen. John Kelly, D-Detroit; W.
Edward Wendover, publisher of the Plymouth-Canton Community Crier;
former Detroit News gossip columnist Matt Beer; a former News
circulation employee, William Cowan; David Kersh, president of
Metro Publications Inc., and Murray Greenhalge, a Free Press
printer.
   They were represented by Public Citizen Litigation Group, a
Washington-based organization founded by Ralph Nader.
   Kelly said the group sought closer scrutiny ``of something that
would have a 100-year monopoly than the legal review given it by
Mr. Meese.''
</TEXT>
