<HEAD>Steady Rise In International Traffic Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International air passenger traffic is expected to
rise an average 7 percent annually until 1992, with Asia and the
Pacific showing the fastest growth, an industry group said Friday.
   This year, non-domestic traffic is likely to increase about 8
percent worldwide, and growth will taper off slightly but remain
strong over the next four years, the International Air Transport
Association said.
   The average annual increase until 1992 was forecast at 9 percent
for Asia and the Pacific, 7 percent for traffic to and from North
America, and about 6 percent for Europe.
</TEXT>
