<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Turkey-EEC     08-19 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Turkey-EEC,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Wants ECC Membership Bid Handled In Reasonable Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz on Friday
urged EEC nations to remember that Turkey is ``part of Europe'' and
cautioned against delay in considering his nation's bid to be a
full-fledged member of the European Economic Community.
   Yilmaz, in his first news conference since assuming the post
nine months ago, said Turkey's application, submitted in April
1987, is currently being studied at technical levels by a committee.
   The EEC's governing body, the council of ministers, will act
upon the committee report, either turning down Turkey's bid or
inviting Turkey to join in talks aimed at arranging full membership.
   ``The message we give to our European friends is that no matter
what the committee recommends, the final decision is basically a
political one and Turkey is politically and strategically a part of
Europe,'' Yilmaz said.
   Turkey will not settle for less than eventual full membership,
Yilmaz said.
   Negotiations for membership should start ``in a reasonable
period of time,'' the foreign minister said without citing a
timetable.
   If the trading bloc turns down Turkey's application or takes too
long to review it, ``Turkey will review its relationship with
Western Europe,'' Yilmaz told reporters.
   Many member countries have opposed Turkey's membership on
grounds that it the country is economically backward or that its
democracy needs perfecting.
   Greece, which has major disputes with Turkey, has made clear it
will block Turkey's bid unless Turkish troops in Cyprus are
withdrawn.
</TEXT>
