<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
but quickly turned mixed today in light trading on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Much of the early buying was based on the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Thursday that it had targeted China
for sales of an additional 2 million metric tons of subsidized U.S.
wheat, analysts said.
   ``That got things fired up a little bit here. The excitement was
on the wheat,'' said Jerry Gidel, a grain market analyst with G.H.
Miller, a Chicago-based commodities trading division of
British-owned LIT America Inc.
   But light showers and cooler temperatures in the heart of the
Midwestern croplands put pressure on corn and soybean futures.
   Analysts say the grain markets appear to be responding more
readily to export news than to weather factors, although soybean
growers would welcome more rain to help their plants through the
end of the critical flowering and pod-setting stage.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.96 a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to 1\ cents higher with September at $2.89 a bushel;
oats were 2{ cents to 3 cents lower with September at $2.58{ a
bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 9 cents higher with August
at $8.80 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .40 cent lower to .18 cent higher with August
at 71.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .62 cent
lower with August at 81.95 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.35 cent higher with August at 47.70 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .85 cent to 1.63 cent higher with August at 37.80
cents a pound.
   Pork bellies settled sharply higher on Thursday, hog futures
were higher and cattle were mixed.
</TEXT>
