<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IrishDistillersBid     08-19 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Irish Distillers Bid,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GC&B Brands Launches New Bid For Irish Distillers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GC&C Brands Ltd. on Friday launched a new bid for
Irish Distillers Group PLC that values Ireland's leading whiskey
distiller at 253 million Irish punts, or about $354 million.
   The $5.60-a-share bid was made hours after GC&C received
regulatory clearance from Britain's Panel on Takeovers and Mergers
to proceed with a new bid for Irish Distillers, maker of Jameson's
and other whiskies.
   GC&C, a consortium-owned group, was restructured as a wholly
owned subsidiary of Grand Metropolitan PLC on Wednesday. The move
was part of a negotiated settlement between the European Community
Commission and the three original partners in the consortium.
   Under terms of the settlement, Grand Metropolitan agreed to buy
out the interests of Allied-Lyons PLC and Guinness PLC, the two
other companies involved.
   The group originally launched a joint $281 million bid for Irish
Distillers. Under conditions set by the takeover panel, GC&C's
offer constitutes a new bid and isn't technically a revised offer.
   The takeover panel had given GC&C until Monday to announce terms
of a new bid and set a 21-day limit for the offer to remain open.
   GC&C's original offer, which was launched in May and amounted to
$4.46 a share, had attracted 20.34 percent of the shares by last
week.
   The EC blocked the joint bid because officials said the
consortium decided in advance to split up Irish Distillers' markets
and brands, which would violate the Community's competition law.
</TEXT>
