<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv22   08-19 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 22,0622</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Aug. 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Global Market in Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few Americans need to be told anymore that they
are living in a global market, not with all the European cars and
Japanese cameras they have been buying.
   They read stories about British corporations buying out their
American counterparts and Japanese buying up skyscrapers. They
drink Mexican beer. They wear Italian and Brazilian shoes. They
stay at foreign-owned hotels.
   Hardly a day goes by that they do not hear about the value of
the dollar in relation to the pound, yen and mark, and while they
might not realize what all the to-do is about they recognize it is
of global importance.
   And, of course, they also hear about the need for American
companies to export in order to reduce the imbalance of
international payments, which is high on any list of the country's
most urgent and exasperating problems.
   While all this is not new, the understanding of it may even now
not be fully appreciated, because the United States for a century
had the world's biggest economy. It didn't need to export. It
didn't even think about it.
   But now that the global economy is here, Americans face a big
question mark in an area they have not yet given much thought to.
The labor market, that is, also has become globalized, and it could
be affecting millions already.
   In fact, many economic analysts wonder if global competition has
not had a lot to do with the stability of American wages over the
past five years, marked especially by unusual calm in labor
union-management relations.
   Having lost millions of jobs to lower-cost producers in other
countries, organized labor was forced to acknowledge that jobs
could be exported as readily as goods. Foreign workers wanted those
jobs; they got millions of them.
   The impact of all this, however, has been overshadowed during
the past five years by a concurrent phenomenon, the enormous growth
of domestic jobs. To some extent, it hid the fact that so much
employment was sent abroad.
   Now, a test is coming.
   Many economists contend that with the jobless rate now at about
5.4 percent of the civilian labor force, further declines cannot
take place without putting upward pressure on wages. It would
ignite inflation, they say.
   But maybe not. In a global marketplace, such a situation
conceivably could be averted by importing goods made by foreign
workers rather than employing American workers in domestic
factories.
   This factor already was cited in the most recent quarterly
report of the National Federation of Independent Business. ``The
impact of operating in a world labor market (coupled with good
inflation experience) seems to be keeping the lid on wages
increases,'' said economist William Dunkelberg.
   American workers obviously are loathe to lose jobs to foreign
competition, and therefore seem reluctant to seek higher wages.
Based on the low jobless rate they seemingly could; it used to be a
regular occurrence when the jobless rate fell. But according to the
survey, little pressure is evident yet.
   This is uncharted territory for workers, the U.S. economy and
economists.
   ``In this new environment, with differing labor demands, it will
be interesting to see how low the unemployment rate can go before
we encounter significant labor shortages,'' says Dunkelberg.
   Nobody really knows how low that might be, because American
workers know that management has an alternative. That is, it can
simply decide it is less expensive to make products abroad than it
is at home.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday Aug. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
