<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Poland-Miners     08-19 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Miners,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mining Town Caught Up in Strikes & Uncertainty</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, which is moving on general news wires only</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JASTRZEBIE, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the end of their shift, the miners
of Jastrzebie trade their cramped quarters in the coal pits for
their tiny apartments in concrete high-rises.
   Many miners in this town at the center of the latest wave of
Polish strikes must toil seven days a week to supplement their
wages and gain access to special stores that are open only to
miners who agree to work weekends.
   They say long lines for food, irregular family life and constant
manipulation of their interests by management led to anger,
frustration and the strikes that began Tuesday in this mountain
town of 100,000 near the Czechoslovakian border.
   ``What kind of a family life can a man have here?'' said a miner
in his mid-30s, speaking in his two-room apartment overlooking the
mine. He asked that his name not be used.
   For many miners the outlawed trade union Solidarity gave them a
voice and hope that they could change the way they work and live.
   Residents are still proud that key agreements between Solidarity
and the government were signed in Jastrzebie in September 1980.
   And they will never forget the nine miners killed by security
police at the Wujek mine near Katowice, about 35 miles to the
northeast, after martial law was imposed in December 1981,
suppressing Solidarity. The series of strikes are for better wages
and recognition of Solidarity.
   ``You've got to have a goal. In Solidarity you found out you
were worth something. It's a wonderful thing nobody can take
away,'' said Janina Wolnikowska, a local Solidarity activist.
   While her son and husband strike in two different mines, Mrs.
Wolnikowka runs a strike support center in the nearby Holy Virgin
Mary Roman Catholic church that supplies sandwiches and coffee.
   ``I didn't sleep all night, but it's not hard for me,'' she
said. ``We must get through to the men on strike and it's our job
to organize that.''
   Residents have started collecting money to assist the striking
miners and their families.
   Outside the modern July Manifesto mine, which produces
high-grade coal for export, families line up daily waiting for
police to allow them through the barriers to deliver food and
encouragement to their striking relatives holed up in the plant.
   Bread is scarce in the stores near the mine and beer has
disappeared.
   Police patrol the town and are stationed at the entrance to the
church, where the phone was cut early in the strike. Management has
refused to allow priests into the mine.
   Situated atop rolling hills, Jastrzebie was a small spa until it
was rapidly built up about 25 years ago to exploit the rich coal
beds.
   To attract workers, wages were set above the national average
and the waiting time for apartments was often less than a year.
People in other parts of Poland can wait for decades.
   Children, whose lives and future are tied to the mine, appear
immune to the strict police controls, darting in and out of the
dozens of large police vans and trucks around the mine.
   ``Our whole town is on strike. Is America on strike too?'' asked
one small boy.
   Residents spend evenings listening to foreign radio stations,
wondering who will support them throughout the country.
   ``Are you going to work?'' one miner asked another in the
elevator of one high-rise.
   ``Maybe,'' replied the other, who walked away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
