<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AbsenceSurvey     08-19 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Absence Survey,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Finds 18 Percent of Firms Lose One Day Per Worker Each Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of employee absence rates has found
that 18 percent of companies have almost one full day of absence
each week per worker.
   The survey, by Uniforce Temporary Services, a temporary
employment agency, found these companies have an absence rate of 11
percent to 20 percent. Meanwhile, 82 percent of the businesses that
responded to the survey reported absence rates of 2 percent to 10
percent.
   Uniforce said it mailed 5,000 questionnaires, of which 26
percent, or 1,342, were returned. Eighty-one percent of the
respondents were in banking or finance, 28 percent were
manufacturers and 22 percent described themselves as service
companies. Government agencies and educational institutions were
among the other respondents.
   The survey was the first on the issue taken by Uniforce.
   The questionnaire asked managers to list the causes of excessive
absenteeism in order of importance. Lack of supervision for
employees was ranked first, followed by the lack of a policy on
absenteeism and the lack of rewards for good attendance.
   To control excessive absenteeism, 41 percent of the respondents
said they use disciplinary action or penalties combined with
rewards or incentives, 52 percent use disciplinary action alone and
7 percent used rewards alone.
</TEXT>
