<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1421EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-19 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0238</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced marginally today in
thin pre-weekend trading, but few brokers saw signs of a clear
breakout from the current slump.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 4.98 points
to 2,032.01 as of 2 p.m. EDT.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.19 to 148.00. The
American Stock Exchange market-value index fell 0.02 to 294.94.
   Gaining issues outnumbered advances by about 7-to-6 on the NYSE,
with 701 up, 584 down and 561 unchanged. Volume totaled 77.76
million shares with two hours of trading left.
   Hildegarde Zagorski, a stock analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York, linked the advance to higher prices in
the bond market, which pushed yields lower and made stocks a more
attractive investment than bonds. But the bond market retreated
later and the stock gains eroded as well.
   ``Nobody's committing any money,'' said Robert O'Toole, manager
of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York. ``We're going to be in the doldrums for awhile.''
   Several computer issues fell sharply. IBM lost ~ to 113} and
Digital plunged 2] to 92[. On the over-the-counter market, Apple
fell 1| to 40~.
   Polaroid rose { to 43}. The company has been resisting a hostile
takeover attempt by Shamrock Holdings Inc.
