<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Continental-Layoffs 1stLd-Wriethru f0068 08-19 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental-Layoffs, 1st Ld-Wriethru, f0068,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Expected to Lay Off Up to 1,000 Employees, Paper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with confirmation from chairman</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines will lay off up to 1,000
pilots, flight attendants and other personnel as part of a fall
cutback in service, the company's chairman said today.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of both Continental and its parent,
Texas Air Corp., said the layoffs will be formally announced in the
next few days as part of the carrier's new fall schedule.
   Lorenzo, who testified at a federal court hearing on plans by
Continental's sister carrier, Eastern Airlines, to curtail service
to 14 cities, said the retrenchment would include laying off
between 300 and 500 pilots.
   Speaking to reporters after his court appearance, Lorenzo said
the layoffs would involve 2 percent to 3 percent of the company's
36,000 employees. He did not provide a breakdown of the other
employees who would be furloughed, but said they included flight
attendants and management personnel.
   Continental posted a net loss of $231 million for the first six
months of the year.
   The layoffs were first reported by the Houston Chronicle in
today's editions. The newspaper quoted unidentified sources as
saying Denver would be the primary focus of the layoffs.
   Continental announced earlier this year that it would reduce the
number of flights at Denver's Stapleton International Airport from
260 a day to 200, beginning next month.
   ``Obviously, we continue to look at our fall schedule and the
continued overcapacity of Denver and are focusing our attention on
what changes may be required and the effect that might have on our
employees,'' Texas Air spokesman Bruce Hicks told the Chronicle.
   Earlier this month Miami-based Eastern announced it was reducing
operations by 12 percent and eliminating about 4,000 jobs.
   A federal judge in Washington, however, issued a temporary
injunction blocking the job cuts and is holding hearings on the
issue.
   Eastern currently is in federally supervised contract
negotiations with two of its unions.
</TEXT>
