<2ND_LINE>AM-Goodyear-Pipeline,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodyear Trying To Sell All-American Pipeline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. said Friday that
its 1,750-mile All-American Pipeline, which it started building
three years ago, will be sold to pay off debts.
   Goodyear Chairman Robert E. Mercer said that while the company
is forming a plan to sell the oil pipeline to a group of
purchasers, ``no consortium has been formed, no negotiations have
been held and no specific terms have been discussed, including
price.''
   ``We have held some preliminary discussions with several firms
and have received some indications of interest,'' he said in a
statement.
   The $1-billion pipeline project was started to transport oil
from the West Coast to refineries in Texas, said Goodyear spokesman
John Perduyn. The pipeline currently extends 1,200 miles from Santa
Barbara, Calif., to McCamey, Texas, and is pumping 70,000 barrels
of oil a day on a test basis, he said.
   Goodyear began selling some assets a year ago to pay a debt
incurred to fend off a hostile takeover bid by Anglo-French
financier Sir James Goldsmith.
   The Akron-based tire company avoided Goldsmith's grasp by buying
back Goldsmith's 11.5 percent stake for $49.50 a share, or $619
million.
   Among the assets already sold by Goodyear are its oil and gas
fields, with the West Coast fields going to Exxon Corp.
</TEXT>
