<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Peugeot Bjt   08-19 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peugeot, Bjt,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Carmaker Looks To Open Door Wider In U.S. Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French automaker Peugeot SA, its minuscule
presence in the U.S. auto market continuing to decline, is pinning
hopes for recovery on a new model that Europe has named its car of
the year.
   The front-wheel drive Peugeot 405 is being offered in three
models, but Peugeot officials, dealers and industry analysts agree
its most attractive attribute is its base price of $14,500.
   ``We think this car is very right for the marketplace. It is a
range many of our European competitors have gotten away from,''
said Bill Kelly, national sales manager for Peugeot Motors of
America Inc.
   The 405 models, built largely by robot at Peugeot's Sochaux
plant in eastern France, join the Peugeot 505, a basic midsize
sedan, which has been sold in the United States since 1980.
   Sales of the Peugeot 505 have declined drastically in the last
two years _ from 14,431 in 1986 to 9,409 in 1987. Through the first
seven months of this year, Peugeot has sold 4,015 cars compared
with 5,293 for the same period last year.
   Kelly said the company has projected selling 15,405 of the new
Peugeot 405 models in the 1989 sales year and figures on selling
3,505 of the restyled 505 series cars.
   Peugeot's three 405 models are the DL, ($14,500) the S (about
$17,500) and the 16-valve Mi 16 ($21,000).
   ``They've priced it right and it has gotten some good reviews,''
said Thomas O'Grady, an analyst with Integrated Automotive
Resources Inc. in Wayne, Pa. ``The things they've got to get over
are marketing, positioning and advertising. They do have a history
of product and dealer problems,''
   Kelly said Peugeot will launch the most extensive advertising
campaign in Peugeot history to bring the Peugeot 405 to the
attention of the American public, especially the 25- to 49-year-old
male who is making at least $40,000 a year.
   While he declined to say how much the company will spend, Kelly
said the target audience will see the Peugeot 405 an average of 29
times between mid-August and Nov. 1 on cable and network
television, billboards and in magazines.
   The Peugeot's popularity has been mostly on the East Coast but
Kelly said that in the long range, he thinks the front-wheel-drive
405 will find a home with proportionately more Midwestern owners.
   Pascal Henault, Peugeot's U.S. president, said being the lone
French carmaker in the 10 million-unit U.S. market is a plus
because Peugeot can have its product identified without confusion
that accompanies other Europeans battling each other in the United
States.
   ``We are very happy with this lack of confusion,'' he said.
   Yet, Peugeot's problems with the Peugeot 505 _ its consumer
reliability in a recent survey was near the bottom _ and what Kelly
called a disastrous relationship with its dealers, will take time
to heal.
   Henault said special quality control checks of 300 areas of each
car imported to the United States should help Peugeot gain consumer
confidence.
   Kelly said the dealer network is being asked for its opinion on
many aspects of the business and is coming around. Of the 250
Peugeot dealers in the United States, 20 percent of them carry
exclusively Peugeot products.
   In Maplewood, N.J., the nation's largest Peugeot dealer by
volume last year is happy with the new product. One 405 is on the
showroom floor and seven orders have been written based on
customers seeing the single model.
   ``The 405 is bringing us a younger crowd where the front-wheel
drive is certainly important,'' salesman Fernando Valente said.
``We're getting a very, very positive response.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
