<HEAD>Oil Prices Edge Upward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished higher Friday in
dull trading in the absence of any significant news.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, rose 16 cents a barrel to close at $15.73. Other
contract months also increased.
   Futures prices of oil products traded on the exchange also rose.
Contracts for September delivery of wholesale heating oil were up
0.33 cent to finish at 44.48 cents a gallon. September gasoline
climbed 0.31 cent to 47.59 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said Friday's oil futures market was uneventful, with
prices moving in a narrow range.
   ``I would describe the day's market as thin and listless,'' said
John H. O'Connell, an analyst at Refco Inc.
   Traders were not influenced by the coming closeout of the
September crude oil contract on Monday, analysts said. Earlier in
the week, prices on the September contract rose slightly as
investors took last-minute positions in advance of the closeout.
   Analysts said trading in energy futures was generally dull
throughout the week in the absence of fresh news to influence
prices.
</TEXT>
