<DOCNO> AP880819-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SteelPlant-Iraq Bjt   08-19 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Plant-Iraq, Bjt,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USX Plant Sale To Iraq Not A Security Threat, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Government officials say national security does not
appear to be an issue in the proposed sale of steelmaking equipment
from a shuttered USX Corp. plant to the government of Iraq.
   But opponents claim that the sale of the Texas Works plant in
Baytown would threaten peace negotiations between Iraq and Iran and
is a deliberate move by the steelmaker to lessen competition.
   Republican Rep. Jack Fields said Friday he is concerned that USX
would be exporting ``state-of-the-art armorizing technology ...
used for tanks and other military applications'' to a country that
harbors terrorists and last year attacked a U.S. battleship in the
Persian Gulf.
   But a Commerce Department official who spoke on condition of
anonymity said officials believe ``the technology is very old, very
outmoded'' and do not anticipate ``any national security issues to
be involved.''
   Echoing that sentiment, Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col. Keith
Schneider said, ``On the surface, it is not a defense issue.''
   Fields, whose district near Houston includes the plant, has
asked President Reagan, the Justice Department, Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci and Commerce Secretary C. William Verity to
investigate the proposed sale on the grounds that national security
is treatened and that USX may be unlawfully attempting to eliminate
competition.
   ``When Congress returns in September, I think this question
going to be looked at very closely, in terms of national security,
steel supply and that it's anti-competitive,'' Fields said.
   The plant, which once employed as many as 2,000 people, was shut
down two years ago amid labor turmoil and declining demand for
steel. It had produced up to 1.3 million tons a year of
large-diameter pipe used in the United States for oil and natural
gas pipelines.
   The works include electric furnaces for melting scrap, casters
to shape molten steel into slabs and a mill for making slabs into
oil drilling pipe.
   Iraq already has made a $1 million down payment to USX for the
20-year-old steelmaking equipment, which would be dismantled and
then reassembled in Iraq, Field said.
   But two domestic companies are prepared to offer a price
comparable to what Iraq will pay, reported Friday by the New York
Times to be about $100 million, Fields said.
   Among possible domestic purchasers Fields listed were Major
Financial Services Corp. of Tallahassee, Fla., and Birmingham Steel
Corp. of Birmingham, Ala.
   Fields said USX has ``made statements that have led me to
believe they are not concerned about jobs in this country and
really do not want to sell to an American company. They want to
remove capacity, it keeps their prices high.''
   USX spokesman William P. Ryder would not confirm the reported
pricetag on the plant but said USX, formerly US Steel, is
negotiating the sale of the equipment from the closed facility with
the Iraqi minister of industry.
   Ryder would not respond further to Fields' claims.
   ``When you've got domestic purchasers willing to pay as much
value or more, why is USX bent on selling this equipment to Iraq?
They are simply anti-competitive,'' Fields said. ``I am convinced
USX is trying to keep the price of steel slab and steel plate
high.''
   Justice Department spokesman Mark Sheehan said the agency was
taking a preliminary look to see whether an anti-trust
investigation is warranted.
   Fields said he met last week with Iraqi Ambassador Abdul-Amir
Al-Anbari, who requested the meeting a day after Fields blasted the
deal at a Capitol news conference.
   ``Basically, he said he would appreciate me not dragging Iraq
into this controversy. I said, `Like it or not Mr. Ambassador,
you're in this controversy.'''
   Fields said he suggested the ambassador try to persuade Iraq to
back out because ``it would be a tremendous humanitarian gesture in
the interest of jobs'' since 750 people could be employed if the
plant were reopened.
   He said the ambassador was surprised Iraq was buying used
equipment but told him a $1 million down payment had been made.
   ``He kept saying the $1 million had been paid down,'' Fields
said. ``One million is not a lot when it comes to the bad publicity
that your country is going to receive.''
</TEXT>
