<HEAD>Jury Ends 5th Day of Deliberations Without Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury ended its fifth day of
deliberations Friday without reaching a verdict in the
multi-million dollar civil lawsuit brought against Texas oil tycoon
Nelson Bunker Hunt and his two younger brothers.
   U.S. District Judge Morris E. Lasker directed the three-man,
three-woman panel to resume deliberations at 9:30 a.m. Saturday.
   The jury spent much of the day rehearing testimony given in May
by Ismal Fonseca, a silver trader for Minpeco.
   Minpeco, a mineral marketing company owned by the Peruvian
government, is suing the Hunts for $150 million and seeking treble
damages under antitrust and civil racketeering statutes.
   The jury has been deliberating since Monday afternoon. The trial
began in February.
   Minpeco claims the three brothers _ Nelson Bunker Hunt, 62;
William Herbert Hunt, 59, who also has extensive real estate
holdings; and Lamar Hunt, 56, owner of the National Football League
Kansas City Chiefs _ conspired unsuccessfully with several Middle
East businessmen to corner the world silver market.
   The Hunts have denied the allegations.
</TEXT>
