<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2takes   08-19 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0526</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators say the government will
spend $1.3 billion to merge 12 insolvent Texas thrifts in a major
consolidation under the ``Southwest Plan,'' designed to rejuvenate
the troubled industry.
   Private investors will put $48 million into the deal to acquire
the thrifts, with more than 50 branches throughout Texas.
   Officials said Thursday the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance
Corporation, which insures most of the nation's S&Ls, agreed to
provide an immediate $499 million note to fund the new company to
be called American Federal Bank F.S.B. The total cost to the FSLIC
is expected to reach $1.3 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool Corp. says it will acquire a majority
stake in the appliance division of Dutch electronics giant NV
Philips in a $470 million deal that will make Whirlpool the world's
largest appliance concern.
   Whirlpool and Philips said Thursday the world's largest
television producer and Europe's biggest electronics company, will
create a joint venture company that will develop, manufacture and
market major appliances under Philips' brand names.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. has agreed to sell its
pharmaceutical operations to the British firm Fisons for $460
million as part of a two-phase company restructuring.
   Edwin E. Tuttle, chairman and chief executive officer of
Pennwalt, said Thursday the sale of the worldwide operation would
include a special distribution of proceeds to shareholders.
   The Pennwalt operation, based in Rochester, N.Y., makes
prescription drugs plus over-the-counter products such as Desenex
and Allerest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark IV Industries Inc. has sweetened
its tender offer for Armtek Corp. to $44 a share, or about $550
million, a day after Armtek's board rejected its initial offer as
inadequate.
   Bob Jones, an Armtek spokesman, said Thursday the company's
board had no immediate comment on the new offer.
   Armtek's board on Wednesday urged stockholders not to tender
their shares under Mark IV's original $40-a-share tender offer. The
board also directed management to consider measures to increase the
company's stock price.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. has extended the deadline for its
hostile $4.9 billion buyout of Farmers Insurance Group Inc., as
both sides continued negotiating a truce in their lengthy takeover
battle.
   Batus said Thursday it was giving shareholders until midnight
Wednesday to accept its $63-per-share tender offer. The offer had
been set to expire at midnight last Wednesday.
   Batus said 16.3 million of the 68.4 million shares outstanding
were tendered as of Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. has agreed to pay
an apparent-record $35 million to settle an age-discrimination
lawsuit brought by employees who were denied severence pay after
losing their jobs through plant closings.
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission said Thursday
thousands of former Westinghouse employees could receive
substantial payments under the agreement.
   EEOC's negotiators were armed with a federal court ruling that
Westinghouse violated federal law when it denied severence pay to
employees eligible for pensions at the time their jobs were
eliminated.
</TEXT>
