<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed After Central Bank Intervention; Gold Ends Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed Friday in quiet
trading after being tipped lower by central bank intervention that
continued for a third straight day.
   Gold prices weakened in late New York trading after rising in
the Far East and Europe. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a late bid price for gold of $431.25 a troy ounce, down from $432
late Thursday.
   Analysts said the dollar was knocked down by sales by the
Federal Reserve and the West German Bundesbank. The Bundesbank
confirmed its intervention afterward, and traders reported it sold
dollars to buy West German marks when the U.S. currency hit around
1.8950 marks.
   The dollar finished in late New York trading at 1.8965 marks,
down from 1.8980 marks late Thursday.
   ``The intervention just kept a lid on the upside for the
dollar,'' said James Chorek, an analyst for MMS International, an
economic consulting firm in Chicago. ``It didn't really move the
market per se.''
   It was the third consecutive day of intervention by central
banks, which were successful in driving the U.S. currency lower
Thursday after being brushed off on Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.53 Japanese yen to close at 133.40 yen. Later in
London, it also was quoted at 133.40 yen. By the end of trading in
New York, the dollar had recovered to 133.69 yen, up from 133.40
yen late Thursday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7025 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6989 late
Thursday. Later, in New York, a pound was worth $1.6985, a bit
cheaper than $1.6990 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.5955 Swiss francs, up from 1.5945;
6.4190 French francs, down from 6.4470; 1,405.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,406.00; and 1.2300 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2295.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.8925 West German marks, down from 1.8980;
1.5915 Swiss francs, down from 1.5955; 6.4125 French francs, down
from 6.4340; 2.1390 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1438; 1,405.50
Italian lire, up from 1,402.75, and 1.2271 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2298.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $432 troy ounce, up
from Thursday's late bid of $431. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold was
higher, closing at a bid $432.50, up from $431 late Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.93 to close at a bid $434.21.
   Gold for current delivery declined on the New York Commodity
Exchange to $431.70 a troy ounce from $432.30 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London, where the metal was
trading at a late bid price of $6.68 a troy ounce, up from late
Thursday's $6.66.
   On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery fell to $6.657
a troy ounce from $6.675 late Thursday.
</TEXT>
