<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TimberStrike     08-19 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Strike,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Against Boise Cascade Ends After Workers Ratify Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boise Cascade Corp. employees in three
Northwest states ended their 2-month-old strike against the
wood-products company Friday after ratifying a new three-year
contract.
   The pact was approved by a substantial margin of the estimated
2,000 union woodworkers eligible to vote, said Brad Witt, a
spokesman for the Western Council of Industrial Workers in Portland.
   Exact results of the vote taken Thursday were not released.
   The company, based in Boise, Idaho, will begin calling workers
back to their jobs Monday at 15 mills in Oregon, Washington and
Idaho, Witt said.
   The settlement was the second in the regional strike that began
June 6 and eventually spread to eight companies, affecting 9,000
workers. Workers at Willamette Industries Inc. of Portland ratified
a similar contract last week.
   The Boise Cascade pact, like Willamette's, includes a $1,400
signing bonus, a 3 percent raise in the second year and a 4 percent
raise in 1990. The Willamette pact differed in that it included a
fourth year with another 4 percent raise, Witt said.
   Journeyman-level workers at Boise Cascade also will receive an
additional 25-cent an hour raise.
   About 5,900 workers represented by the Western Council and the
International Woodworkers of America-U.S. remained on strike Friday
against six other Northwest wood-products companies with mills and
logging operations in Oregon, Washington, Idaho, Montana and
Northern California.
   Union officials also reported a tentative agreement Friday with
Georgia-Pacific Corp., one of the few large wood-products companies
in the region that was not struck.
   About 1,200 union workers for Georgia-Pacific in Oregon and
Northern California probably will vote on a new four-year pact next
week, said Bill Hubbell, president of the International Woodworkers.
   The other companies still affected by the strike are Simpson
Timber Co., Champion International Corp., DAW Forest Products Inc.,
WI Forest Products Inc., and two smaller Oregon operations:
Lakeview Lumber Co. and the Nicolai door plant operated by Morgan
Products Ltd. in Springfield.
   Progress was reported Friday in negotiations with Simpson Timber
and Champion International. Tentative settlements with those
companies may be announced within a week, Hubbell said.
   Champion International was ``fairly close to an agreement'' with
the unions, Hubbell added.
   Hubbell said the Georgia-Pacific, Simpson Timber and Champion
International contracts also were being negotiated along the lines
of Willamette's contract.
   The unions threatened in July to strike the region's largest
wood-products company, Weyerhaeuser Co. of Tacoma, Wash., but those
plans were postponed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
