<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Polaroid     08-19 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Says It Has More Suitors, Urges Voluntary Retirements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. said Friday it has
received expressions of interest from several corporate suitors
other than Shamrock Holdings Inc. and Forstmann Little & Co., but
the company declined to name the potential bidders.
   Girding for a takeover battle, Polaroid said this week it would
offer early retirement to hundreds more employees, including a
quarter of its top executives. The Cambridge-based film products
firm also warned employees that layoffs may occur if the voluntary
incentives don't work.
   Wall Street analysts said they doubted the cost-cutting would
dissuade potential buyers.
   ``I think the news that they're going to cut another bulk of
their employees out is positive for the company. But will it stop a
takeover? Absolutely not,'' said Alex Henderson of Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   ``The thinking on Wall Street is: The likelihood of further
action on Polaroid stock by potential suitors is extremely high.
... There is too much smoke not to have some fire,'' Henderson said.
   Polaroid's board of directors voted unanimously Tuesday to
reject a hostile offer, valued at about $3 billion, from Shamrock
Holdings Inc., a California investment company controlled by Roy E.
Disney. The company also has rejected a friendly offer from
Forstmann Little, a New York investment firm.
   The warning of potential layoffs came from I. MacAllister Booth,
Polaroid's president and chief executive officer, in a question and
answer session with high-ranking executives on Wednesday.
   Portions of the session were replayed on videotape Thursday
before hundreds of employees at a meeting that the company says was
intended to be closed to the public but was attended by a Boston
Globe reporter.
   ``This company is like a family to me,'' Booth said on the
videotape. ``When my family gets attacked I fight ... and when my
company gets attacked, I fight, too.''
   As an incentive to retire, employees who leave now will be paid
through Nov. 30. ``If that doesn't work,'' Booth said, ``we will
have to rely on layoffs.''
   Referring to an earlier statement in which he had virtually
ruled out layoffs, Booth told the executives, ``I didn't expect to
be in this type of warfare when I made my pledge.''
   Asked about the suitors, Booth said, ``Forstmann Little, along
with lots of others, have talked to us.''
   A company spokesman said Friday that although Polaroid has
received routine letters and expressions of interest from potential
buyers, it is not actively discussing a takeover with anyone.
   The Boston Globe also reported the company increased its target
for the total number of retirements to 1,500.
   ``We do expect to streamline the workforce by a greater number
than what we had originally announced, which was 500 to 800, but I
can't confirm 1,500 or any other figure,'' company spokeswoman
Marcia Phillips said Friday.
   Phillips said Polaroid plans to issue ``a very detailed
statement'' on its restructuring in a few weeks, and ``It would be
premature to say very much before then.''
   Phillips said seven of Polaroid's 27 top executives have elected
to take early retirement.
   In previously announced defensive moves, Polaroid said it would
eliminate 500 to 800 people through voluntary retirements,
repurchase $300 million of its stock and issue 10 million new
shares for an employee stock ownership plan.
   That plan, which gives employees 14 percent control of Polaroid,
has been challenged by Shamrock in a Delaware court. Shamrock
opposes the plan because it would effectively allow employees to
block a takeover by voting with current management.
</TEXT>
