<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 20-21-1st Add, 1st Ld-Writethru,0529</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to update total cost to FSLIC; the first take
stands and will not be retransmitted.</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: tax increase.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In other economic and business developments this past week:
   _The Commerce Department reported the trade deficit swelled to
$12.5 billion in June as imports hit an all-time high. Economists
said the report shows how far the U.S. must still go to solve its
trade problems.
   _The government said housing starts rose a moderate 2.4 percent
in July, but analysts warned rising mortgage rates could slow the
pace of construction.
   _In other reports, the government said factories, mines and
utilities operated at 83.5 percent of capacity and industrial
production shot up 0.8 percent in July.
   _Government regulators announced two separate consolidations in
the troubled Texas savings and loan industry that could cost the
Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation more than $6
billion. The first merged 12 insolvent thrifts, and the second
covered eight troubled institutions, including Sunbelt Savings,
which by itself lost $1.2 billion in the first quarter.
   _A former Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker pleaded guilty to
engaging in a scheme in which he illicitly obtained advance copies
of Business Week and reaped profits from trading stocks mentioned
in the magazine. William Dillon was the first person to be
criminally charged in the insider-trading scandal involving
Business Week.
   _Upjohn Co. won federal approval to market the first hair-growth
formula in the United States. The drug, Rogaine, designed to
stimulate hair growth on men with male-pattern baldness, is
scheduled to hit the market in up to six weeks.
   _Whirlpool Corp. announced a joint venture that will make it the
world's biggest appliance concern. The company said it would
acquire a majority stake in the appliance division of Dutch
electronics giant NV Philips in a $470 million deal.
   _Officials of Farmers Insurance Group Inc. and Batus Inc. began
talks on Batus' proposal for a friendly $4.9 billion buyout. It was
the first time the two sides had met during their 8-month-old
takeover battle, but each company said it was prepared to continue
the fight.
   _Polaroid Corp. rejected a takeover offer from Roy E. Disney's
Shamrock Holdings Inc. valued at roughly $3 billion.
   _An investor group began a $2.69 billion hostile tender offer
for Interco Inc. after the furniture and apparel company rejected
the takeover proposal.
   _Armtek Corp. rejected a buyout bid from Mark IV Industries
Inc., which responded by sweetening its offer Armtek Corp. to $44 a
share, or about $550 million.
   _Westinghouse Electric Corp. agreed to pay an apparent-record
$35 million to settle an age-discrimination lawsuit brought by
employees denied severence pay after losing their jobs through
plant closings.
   _DeLaurentiis Entertainment Group Inc., hit by a string of box
office flops, filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter
11 of federal bankruptcy laws.
   _The Belgian company Donnay SA, once the world's top maker of
tennis rackets, was declared bankrupt after failing to reach a deal
with its creditors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
